n=center | 15\n| [[New Orleans-Metairie-Hammond combined statistical area|New Orleans-Metairie-Hammond]]\n| [[Louisiana|LA]]-[[Mississippi|MS]]\n| align=right | 1,510,162\n|-\n| align=center | 16\n| [[Oklahoma City metropolitan area|Oklahoma City-Shawnee]]\n| [[Oklahoma|OK]]\n| align=right | 1,455,935\n|-\n| align=center | 17\n| [[Greenville-Spartanburg-Anderson, SC Combined Statistical Area|Greenville-Spartanburg-Anderson]]\n| [[South Carolina|SC]]\n| align=right | 1,460,036\n|-\n| align=center | 18\n| [[Memphis metropolitan area|Memphis-Forrest City]]\n| [[Tennessee|TN]]-[[Mississippi|MS]]-[[Arkansas|AR]]\n| align=right | 1,374,190\n|-\n| align=center | 19\n| [[Birmingham-Hoover-Talladega, AL Combined Statistical Area|Birmingham-Hoover-Talladega]]\n| [[Alabama|AL]]\n| align=right | 1,364,062\n|-\n| align=center | 20\n| [[Tulsa-Muskogee-Bartlesville, OK Combined Statistical Area|Tulsa-Muskogee-Bartlesville]]\n| [[Oklahoma|OK]]\n| align=right | 1,160,612\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Black Belt in the American South]]\n* [[Cuisine of the Southern United States]]\n* [[Culture of honor (Southern United States)]]\n* [[Deep South]]\n* [[King Cotton]]\n* [[List of plantations in the United States]]\n* [[Rice Belt]]\n* [[Southern American English]]\n* [[Southern art]]\n* [[Southern hospitality]]\n* [[Southern literature]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |author = Allen, John O. and Clayton E. Jewett |title = Slavery in the South: A State-by-State History |publisher = Greenwood Press |year = 2004 |isbn = 978-0-313-32019-4 }}\n* Ayers, Edward L. ''What Caused the Civil War? Reflections on the South and Southern History'' (2005)\n* {{Cite book |author = Ayers, Edward L. |title = The Promise of the New South: Life after Reconstruction |year = 1993 |publisher = Oxford University Press |isbn = 978-0-19-508548-8 }}\n* {{Cite book |author = Billington, Monroe Lee |title = The Political South in the 20th