{"title_page": "Jean Malo-Renault", "text_new": "\n\n{{France-bio-stub}}\n\n'''Pas de place pour les <big>fran\u00e7ais</big> sur les ordi de USA?!'''\n\n<big>No place for Franchies on US computer</big>\n", "text_old": "''Not to be confused with [[Malo-Renault|Emile Malo-Renault]] or [[:fr:Nori_Malo-Renault|Nori Malo-Renault]].''\n\n{{Infobox Biography|name=Jean Malo-Renault|birth_date=1900 june 09|birth_place=Paris|death_date=1988 August 09|death_place=Rennes|nationality=Fran\u00e7aise|education=Licence d'histoire \u00e0 la Sorbonne, Paris (1924). Dipl\u00f4me de l'\u00e9cole du Louvre, Paris (1926)|occupation=librarian, bibliographer and French author|mother=Nori Malo-Renault|father=Emile Malo-Renault|image=File:Jean Malo-Renault (1900-1988).jpg}}\n\n<br>\n== Biography ==\n'''Jean Malo-Renault''' (9 June 1900 in Paris \u2013 9 August 1988 in Rennes) was a [[France|French]] librarian. Malo-Renault was born in [[Paris]] on 9 June 1900 into a family originating from Saint-Malo. He was the son of the pastellist, engraver and illustrator, [[Malo-Renault|\u00c9mile Malo-Renault]], real name \u00c9mile Auguste Renault, and his wife Honorine, C\u00e9sarine Tian,  herself an printmaker (etching in color), the name of artist: [[:fr:Nori_Malo-Renault|Nori Malo-Renault]].  \n\nJean Malo-Renault obtained his degree in history from the [[Sorbonne]] in 1924, and went on to the [[\u00c9cole du Louvre]], where he wrote a thesis on religious architecture in Brittany in the Middle Ages. \n\n== Career ==\nIn 1928, he was appointed medical science subject librarian at the [[University of Toulouse]]; in 1932, he became librarian at the [[University of Montpellier]] .For a complementary thesis, he studying  ''the letter adorned in the Middle Ages''.  Going on to be chief librarian of the public library of Montpellier in 1935. He returned to Brittany in 1937, and was in charge of [[Rennes University]] and Municipal Libraries until 1954. \n\nJean Malo-Renault collected a copious iconographic documentation towards a thesis on the religious architecture of Brittany. More broadly he was interested in Breton costume and popular arts.\n\nHe is known as the author of a vast retrospective bibliography of Brittany<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://opac.si.leschampslibres.fr/iii/encore/record/C__Rb1289145__SMalo-Renault%20jean__P0%2C3__Orightresult__U__X3?lang=frf&suite=pearl|title=Bibliographie r\u00e9trospective de la Bretagne 1480-1960 par Jean Malo-Renault (1900-1988)}}</ref> for which he analysed printed sources and periodicals from the period 1480 to 1960, which is preserved (''150 000 handwritten records'') in the Biblioth\u00e8que de Rennes M\u00e9ropole<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bibliotheque.leschampslibres.fr/|title=Biblioth\u00e8que des Champs Libres}}</ref> and available on microfiche since 1988.\n\nIn addition to the retrospective Bibliography of Brittany, he publishes ''Les pseudonymes des bretons''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb35029958f|title=Notice bibliographique: Pseudonyme des bretons}}</ref> ''(16th - 20th centuries) in 1987.''\n\nHe died at [[Rennes]] on 9 August 1988, aged 88.\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* \u00ab ''L'art du livre'' \u00bb, Bookstorest Garnier fr\u00e8res, Paris, 1931\n* \u00ab ''Les monuments fran\u00e7ais en p\u00e9ril en Bretagne'' \u00bb, ''Bulletin de l'Art'', supplement of the ''Revue de l'Art'', January 1932, <abbr>p.</abbr> 26  to 28.\n* ''La lettre orn\u00e9e du Moyen \u00c2ge'', 1934. According to the manuscripts of Montpellier\n* ''Le Malouin Jean Le Cudennec, roi de Madagascar'', typed plate, 1948, 5 p.\n* ''Bibliographie r\u00e9trospective de la Bretagne 1480-1960'', 1987.\n* ''Notice sur la Bibliographie R\u00e9trospective de la Bretagne'', 1972.\n* \u00ab ''L'\u00e9glise de Fouesnant'' \u00bb  periodical, ''Fouesnant'', <abbr>n<sup>o</sup></abbr> 4, 1974, <abbr>p.</abbr> 11 to 17<sup>,</sup>\n* \u00ab ''La sculpture gothique en Bretagne : les calvaires'' \u00bb, ''Revue de l'art'', <abbr>n<sup>o</sup></abbr> 319,  September-October 1930, <abbr>p.</abbr> 109 to130. ''Notre-Dame de Trono\u00ebn'', Chapel (Finist\u00e8re).\n* \u00ab ''Notes sur trois cath\u00e9drales bretonnes'' \u00bb Notebook n\u00b0 103 - 26 \u00e8me ann\u00e9e n\u00b0 3, ''Cahiers de l'Iroise'', 1979, <abbr>p.</abbr> 141 to 145.\n* ''Les Pseudonymes des Bretons, <abbr>XVI<sup>e</sup></abbr>\u2009\u2013\u2009<abbr>XX<sup>e</sup></abbr> si\u00e8cles'', 2 volumes, reissue. 1987-1988<sup>,</sup>\n* \u00ab Max Jacob par Max Jacob \u00bb, ''Cahiers de l'Iroise'',<abbr>n<sup>o</sup></abbr> 4, reprinted (tir\u00e9-\u00e0-part), October-December 1987.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malo-Renault, Jean}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:French bibliographers]]\n[[Category:French librarians]]\n[[Category:History of Brittany]]\n\n{{France-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Fran\u00e7ois Malo-Renault", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Pas de place pour les fran\u00e7ais sur les ordi de USA?!  No place for Franchies on US computers)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Malo-Renault"}
{"title_page": "Donna Rice Hughes", "text_new": "{{for|other people with the name Donna Hughes|Donna Hughes (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Donna Rice Hughes\n|image =\n|caption = \n|birth_name = Donna Rice\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1958|1|7}}\n|birth_place = [[Delacroix Island, Louisiana|Delacroix, Louisiana]], U.S.\n|death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1958|01|07}} -->\n|death_place =\n|body_discovered =\n|death_cause =\n|resting_place =\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|residence = [[Vienna, Virginia]], U.S.\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for =\n|alma_mater = [[University of South Carolina]] <small>([[Bachelor of Science|BSc]])</small>\n|employer = [[Enough Is Enough (organization)|Enough Is Enough]]\n|occupation =\n|years_active =\n|home_town =\n|title =\n|salary =\n|networth =\n|height =\n|weight =\n|term =\n|predecessor =\n|successor =\n|party =\n|opponents =\n|boards =\n|religion =\n|spouse = {{marriage|Jack Hughes|1994}}\n|partner =\n|children =\n|parents =\n|relations =\n|callsign =\n|signature =\n|website =\n|footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Donna Rice Hughes''' (born January 7, 1958) is president and [[CEO]] of [[Enough Is Enough (organization)|Enough Is Enough]], an author, speaker and film producer. In her work with Enough is Enough, Hughes has appeared on a variety of outlets as an Internet safety advocate.<ref name=Fighter>{{cite news|title=Once Touched by Notoriety, Donna Rice Is Now in Limelight Fighting Smut|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/27/us/once-touched-by-notoriety-donna-rice-is-now-in-limelight-fightingsmut.html|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=27 November 1995|author=Edmund L. Andrews|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221142354/http://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/27/us/once-touched-by-notoriety-donna-rice-is-now-in-limelight-fightingsmut.html|archive-date=2013-12-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=reinvent/>  She first became known as a key figure in a widely publicized 1987 political scandal that contributed to end the second campaign of former Senator [[Gary Hart]] for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nomination for [[President of the United States|President]].\n\n=={{anchor|Education and Family}}Personal life==\n\nRice grew up in the Irmo area near Columbia, South Carolina. Rice attended the [[University of South Carolina]], where she was a cheerleader and a member of the [[Phi Beta Kappa]] honor society and graduated with a Bachelors of Science degree in biology.<ref name=reinvent>{{cite news|title=Donna Rice Says No Excuses for Net Porn / Gary Hart's ex-paramour has reinvented herself|url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Donna-Rice-Says-No-Excuses-for-Net-Porn-Gary-2979705.php|accessdate=5 July 2012|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=9 November 1998|author=Jon Swartz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141128210031/http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Donna-Rice-Says-No-Excuses-for-Net-Porn-Gary-2979705.php|archive-date=2014-11-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDonna Rice is married to Jack Hughes and has two grown step-children, Sean and Mindy, and three grandchildren.<ref name=\"Internet Safety 101\"/> Rice has openly said she was a victim of [[date rape]] \"on the way to New York City by an older man who was involved with the pageant system, and lost my virginity at that time\". She says the rape was \"the turning point in my life, the catalyst that propelled me further into an unhealthy lifestyle\".<ref name=Bio/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter she graduated from college, she entered the Miss South Carolina World beauty pageant and won.<ref name=\"Alan Richman 1987\">Alan Richman, [http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20096297,00.html Donna Rice: 'The Woman in Question] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129015424/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20096297,00.html |date=2014-11-29 }}, ''People Magazine'' (Vol. 27, No. 20, May 18, 1987)</ref>  She went to [[New York City|New York]] to compete nationally.<ref name=Bio>{{cite news|title=When Enough was Enough: The Story of Donna Rice Hughes|url=http://www.salvomag.com/new/articles/salvo20/the-story-of-donna-rice-hughes.php|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=Salvo Magazine|author=Marcia Segelstein|date=12 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105022111/http://www.salvomag.com/new/articles/salvo20/the-story-of-donna-rice-hughes.php|archive-date=2014-01-05|url-status=live}}</ref>  Rice later moved to [[Miami]], where she worked as a marketing representative for pharmaceutical giant Wyeth Laboratories in South Florida.  She also worked as a television commercial actress and appeared in a 1986 episode of the TV series ''[[Miami Vice]]''<ref name=Bio/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5134602/|title=Donna Rice|accessdate=13 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218091515/http://www.imdb.com/name/nm5134602/|archive-date=2017-02-18|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as an episode of the soap opera ''[[One Life to Live]]'', and played a secretary in the movie ''The Last Plane Out''.<ref name=\"Alan Richman 1987\"/>\n\n===Advocacy===\nSince 1994, when she became communications director and spokesperson for Enough Is Enough, an American secular nonpartisan [[non-profit organization]] whose mission is to make the [[Internet]] safer for families and children, Hughes has been an advocate and speaker on the issue of protecting children online. Hughes became president and CEO of the organization in 2002. The organization has produced an Internet Safety 101SM program with the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] and other partners. She is the executive producer, host and instructor of the ''Internet Safety 101'' DVD series, which ran as a TV series on [[PBS]], garnering Hughes an Emmy nomination in 2012 and the series an Emmy Award in 2013.<ref name=\"Internet Safety 101\">{{cite web|url=http://www.internetsafety101.org/DonnaRiceHughes.htm|title=Donna Rice Hughes, President & CEO, Enough Is Enough|work=InternetSafety101.org: Spokespersons|publisher=Enough Is Enough|access-date=2011-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110426195528/http://www.internetsafety101.org/DonnaRiceHughes.htm|archive-date=2011-04-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ryan|first1=Kiki|title=Donna Rice Hughes: Internet Maven|url=http://www.politico.com/click/stories/1010/donna_rice_hughes_internet_maven.html|website=Politico Click|publisher=Politico|accessdate=23 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924133747/http://www.politico.com/click/stories/1010/donna_rice_hughes_internet_maven.html|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Whathappened>{{cite news|title=Whatever Happened To ... the woman on the senator's lap|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/25/AR2010062503844.html|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=Washington Post|date=4 July 2010|author=Kathleen Hom|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075846/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/25/AR2010062503844.html|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHughes has appeared on ''[[The Today Show]]'' and other national broadcasts including the ''[[Oprah Winfrey Show]]'',<ref>{{Citation|last=Enough Is Enough|title=Oprah1a l|date=2011-05-02|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vlFst3nAHBo&t=225s|accessdate=2017-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028181642/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vlFst3nAHBo&t=225s|archive-date=2017-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref> CNN,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/04/justice/florida-child-pornography/index.html|title=Police: Florida man linked to 1 million child porn videos, images|author=By Chandler Friedman and Greg Botelho|website=CNN|access-date=2017-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907215035/http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/04/justice/florida-child-pornography/index.html|archive-date=2017-09-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Dateline NBC,<ref>{{Citation|last=Enough Is Enough|title=Dateline 4 9 06 l|date=2011-05-02|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vndSHRe88ro|accessdate=2017-09-07}}</ref> and has been interviewed by [[Barbara Walters]] on numerous occasions.<ref>{{Citation|last=Enough Is Enough|title=20/20 5/8/02|date=2011-05-02|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AbWRbzLNvCk&t=2s|accessdate=2017-09-07}}</ref>\n\nHughes has testified before multiple congressional hearings on protecting children online. Hughes and Enough Is Enough supported the [[Communications Decency Act]] (CDA) of 1996, the [[Children's Internet Protection Act]] (CIPA), and the [[Child Online Protection Act]] (COPA).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Janofsky|first1=Michael|title=What Would Dewey Do? Libraries Grapple With Internet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/02/national/02LIBR.html|accessdate=23 September 2014|work=The New York Times|date=2 December 2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708115545/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/02/national/02LIBR.html|archive-date=2014-07-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hudson, Jr.|first1=David L.|title=Donna Rice Hughes makes it her mission to fight cyberporn|url=http://www.firstamendmentcenter.org/donna-rice-hughes-makes-it-her-mission-to-fight-cyberporn|website=firstamendmentcenter.org|publisher=First Amendment News|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> She was appointed by Senator [[Trent Lott]] to serve on the COPA Commission and served as co-chair of the COPA Hearings on filtering/ratings/labeling technologies. She also serves on various Internet safety advisory boards and task forces including the 2006 Virginia Attorney General's Youth Internet Safety Task Force and the 2008 Internet Safety Technical Task Force, formed with [[MySpace]] and the U.S. Attorneys General. Beyond addressing the dangers of Internet pornography, Hughes has also spoken into the issue of privacy online, teen suicide and the impact of [[cyberbullying]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hampson|first1=Rick|last2=Leinwand|first2=Donna|last3=Brophy Marcus|first3=Mary|title=Suicide shows need for civility, privacy online|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2010-09-30-rutgers-suicide-sex-video_N.htm|accessdate=23 September 2014|work=USA Today|date=4 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910143701/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2010-09-30-rutgers-suicide-sex-video_N.htm|archive-date=2014-09-10|url-status=live}}</ref> She has received numerous awards including the National Law Center for Children and Families Annual Appreciation Award, and the \"Protector of Children Award\" and Media Impact Award from the National Abstinence Clearinghouse.<ref name=\"Internet Safety 101\"/> Most recently, Hughes received the 2013 Women in Technology Leadership Award for \"Social Impact.\"<ref name=\"Women in Technology Awards\">{{cite web|title=2013 WIT Leadership Awards Winners Announced|url=http://www.womenintechnology.org/career-development/wit-leadership-awards|website=womenintechnology.org|accessdate=19 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211231117/http://www.womenintechnology.org/career-development/wit-leadership-awards|archivedate=11 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 2014, the group's \"National Porn Free Wi-Fi\" campaign\" encouraged [[McDonald's]] and [[Starbucks]] to add filters to block pornography on their Wi-Fi networks. In 2016, McDonald's implemented their filtered Wi-Fi policy in the majority of their 14,000 stores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/07/15/news/companies/starbucks-mcdonalds-wifi-porn/index.html|title=Starbucks and McDonald's move to block porn from their Wi-Fi networks|last=Isidore|first=Chris|date=2016-07-15|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2016-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220121059/http://money.cnn.com/2016/07/15/news/companies/starbucks-mcdonalds-wifi-porn/index.html|archive-date=2016-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref>  Starbucks followed suit nationally and announced they would implement a global policy as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enough.org/thankstarbucks|title=Enough Is Enough:|website=enough.org|access-date=2016-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161125023249/http://enough.org/thankstarbucks|archive-date=2016-11-25|url-status=live}}</ref> That same year, she won the 2014 Professional Women in Advocacy Excellence In Advocacy Award for \u201cVeteran Practitioner.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womeninadvocacy.com/2014/11/|title=Professional Women in Advocacy Conference Announces the 2014 Excellence in Advocacy Awardees|website=Women In Advocacy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316214846/http://womeninadvocacy.com/2014/11/|archive-date=2018-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEnough Is Enough sponsored a \"Children\u2019s Internet Safety Presidential Pledge\" in 2016, asking presidential candidates to pledge to combat both Internet pornography\u2014including both illegal child pornography and legal adult pornography\u2014if elected president.<ref>Craig Hlavaty, [http://www.timesunion.com/news/nation-world/article/Donald-Trump-says-he-will-crack-down-on-internet-8976017.php Donald Trump says he will crack down on internet porn while in office] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108123038/http://www.timesunion.com/news/nation-world/article/Donald-Trump-says-he-will-crack-down-on-internet-8976017.php |date=2016-11-08 }}, ''Houston Chronicle'' (August 1, 2016).</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enough.org/presidential_pledge|title=Enough Is Enough: Presidential Pledge 2016|website=enough.org|access-date=2016-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220075921/http://enough.org/presidential_pledge|archive-date=2016-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref> The Pledge states that if elected President of the United States of America, [the pledging person] promises to \"uphold the rule of law by aggressively enforcing existing federal laws to prevent the sexual exploitation of children online, including the federal obscenity laws, child pornography laws, sexual predation laws and the sex trafficking laws.\" Republican U.S. presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]] signed the pledge, and Democratic U.S. presidential candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] sent a letter of support.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bedard|first1=Paul|title=Trump signs first ever internet anti-porn pledge, Clinton refuses|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/trump-signs-first-ever-internet-anti-porn-pledge-clinton-refuses/article/2598269|publisher=The Washington Examiner|access-date=2017-05-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420080049/http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/trump-signs-first-ever-internet-anti-porn-pledge-clinton-refuses/article/2598269|archive-date=2017-04-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Children's Internet Safety Presidential Pledge|url=http://enough.org/presidential_pledge#pledge|website=Enough Is Enough|access-date=2016-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220075921/http://enough.org/presidential_pledge#pledge#pledge|archive-date=2016-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring a period of national political divide following the presidential election, Hughes launched Enough Is Enough's \"High Road Campaign\" confronting the global epidemic of hate and cyberbullying by promoting civility, common decency and kindness. The campaign's efforts included Hughes' hour-long [[C-SPAN]] interview<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/standalone/?419568-5/washington-journal-donna-rice-hughes-melania-trumps-focus-cyberbullying&popoutPlayer|title=Washington Journal|date=15 December 2016|work=C-SPAN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116023220/https://www.c-span.org/video/standalone/?419568-5%2Fwashington-journal-donna-rice-hughes-melania-trumps-focus-cyberbullying&popoutPlayer|archive-date=2018-11-16|url-status=live}}</ref> and her op-ed on CNN.com titled \"Cruel attacks on Melania Trump obscure her positive role\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/09/opinions/melania-trump-cyberbully-spokeswoman-opinion-hughes/index.html|title=Cruel attacks on Melania Trump obscure her positive role|last=Rice Hughes|first=Donna|date=10 April 2017|work=CNN.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223180447/http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/09/opinions/melania-trump-cyberbully-spokeswoman-opinion-hughes/index.html|archive-date=2017-12-23|url-status=live}}</ref> in support of [[Melania Trump]]'s cyberbullying platform which had one million readers and 850 comments in the first 24 hours.\n\nHughes has publicly spoken against articles appearing in ''[[Teen Vogue]]'' magazine for promoting sexual activity of any kind to teens,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/teen-vogues-sexual-obscenity-must-be-stopped-to-protect-kids-from-exploitation-activist-says-210560/|title=Teen Vogue's Sexual Obscenity Must Be Stopped to Protect Kids From Exploitation, Activist Says|last=Showalter|first=Brandon|date=19 December 2017|website=The Christian Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117070159/https://www.christianpost.com/news/teen-vogues-sexual-obscenity-must-be-stopped-to-protect-kids-from-exploitation-activist-says-210560/|archive-date=2018-01-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://soundcloud.com/the-eric-metaxas-show/donna-rice-hughes2|title=The Eric Metaxas Show|date=3 August 2017}}</ref> sparking an online petition her organization initiated called \u201cSay No To Teen Vogue\u201d after it published ''Anal Sex: What You Need to Know/How to Do it the Right Way''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.citizengo.org/en-us/72448-say-no-teen-vogue|title=Teen Vogue Must Stop Promoting Sexual Activity to Teens!|date=19 July 2017|website=CitizenGO|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117011942/http://www.citizengo.org/en-us/72448-say-no-teen-vogue|archive-date=2018-01-17|url-status=live}}</ref> The petition has generated more than 29,000 signatures calling to \"boycott Teen Vogue until this article is retracted and these types of articles cease to be published.\"\n\nIn October 2017, Hughes participated as one of 120 world leaders in the area of Internet safety in Rome, Italy for the \"Child Dignity In the Digital World\" World Congress to set the global agenda in the fight against child sexual abuse and exploitation in the digital age.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enough.org/news/drw-world-congress-201710|title=Enough Is Enough: Statement: Donna Rice Hughes, World Congress: Child Dignity in the Digital World, October, 2017|website=enough.org|language=en|access-date=2017-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017201731/http://enough.org/news/drw-world-congress-201710|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2017/10/06/pope-francis-we-must-do-more-to-protect-children-from-online-abuse/|title=Pope Francis: We must do more to protect children from online abuse {{!}} CatholicHerald.co.uk|date=2017-10-06|work=CatholicHerald.co.uk|access-date=2017-10-17|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017202434/http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2017/10/06/pope-francis-we-must-do-more-to-protect-children-from-online-abuse/|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.childdignity2017.org/fileadmin/downloads/press_releases/20170531/Child_Dignity_World_Congress_Declaration_ENG.pdf|title=Declaration of Rome: World Congress: Child Dignity in the Digital World|website=Child Dignity 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018012539/https://www.childdignity2017.org/fileadmin/downloads/press_releases/20170531/Child_Dignity_World_Congress_Declaration_ENG.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-18|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Congress concluded with a papal audience at the [[Vatican City|Vatican]] in which [[Pope Francis]] applauded the Congress in his address for concentrating with great foresight \"on what is probably the most crucial challenge for the future of the human family-the protection of young people's dignity, their healthy development, their joy and their hope.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.childdignity2017.org/fileadmin/downloads/Pope/Child_Dignity_World_Congress_Declaration_Pope_Francis_Speech_IT_FR_ENG_ES.pdf|title=Child Dignity in the Digital World|last=Pope Francis|authorlink=Pope Francis|date=October 6, 2017|website=Child Dignity 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017201648/https://www.childdignity2017.org/fileadmin/downloads/Pope/Child_Dignity_World_Congress_Declaration_Pope_Francis_Speech_IT_FR_ENG_ES.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Hughes joined [[Candy Carson]] and others at the invitation of Homemakers for America for the grand opening of the Museum of the Bible in Washington D.C. to ring the replica of the [[Liberty Bell]], launching a nationwide ringing of bells by churches to calling Americans to come together to \u201cLet Freedom Ring!\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.homemakersforamerica.org/liberty-vine-nov-17.html|title=November Liberty Vine|date=November 2017|website=HomeMakers for America|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317035743/http://www.homemakersforamerica.org/liberty-vine-nov-17.html|archive-date=March 17, 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Hughes joined others from the [[Moms March]] Movement to speak at a press conference organized by the HomeMakers for America, in Washington D.C. to share the Declaration of Mothers reclaiming culture for truth, family, and freedom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=1898653186876044&id=198040786937301|title=Mom's March for America Press Conference|date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> The event also proclaimed March 8 as International Mother's Influence Day<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gatheringfamilies.com/2018/03/08/governor-herbert-signs-declaration-of-international-mothers-influence-day/|title=Governor Herbert Signs Declaration of International Mothers Influence Day|date=March 8, 2018|website=Gathering Families|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316214930/http://gatheringfamilies.com/2018/03/08/governor-herbert-signs-declaration-of-international-mothers-influence-day/|archive-date=2018-03-16|url-status=live|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> and launched \u201cA Day With a Mother.\u201d\n\nUnder her leadership at Enough Is Enough, Hughes rolled out a  Random Posts of Kindness campaign designed to generate a culture of dignity and respect in order to create a safer, more civil Internet. The campaign includes a special initiative, Sweet Tweets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://marklarson.hipcast.com/deluge/marklarson-20180213144442-6284.mp3|title=Random Posts of Kindness|last=Larson|first=Mark|date=March 13, 2018|work=The Mark Larson Show 760 KFMB Radio|location=Start time at :34 Minutes}}</ref>\n\n=== Writing ===\nShe co-wrote the story for the May 2000 season finale episode of ''[[Touched by an Angel]] '' that dealt with online safety.<ref name=\"Internet Safety 101\"/> She authored the book ''Kids Online: Protecting Your Children in Cyberspace'' and website ''ProtectKids.com''.<ref name=KidsOnline>{{cite book|title=Kids Online: Protecting Your Children in Cyberspace|date=August 1998|publisher=Fleming H. Revell|isbn=978-0800756727|pages=[https://archive.org/details/kidsonlineprotec0000hugh/page/269 269]|url=https://archive.org/details/kidsonlineprotec0000hugh/page/269|author=Donna Rice Hughes|access-date=2012-07-04|url-status=live}}</ref> As a platform issue of Enough Is Enough,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internetsafety101.org/cyberbullying|title=Internet Safety 101: CyberBullying 101|website=internetsafety101.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912101959/http://internetsafety101.org/cyberbullying|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref> she has written and spoken regularly on the harms of online bullying, the relational brokenness of young people,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/digital-addiction-sexualized-culture-driving-rising-teen-suicide-rates-fight-is-spiritual-battle-some-say-196417/|title=Digital Addiction, Sexualized Culture Driving Rising Teen Suicide Rates; Fight Is 'Spiritual Battle,' Some Say|website=christianpost.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912055714/http://www.christianpost.com/news/digital-addiction-sexualized-culture-driving-rising-teen-suicide-rates-fight-is-spiritual-battle-some-say-196417/|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref> and the need for a safer, kinder and ethical community on and offline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internetsafety101.org/cyberbullying|title=Internet Safety 101: CyberBullying 101|website=internetsafety101.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912101959/http://internetsafety101.org/cyberbullying|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHughes was an outspoken supporter of Republican presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]] during his 2016 presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2016/11/05/donna-rice-hughes-one-womans-case-for-donald-trump.html|title=Donna Rice Hughes: One woman's case for Donald Trump|first=Donna Rice|last=Hughes|date=5 November 2016|accessdate=13 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211183220/http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2016/11/05/donna-rice-hughes-one-womans-case-for-donald-trump.html|archive-date=2017-02-11|url-status=live}}</ref> She has also written numerous commentaries that have been published in the L.A. Times, USA Today, Politico, CNN, FOX News and other media outlets.\n\nHughes has called upon [[The Walt Disney Company]] to crack down on unauthorized \"Disney porn\" on the Internet.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Donna Rice Hughes|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/disneys-full-frontal-hypocrisy/article/2603753|title=Disney's full-frontal hypocrisy|newspaper=Washington Examiner|date=October 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Professional speaking ===\nShe has spoken on the subject of Internet dangers, safety, and cybersecurity in educational and professional forums including: keynotes at the White House, University of Houston Law School, MIT, Johns Hopkins University, the Media Institute, the Freedom Forum, and the National Press Club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://faithandliberty.org/content/donna-rice-hughes|title=Donna Rice Hughes {{!}} Faith and Liberty Talk Show|website=faithandliberty.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907213344/http://faithandliberty.org/content/donna-rice-hughes|archive-date=2017-09-07|url-status=live}}</ref> She also conducted a seminar at the request of AG John Ashcroft, at the Department of Justice's Federal Prosecutors' Obscenity Symposium.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://aclj.org/us-constitution/steps-in-the-right-direction-to-combat-adult-obscenity-2004|title=Steps in the Right Direction to Combat Adult Obscenity - 2004 {{!}} American Center for Law and Justice|date=2011-06-16|work=American Center for Law and Justice|access-date=2017-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907212826/https://aclj.org/us-constitution/steps-in-the-right-direction-to-combat-adult-obscenity-2004|archive-date=2017-09-07|url-status=live}}</ref>  Hughes told a group of women attending the \"[http://momsmarchusa.com/ Mom's March across America]\" event in September 2017 that  \"A culture of human dignity and mutual respect has made this nation strong even in the most turbulent of times in our history.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://momsmarchusa.com/speaker-lineup/|title=Speaker Lineup \u2013 Mom's March for America|website=momsmarchusa.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017201848/http://momsmarchusa.com/speaker-lineup/|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Involvement in political scandal ==\nRice met former Senator [[Gary Hart]] at a 1986-87 New Year's Eve Party at the Aspen, Colorado home of her then boyfriend, rocker [[Don Henley]].<ref name=\"Alan Richman 1987\"/>  Rice later met Hart in Miami, and stated that she was \"very interested in getting into fund raising\".<ref name=\"Alan Richman 1987\"/>  Soon after meeting Rice, Hart announced that he would run for the nomination as the Democratic candidate for president. Having enjoyed a surprisingly strong campaign in [[1984 United States presidential election|1984]] against the eventual nominee, former [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Walter Mondale]], he was widely perceived as a front-runner for the Democratic nomination in 1988. Shortly thereafter rumors began circulating about his being a \"[[wikt:womanizer|womanizer]]\", leading the candidate to invite the media to observe his public behavior, and to also claim that anybody who did so would \"be very bored.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Maureen Dowd, \"Liberties; Change of Hart\", New York Times, March 22, 1998</ref>  However, he never intended to invite reporters to be \"skulking around in the shadows\" of his home.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nReporters for the ''[[Miami Herald]]'', in a controversial move, stalked Rice on a flight from Miami to Washington, D.C., and then staked-out Hart's townhouse following a phone call from someone trying to sell pictures from the trip.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cramer|first1=Richard Ben|authorlink=Richard Ben Cramer|title=[[What It Takes: The Way to the White House]]|date=1992|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-394-56260-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whatittakeswayt00cram/page/432 432\u2013433]}}</ref> There, the ''Herald'' 's Jim McGee saw Hart and Rice return to Hart's townhouse.<ref name=\"What It Takes\">{{cite book|last1=Cramer|first1=Richard Ben|title=[[What It Takes: The Way to the White House]]|date=1992|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-394-56260-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whatittakeswayt00cram/page/452 452]}}</ref>  The ''Herald'' then reported that Rice had spent the night at Hart's residence,<ref name=\"Newspaper Stakeout Infuriates Hart\">{{cite news|first1=James R.|last1=Dickenson|first2=Paul|last2=Taylor|title=Newspaper Stakeout Infuriates Hart|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/tours/scandal/hart.htm|accessdate=25 August 2015|publisher=Washington Post|date=May 4, 1987|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151026132431/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/tours/scandal/hart.htm|archive-date=2015-10-26|url-status=live}}</ref>  but later conceded that they had not watched the back door to know when she had left.<ref name=\"What It Takes\"/>\n\nTheir story was published on the same day that his quotation appeared in ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]''. The ensuing report sent the media into frenzy.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book|last1=Cramer|first1=Richard Ben|title=[[What It Takes: The Way to the White House]]|date=1992|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-394-56260-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whatittakeswayt00cram/page/455 455]}}</ref>  While Hart contended that the reporters could have no knowledge of exactly when Rice arrived or why she was there,<ref name=Hart>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/05/09/us/courting-danger-the-fall-of-gary-hart.html |title=Courting Danger: The Fall of Gary Hart |author=E.J. Dionne Jr. |date=9 May 1987 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=4 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618004254/http://www.nytimes.com/1987/05/09/us/courting-danger-the-fall-of-gary-hart.html |archive-date=2013-06-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Rice declared the association had been innocent, and denied that she had slept at Hart's house, or that the relationship was sexual.<ref name=\"What It Takes\"/>  Hart also denied the accuracy of the story.<ref name=\"Newspaper Stakeout Infuriates Hart\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cramer|first1=Richard Ben|title=[[What It Takes: The Way to the White House]]|date=1992|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-394-56260-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whatittakeswayt00cram/page/458 458]}}</ref>\n\nHart's popular appeal nevertheless suffered, and polls taken almost immediately afterward found him to be 10 points behind [[Massachusetts]] governor [[Michael Dukakis]] in New Hampshire.<ref name=Time1>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,964394,00.html|title=Stakeouts And Shouted Questions|author=Richard Zoglin|date=18 May 1987|newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=2007-01-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001000025/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,964394,00.html|archive-date=2007-10-01|url-status=live}}</ref>  On May 8, 1987, a week after the story broke, Hart suspended his campaign after the ''Washington Post'' threatened to run a story about a woman Hart had dated while separated from his wife,<ref>David Johnston for the New York Times.  7 June 1987 [https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/07/us/hart-s-link-to-2d-woman-was-found-by-a-private-detective.html Hart's Link to 2d Woman was Found by a Private Detective] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110070458/http://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/07/us/hart-s-link-to-2d-woman-was-found-by-a-private-detective.html |date=2017-11-10 }}</ref> and his wife and daughter became similar subjects of interest for tabloid newspapers.<ref name=2014bai>[[Matt Bai]]. ''All The Truth Is Out: The Week That Politics Went Tabloid.'' Knopf (September 30, 2014) {{ISBN|978-0307273383}}</ref>\n\n===''Monkey Business'' photo===\nOn the cover of its June 2, 1987 edition,<ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-06-01/news/mn-5369_1_gary-hart|title=Hart Photo Said to Cost $25,000|first=United Press|last=International|date=1 June 1987|accessdate=13 January 2017|via=LA Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424162716/http://articles.latimes.com/1987-06-01/news/mn-5369_1_gary-hart|archive-date=2017-04-24|url-status=live}}</ref> the celebrity tabloid ''[[National Enquirer]]'' published a photograph of Rice sitting on Hart's lap. The pair were pictured on a dock during a yacht trip to [[Bimini]] that Hart, Rice and others took before he announced his campaign for President of the United States.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cramer|first1=Richard Ben|title=[[What It Takes: The Way to the White House]]|date=1992|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-394-56260-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whatittakeswayt00cram/page/436 436\u2013437]}}</ref> Hart is wearing a T-shirt bearing the words ''[[Monkey Business (yacht)|Monkey Business]]'', the name of the yacht. The photo was published alongside the headline \"Gary Hart Asked Me to Marry Him\".<ref name=\"LAT\"/> It was published weeks after Hart suspended his campaign, but has been subsequently collectively confused as the reason for Hart's exit.<ref name=2014bai/><ref name=NYTimesBai>{{cite news |last=Bai |first=Matt |date=September 18, 2014 |title=How Gary Hart\u2019s Downfall Forever Changed American Politics |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/21/magazine/how-gary-harts-downfall-forever-changed-american-politics.html |magazine=The New York Times Magazine |access-date=2017-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207204156/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/21/magazine/how-gary-harts-downfall-forever-changed-american-politics.html |archive-date=2017-02-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> There are allegations that the photo was a set up by Republican operative [[Lee Atwater]] to discredit Hart.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/11/was-gary-hart-set-up/570802/|title=Was Gary Hart Set Up?|last=Fallows|first=James|date=2018-10-16|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-10-16|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016142315/https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/11/was-gary-hart-set-up/570802/|archive-date=2018-10-16|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nBoth Rice and Hart have consistently denied that their relationship was sexual and have stated they were just friends.<ref name=\"Alan Richman 1987\"/>\n\nThe scandal is depicted in the 2018 film ''[[The Front Runner (film)|The Front Runner]]'', with Rice played by [[Sara Paxton]].\n===Aftermath===\nThe enormous publicity generated by the Hart scandal resulted in numerous lucrative offers, and while Rice refused most \u2013 including one for an interview with ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine, an ABC movie of the week, book and magazine offers \u2013 she did appear in 1987 as the No Excuses jeans girl in commercials and advertisements for No Excuses jeans.<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/16/us/rice-loses-her-job.html|title=Rice Loses Her Job - Correction Appended|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=16 December 1987|access-date=2018-07-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729112238/https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/16/us/rice-loses-her-job.html|archive-date=2018-07-29|url-status=live}}</ref> She said, \"A month after the scandal broke, I tried to go back to work at the pharmaceutical company after a leave of absence. But because of all the publicity and resulting pressure and stress, I finally resigned.\"<ref name=Salon>{{cite news|url=http://archive.salon.com/business/green/2000/09/12/donna/index.html|title=Donna Rice Hughes says Enough is Enough|author=Amy Debra Feldman|date=September 12, 2000|newspaper=[[Salon Magazine]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209174428/http://archive.salon.com/business/green/2000/09/12/donna/index.html|archivedate=February 9, 2007}}</ref>  A month after the scandal broke, she began reconnecting with her Christian faith and then disappeared from the public eye for seven years.<ref name=20140509beast>{{cite news|last1=Goff|first1=Keli|title=Donna Rice: 'My Heart Really Goes Out to Monica Lewinsky'|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/05/09/donna-rice-my-heart-really-goes-out-to-monica-lewinsky.html|accessdate=19 September 2014|work=The Daily Beast|date=9 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817102722/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/05/09/donna-rice-my-heart-really-goes-out-to-monica-lewinsky.html|archive-date=2014-08-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Rice lived in Los Angeles briefly, then moved to the Washington, D.C. suburbs in Northern Virginia in the early 1990s. There Rice married Jack Hughes, a businessman, in May 1994.<ref name=20140509beast /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/25/AR2010062503844.html|title=Whatever Happened To ... the woman on the senator's lap|first=Kathleen|last=Hom|date=4 July 2010|accessdate=13 January 2017|via=washingtonpost.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128090856/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/25/AR2010062503844.html|archive-date=2017-01-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101216034158/http://enough.org/inside.php?tag=92OZ003W Enough Is Enough: Making the Internet Safer for Children and Families]\n* {{YouTube|Dsr4tYtqLM8|Internet Safety 101: The Perfect Storm}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/21/magazine/how-gary-harts-downfall-forever-changed-american-politics.html How Gary Hart\u2019s Downfall Forever Changed American Politics, The New York Times Magazine, September 18, 2014]\n* [http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/article2185644.html Who blabbed about Gary Hart-Donna Rice affair?, The Miami Herald, September 20, 2014]\n* {{C-SPAN|Donna Hughes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rice, Donna}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:American female models]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anti-pornography activists]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:American nonprofit chief executives]]\n[[Category:University of South Carolina alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|other people with the name Donna Hughes|Donna Hughes (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Donna Rice Hughes\n|image =\n|caption = \n|birth_name = Donna Rice\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1958|1|7}}\n|birth_place = [[Delacroix Island, Louisiana|Delacroix, Louisiana]], U.S.\n|death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1958|01|07}} -->\n|death_place =\n|body_discovered =\n|death_cause =\n|resting_place =\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|residence = [[Vienna, Virginia]], U.S.\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for =\n|alma_mater = [[University of South Carolina]] <small>([[Bachelor of Science|BSc]])</small>\n|employer = [[Enough Is Enough (organization)|Enough Is Enough]]\n|occupation =\n|years_active =\n|home_town =\n|title =\n|salary =\n|networth =\n|height =\n|weight =\n|term =\n|predecessor =\n|successor =\n|party =\n|opponents =\n|boards =\n|religion =\n|spouse = {{marriage|Jack Hughes|1994}}\n|partner =\n|children =\n|parents =\n|relations =\n|callsign =\n|signature =\n|website =\n|footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Donna Rice Hughes''' (born January 7, 1958) is president and [[CEO]] of [[Enough Is Enough (organization)|Enough Is Enough]], an author, speaker and film producer. In her work with Enough is Enough, Hughes has appeared on a variety of outlets as an Internet safety advocate.<ref name=Fighter>{{cite news|title=Once Touched by Notoriety, Donna Rice Is Now in Limelight Fighting Smut|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/27/us/once-touched-by-notoriety-donna-rice-is-now-in-limelight-fightingsmut.html|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=27 November 1995|author=Edmund L. Andrews|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221142354/http://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/27/us/once-touched-by-notoriety-donna-rice-is-now-in-limelight-fightingsmut.html|archive-date=2013-12-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=reinvent/>  She first became known as a key figure in a widely publicized 1987 political scandal that contributed to end the second campaign of former Senator [[Gary Hart]] for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nomination for [[President of the United States|President]].\n\n=={{anchor|Education and Family}}Personal life==\n\nRice grew up in the Irmo area near Columbia, South Carolina. Rice attended the [[University of South Carolina]], where she was a cheerleader and a member of the [[Phi Beta Kappa]] honor society and graduated with a Bachelors of Science degree in biology.<ref name=reinvent>{{cite news|title=Donna Rice Says No Excuses for Net Porn / Gary Hart's ex-paramour has reinvented herself|url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Donna-Rice-Says-No-Excuses-for-Net-Porn-Gary-2979705.php|accessdate=5 July 2012|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=9 November 1998|author=Jon Swartz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141128210031/http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Donna-Rice-Says-No-Excuses-for-Net-Porn-Gary-2979705.php|archive-date=2014-11-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDonna Rice is married to Jack Hughes and has two grown step-children, Sean and Mindy, and three grandchildren.<ref name=\"Internet Safety 101\"/> Rice has openly said she was a victim of [[date rape]] \"on the way to New York City by an older man who was involved with the pageant system, and lost my virginity at that time\". She says the rape was \"the turning point in my life, the catalyst that propelled me further into an unhealthy lifestyle\".<ref name=Bio/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter she graduated from college, she entered the Miss South Carolina World beauty pageant and won.<ref name=\"Alan Richman 1987\">Alan Richman, [http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20096297,00.html Donna Rice: 'The Woman in Question] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129015424/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20096297,00.html |date=2014-11-29 }}, ''People Magazine'' (Vol. 27, No. 20, May 18, 1987)</ref>  She went to [[New York City|New York]] to compete nationally.<ref name=Bio>{{cite news|title=When Enough was Enough: The Story of Donna Rice Hughes|url=http://www.salvomag.com/new/articles/salvo20/the-story-of-donna-rice-hughes.php|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=Salvo Magazine|author=Marcia Segelstein|date=12 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105022111/http://www.salvomag.com/new/articles/salvo20/the-story-of-donna-rice-hughes.php|archive-date=2014-01-05|url-status=live}}</ref>  Rice later moved to [[Miami]], where she worked as a marketing representative for pharmaceutical giant Wyeth Laboratories in South Florida.  She also worked as a television commercial actress and appeared in a 1986 episode of the TV series ''[[Miami Vice]]''<ref name=Bio/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm5134602/|title=Donna Rice|accessdate=13 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218091515/http://www.imdb.com/name/nm5134602/|archive-date=2017-02-18|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as an episode of the soap opera ''[[One Life to Live]]'', and played a secretary in the movie ''The Last Plane Out''.<ref name=\"Alan Richman 1987\"/>\n\n===Advocacy===\nSince 1994, when she became communications director and spokesperson for Enough Is Enough, an American secular nonpartisan [[non-profit organization]] whose mission is to make the [[Internet]] safer for families and children, Hughes has been an advocate and speaker on the issue of protecting children online. Hughes became president and CEO of the organization in 2002. The organization has produced an Internet Safety 101SM program with the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] and other partners. She is the executive producer, host and instructor of the ''Internet Safety 101'' DVD series, which ran as a TV series on [[PBS]], garnering Hughes an Emmy nomination in 2012 and the series an Emmy Award in 2013.<ref name=\"Internet Safety 101\">{{cite web|url=http://www.internetsafety101.org/DonnaRiceHughes.htm|title=Donna Rice Hughes, President & CEO, Enough Is Enough|work=InternetSafety101.org: Spokespersons|publisher=Enough Is Enough|access-date=2011-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110426195528/http://www.internetsafety101.org/DonnaRiceHughes.htm|archive-date=2011-04-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ryan|first1=Kiki|title=Donna Rice Hughes: Internet Maven|url=http://www.politico.com/click/stories/1010/donna_rice_hughes_internet_maven.html|website=Politico Click|publisher=Politico|accessdate=23 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924133747/http://www.politico.com/click/stories/1010/donna_rice_hughes_internet_maven.html|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Whathappened>{{cite news|title=Whatever Happened To ... the woman on the senator's lap|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/25/AR2010062503844.html|accessdate=4 July 2012|newspaper=Washington Post|date=4 July 2010|author=Kathleen Hom|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075846/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/25/AR2010062503844.html|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHughes has appeared on ''[[The Today Show]]'' and other national broadcasts including the ''[[Oprah Winfrey Show]]'',<ref>{{Citation|last=Enough Is Enough|title=Oprah1a l|date=2011-05-02|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vlFst3nAHBo&t=225s|accessdate=2017-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028181642/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vlFst3nAHBo&t=225s|archive-date=2017-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref> CNN,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/04/justice/florida-child-pornography/index.html|title=Police: Florida man linked to 1 million child porn videos, images|author=By Chandler Friedman and Greg Botelho|website=CNN|access-date=2017-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907215035/http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/04/justice/florida-child-pornography/index.html|archive-date=2017-09-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Dateline NBC,<ref>{{Citation|last=Enough Is Enough|title=Dateline 4 9 06 l|date=2011-05-02|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vndSHRe88ro|accessdate=2017-09-07}}</ref> and has been interviewed by [[Barbara Walters]] on numerous occasions.<ref>{{Citation|last=Enough Is Enough|title=20/20 5/8/02|date=2011-05-02|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AbWRbzLNvCk&t=2s|accessdate=2017-09-07}}</ref>\n\nHughes has testified before multiple congressional hearings on protecting children online. Hughes and Enough Is Enough supported the [[Communications Decency Act]] (CDA) of 1996, the [[Children's Internet Protection Act]] (CIPA), and the [[Child Online Protection Act]] (COPA).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Janofsky|first1=Michael|title=What Would Dewey Do? Libraries Grapple With Internet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/02/national/02LIBR.html|accessdate=23 September 2014|work=The New York Times|date=2 December 2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708115545/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/02/national/02LIBR.html|archive-date=2014-07-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hudson, Jr.|first1=David L.|title=Donna Rice Hughes makes it her mission to fight cyberporn|url=http://www.firstamendmentcenter.org/donna-rice-hughes-makes-it-her-mission-to-fight-cyberporn|website=firstamendmentcenter.org|publisher=First Amendment News|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> She was appointed by Senator [[Trent Lott]] to serve on the COPA Commission and served as co-chair of the COPA Hearings on filtering/ratings/labeling technologies. She also serves on various Internet safety advisory boards and task forces including the 2006 Virginia Attorney General's Youth Internet Safety Task Force and the 2008 Internet Safety Technical Task Force, formed with [[MySpace]] and the U.S. Attorneys General. Beyond addressing the dangers of Internet pornography, Hughes has also spoken into the issue of privacy online, teen suicide and the impact of [[cyberbullying]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hampson|first1=Rick|last2=Leinwand|first2=Donna|last3=Brophy Marcus|first3=Mary|title=Suicide shows need for civility, privacy online|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2010-09-30-rutgers-suicide-sex-video_N.htm|accessdate=23 September 2014|work=USA Today|date=4 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910143701/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2010-09-30-rutgers-suicide-sex-video_N.htm|archive-date=2014-09-10|url-status=live}}</ref> She has received numerous awards including the National Law Center for Children and Families Annual Appreciation Award, and the \"Protector of Children Award\" and Media Impact Award from the National Abstinence Clearinghouse.<ref name=\"Internet Safety 101\"/> Most recently, Hughes received the 2013 Women in Technology Leadership Award for \"Social Impact.\"<ref name=\"Women in Technology Awards\">{{cite web|title=2013 WIT Leadership Awards Winners Announced|url=http://www.womenintechnology.org/career-development/wit-leadership-awards|website=womenintechnology.org|accessdate=19 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211231117/http://www.womenintechnology.org/career-development/wit-leadership-awards|archivedate=11 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 2014, the group's \"National Porn Free Wi-Fi\" campaign\" encouraged [[McDonald's]] and [[Starbucks]] to add filters to block pornography on their Wi-Fi networks. In 2016, McDonald's implemented their filtered Wi-Fi policy in the majority of their 14,000 stores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/07/15/news/companies/starbucks-mcdonalds-wifi-porn/index.html|title=Starbucks and McDonald's move to block porn from their Wi-Fi networks|last=Isidore|first=Chris|date=2016-07-15|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2016-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220121059/http://money.cnn.com/2016/07/15/news/companies/starbucks-mcdonalds-wifi-porn/index.html|archive-date=2016-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref>  Starbucks followed suit nationally and announced they would implement a global policy as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enough.org/thankstarbucks|title=Enough Is Enough:|website=enough.org|access-date=2016-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161125023249/http://enough.org/thankstarbucks|archive-date=2016-11-25|url-status=live}}</ref> That same year, she won the 2014 Professional Women in Advocacy Excellence In Advocacy Award for \u201cVeteran Practitioner.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womeninadvocacy.com/2014/11/|title=Professional Women in Advocacy Conference Announces the 2014 Excellence in Advocacy Awardees|website=Women In Advocacy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316214846/http://womeninadvocacy.com/2014/11/|archive-date=2018-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEnough Is Enough sponsored a \"Children\u2019s Internet Safety Presidential Pledge\" in 2016, asking presidential candidates to pledge to combat both Internet pornography\u2014including both illegal child pornography and legal adult pornography\u2014if elected president.<ref>Craig Hlavaty, [http://www.timesunion.com/news/nation-world/article/Donald-Trump-says-he-will-crack-down-on-internet-8976017.php Donald Trump says he will crack down on internet porn while in office] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108123038/http://www.timesunion.com/news/nation-world/article/Donald-Trump-says-he-will-crack-down-on-internet-8976017.php |date=2016-11-08 }}, ''Houston Chronicle'' (August 1, 2016).</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enough.org/presidential_pledge|title=Enough Is Enough: Presidential Pledge 2016|website=enough.org|access-date=2016-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220075921/http://enough.org/presidential_pledge|archive-date=2016-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref> The Pledge states that if elected President of the United States of America, [the pledging person] promises to \"uphold the rule of law by aggressively enforcing existing federal laws to prevent the sexual exploitation of children online, including the federal obscenity laws, child pornography laws, sexual predation laws and the sex trafficking laws.\" Republican U.S. presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]] signed the pledge, and Democratic U.S. presidential candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] sent a letter of support.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bedard|first1=Paul|title=Trump signs first ever internet anti-porn pledge, Clinton refuses|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/trump-signs-first-ever-internet-anti-porn-pledge-clinton-refuses/article/2598269|publisher=The Washington Examiner|access-date=2017-05-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420080049/http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/trump-signs-first-ever-internet-anti-porn-pledge-clinton-refuses/article/2598269|archive-date=2017-04-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Children's Internet Safety Presidential Pledge|url=http://enough.org/presidential_pledge#pledge|website=Enough Is Enough|access-date=2016-12-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220075921/http://enough.org/presidential_pledge#pledge#pledge|archive-date=2016-12-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDuring a period of national political divide following the presidential election, Hughes launched Enough Is Enough's \"High Road Campaign\" confronting the global epidemic of hate and cyberbullying by promoting civility, common decency and kindness. The campaign's efforts included Hughes' hour-long [[C-SPAN]] interview<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/standalone/?419568-5/washington-journal-donna-rice-hughes-melania-trumps-focus-cyberbullying&popoutPlayer|title=Washington Journal|date=15 December 2016|work=C-SPAN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116023220/https://www.c-span.org/video/standalone/?419568-5%2Fwashington-journal-donna-rice-hughes-melania-trumps-focus-cyberbullying&popoutPlayer|archive-date=2018-11-16|url-status=live}}</ref> and her op-ed on CNN.com titled \"Cruel attacks on Melania Trump obscure her positive role\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/09/opinions/melania-trump-cyberbully-spokeswoman-opinion-hughes/index.html|title=Cruel attacks on Melania Trump obscure her positive role|last=Rice Hughes|first=Donna|date=10 April 2017|work=CNN.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223180447/http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/09/opinions/melania-trump-cyberbully-spokeswoman-opinion-hughes/index.html|archive-date=2017-12-23|url-status=live}}</ref> in support of [[Melania Trump]]'s cyberbullying platform which had one million readers and 850 comments in the first 24 hours.\n\nHughes has publicly spoken against articles appearing in ''[[Teen Vogue]]'' magazine for promoting sexual activity of any kind to teens,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.christianpost.com/news/teen-vogues-sexual-obscenity-must-be-stopped-to-protect-kids-from-exploitation-activist-says-210560/|title=Teen Vogue's Sexual Obscenity Must Be Stopped to Protect Kids From Exploitation, Activist Says|last=Showalter|first=Brandon|date=19 December 2017|website=The Christian Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117070159/https://www.christianpost.com/news/teen-vogues-sexual-obscenity-must-be-stopped-to-protect-kids-from-exploitation-activist-says-210560/|archive-date=2018-01-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://soundcloud.com/the-eric-metaxas-show/donna-rice-hughes2|title=The Eric Metaxas Show|date=3 August 2017}}</ref> sparking an online petition her organization initiated called \u201cSay No To Teen Vogue\u201d after it published ''Anal Sex: What You Need to Know/How to Do it the Right Way''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.citizengo.org/en-us/72448-say-no-teen-vogue|title=Teen Vogue Must Stop Promoting Sexual Activity to Teens!|date=19 July 2017|website=CitizenGO|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117011942/http://www.citizengo.org/en-us/72448-say-no-teen-vogue|archive-date=2018-01-17|url-status=live}}</ref> The petition has generated more than 29,000 signatures calling to \"boycott Teen Vogue until this article is retracted and these types of articles cease to be published.\"\n\nIn October 2017, Hughes participated as one of 120 world leaders in the area of Internet safety in Rome, Italy for the \"Child Dignity In the Digital World\" World Congress to set the global agenda in the fight against child sexual abuse and exploitation in the digital age.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enough.org/news/drw-world-congress-201710|title=Enough Is Enough: Statement: Donna Rice Hughes, World Congress: Child Dignity in the Digital World, October, 2017|website=enough.org|language=en|access-date=2017-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017201731/http://enough.org/news/drw-world-congress-201710|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2017/10/06/pope-francis-we-must-do-more-to-protect-children-from-online-abuse/|title=Pope Francis: We must do more to protect children from online abuse {{!}} CatholicHerald.co.uk|date=2017-10-06|work=CatholicHerald.co.uk|access-date=2017-10-17|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017202434/http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2017/10/06/pope-francis-we-must-do-more-to-protect-children-from-online-abuse/|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.childdignity2017.org/fileadmin/downloads/press_releases/20170531/Child_Dignity_World_Congress_Declaration_ENG.pdf|title=Declaration of Rome: World Congress: Child Dignity in the Digital World|website=Child Dignity 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018012539/https://www.childdignity2017.org/fileadmin/downloads/press_releases/20170531/Child_Dignity_World_Congress_Declaration_ENG.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-18|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Congress concluded with a papal audience at the [[Vatican City|Vatican]] in which [[Pope Francis]] applauded the Congress in his address for concentrating with great foresight \"on what is probably the most crucial challenge for the future of the human family-the protection of young people's dignity, their healthy development, their joy and their hope.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.childdignity2017.org/fileadmin/downloads/Pope/Child_Dignity_World_Congress_Declaration_Pope_Francis_Speech_IT_FR_ENG_ES.pdf|title=Child Dignity in the Digital World|last=Pope Francis|authorlink=Pope Francis|date=October 6, 2017|website=Child Dignity 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017201648/https://www.childdignity2017.org/fileadmin/downloads/Pope/Child_Dignity_World_Congress_Declaration_Pope_Francis_Speech_IT_FR_ENG_ES.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Hughes joined [[Candy Carson]] and others at the invitation of Homemakers for America for the grand opening of the Museum of the Bible in Washington D.C. to ring the replica of the [[Liberty Bell]], launching a nationwide ringing of bells by churches to calling Americans to come together to \u201cLet Freedom Ring!\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.homemakersforamerica.org/liberty-vine-nov-17.html|title=November Liberty Vine|date=November 2017|website=HomeMakers for America|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317035743/http://www.homemakersforamerica.org/liberty-vine-nov-17.html|archive-date=March 17, 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Hughes joined others from the [[Moms March]] Movement to speak at a press conference organized by the HomeMakers for America, in Washington D.C. to share the Declaration of Mothers reclaiming culture for truth, family, and freedom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=1898653186876044&id=198040786937301|title=Mom's March for America Press Conference|date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> The event also proclaimed March 8 as International Mother\u2019s Influence Day<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gatheringfamilies.com/2018/03/08/governor-herbert-signs-declaration-of-international-mothers-influence-day/|title=Governor Herbert Signs Declaration of International Mothers Influence Day|date=March 8, 2018|website=Gathering Families|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316214930/http://gatheringfamilies.com/2018/03/08/governor-herbert-signs-declaration-of-international-mothers-influence-day/|archive-date=2018-03-16|url-status=live|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> and launched \u201cA Day With a Mother.\u201d\n\nUnder her leadership at Enough Is Enough, Hughes rolled out a  Random Posts of Kindness campaign designed to generate a culture of dignity and respect in order to create a safer, more civil Internet. The campaign includes a special initiative, Sweet Tweets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://marklarson.hipcast.com/deluge/marklarson-20180213144442-6284.mp3|title=Random Posts of Kindness|last=Larson|first=Mark|date=March 13, 2018|work=The Mark Larson Show 760 KFMB Radio|location=Start time at :34 Minutes}}</ref>\n\n=== Writing ===\nShe co-wrote the story for the May 2000 season finale episode of ''[[Touched by an Angel]] '' that dealt with online safety.<ref name=\"Internet Safety 101\"/> She authored the book ''Kids Online: Protecting Your Children in Cyberspace'' and website ''ProtectKids.com''.<ref name=KidsOnline>{{cite book|title=Kids Online: Protecting Your Children in Cyberspace|date=August 1998|publisher=Fleming H. Revell|isbn=978-0800756727|pages=[https://archive.org/details/kidsonlineprotec0000hugh/page/269 269]|url=https://archive.org/details/kidsonlineprotec0000hugh/page/269|author=Donna Rice Hughes|access-date=2012-07-04|url-status=live}}</ref> As a platform issue of Enough Is Enough,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internetsafety101.org/cyberbullying|title=Internet Safety 101: CyberBullying 101|website=internetsafety101.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912101959/http://internetsafety101.org/cyberbullying|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref> she has written and spoken regularly on the harms of online bullying, the relational brokenness of young people,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/digital-addiction-sexualized-culture-driving-rising-teen-suicide-rates-fight-is-spiritual-battle-some-say-196417/|title=Digital Addiction, Sexualized Culture Driving Rising Teen Suicide Rates; Fight Is 'Spiritual Battle,' Some Say|website=christianpost.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912055714/http://www.christianpost.com/news/digital-addiction-sexualized-culture-driving-rising-teen-suicide-rates-fight-is-spiritual-battle-some-say-196417/|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref> and the need for a safer, kinder and ethical community on and offline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://internetsafety101.org/cyberbullying|title=Internet Safety 101: CyberBullying 101|website=internetsafety101.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912101959/http://internetsafety101.org/cyberbullying|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHughes was an outspoken supporter of Republican presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]] during his 2016 presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2016/11/05/donna-rice-hughes-one-womans-case-for-donald-trump.html|title=Donna Rice Hughes: One woman's case for Donald Trump|first=Donna Rice|last=Hughes|date=5 November 2016|accessdate=13 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211183220/http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2016/11/05/donna-rice-hughes-one-womans-case-for-donald-trump.html|archive-date=2017-02-11|url-status=live}}</ref> She has also written numerous commentaries that have been published in the L.A. Times, USA Today, Politico, CNN, FOX News and other media outlets.\n\nHughes has called upon [[The Walt Disney Company]] to crack down on unauthorized \"Disney porn\" on the Internet.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Donna Rice Hughes|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/disneys-full-frontal-hypocrisy/article/2603753|title=Disney's full-frontal hypocrisy|newspaper=Washington Examiner|date=October 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Professional speaking ===\nShe has spoken on the subject of Internet dangers, safety, and cybersecurity in educational and professional forums including: keynotes at the White House, University of Houston Law School, MIT, Johns Hopkins University, the Media Institute, the Freedom Forum, and the National Press Club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://faithandliberty.org/content/donna-rice-hughes|title=Donna Rice Hughes {{!}} Faith and Liberty Talk Show|website=faithandliberty.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907213344/http://faithandliberty.org/content/donna-rice-hughes|archive-date=2017-09-07|url-status=live}}</ref> She also conducted a seminar at the request of AG John Ashcroft, at the Department of Justice's Federal Prosecutors' Obscenity Symposium.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://aclj.org/us-constitution/steps-in-the-right-direction-to-combat-adult-obscenity-2004|title=Steps in the Right Direction to Combat Adult Obscenity - 2004 {{!}} American Center for Law and Justice|date=2011-06-16|work=American Center for Law and Justice|access-date=2017-09-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907212826/https://aclj.org/us-constitution/steps-in-the-right-direction-to-combat-adult-obscenity-2004|archive-date=2017-09-07|url-status=live}}</ref>  Hughes told a group of women attending the \"[http://momsmarchusa.com/ Mom's March across America]\" event in September 2017 that  \"A culture of human dignity and mutual respect has made this nation strong even in the most turbulent of times in our history.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://momsmarchusa.com/speaker-lineup/|title=Speaker Lineup \u2013 Mom's March for America|website=momsmarchusa.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017201848/http://momsmarchusa.com/speaker-lineup/|archive-date=2017-10-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Involvement in political scandal ==\nRice met former Senator [[Gary Hart]] at a 1986-87 New Year's Eve Party at the Aspen, Colorado home of her then boyfriend, rocker [[Don Henley]].<ref name=\"Alan Richman 1987\"/>  Rice later met Hart in Miami, and stated that she was \"very interested in getting into fund raising\".<ref name=\"Alan Richman 1987\"/>  Soon after meeting Rice, Hart announced that he would run for the nomination as the Democratic candidate for president. Having enjoyed a surprisingly strong campaign in [[1984 United States presidential election|1984]] against the eventual nominee, former [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Walter Mondale]], he was widely perceived as a front-runner for the Democratic nomination in 1988. Shortly thereafter rumors began circulating about his being a \"[[wikt:womanizer|womanizer]]\", leading the candidate to invite the media to observe his public behavior, and to also claim that anybody who did so would \"be very bored.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Maureen Dowd, \"Liberties; Change of Hart\", New York Times, March 22, 1998</ref>  However, he never intended to invite reporters to be \"skulking around in the shadows\" of his home.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nReporters for the ''[[Miami Herald]]'', in a controversial move, stalked Rice on a flight from Miami to Washington, D.C., and then staked-out Hart's townhouse following a phone call from someone trying to sell pictures from the trip.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cramer|first1=Richard Ben|authorlink=Richard Ben Cramer|title=[[What It Takes: The Way to the White House]]|date=1992|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-394-56260-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whatittakeswayt00cram/page/432 432\u2013433]}}</ref> There, the ''Herald'' 's Jim McGee saw Hart and Rice return to Hart's townhouse.<ref name=\"What It Takes\">{{cite book|last1=Cramer|first1=Richard Ben|title=[[What It Takes: The Way to the White House]]|date=1992|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-394-56260-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whatittakeswayt00cram/page/452 452]}}</ref>  The ''Herald'' then reported that Rice had spent the night at Hart's residence,<ref name=\"Newspaper Stakeout Infuriates Hart\">{{cite news|first1=James R.|last1=Dickenson|first2=Paul|last2=Taylor|title=Newspaper Stakeout Infuriates Hart|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/tours/scandal/hart.htm|accessdate=25 August 2015|publisher=Washington Post|date=May 4, 1987|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151026132431/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/tours/scandal/hart.htm|archive-date=2015-10-26|url-status=live}}</ref>  but later conceded that they had not watched the back door to know when she had left.<ref name=\"What It Takes\"/>\n\nTheir story was published on the same day that his quotation appeared in ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]''. The ensuing report sent the media into frenzy.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book|last1=Cramer|first1=Richard Ben|title=[[What It Takes: The Way to the White House]]|date=1992|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-394-56260-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whatittakeswayt00cram/page/455 455]}}</ref>  While Hart contended that the reporters could have no knowledge of exactly when Rice arrived or why she was there,<ref name=Hart>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/05/09/us/courting-danger-the-fall-of-gary-hart.html |title=Courting Danger: The Fall of Gary Hart |author=E.J. Dionne Jr. |date=9 May 1987 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=4 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618004254/http://www.nytimes.com/1987/05/09/us/courting-danger-the-fall-of-gary-hart.html |archive-date=2013-06-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Rice declared the association had been innocent, and denied that she had slept at Hart's house, or that the relationship was sexual.<ref name=\"What It Takes\"/>  Hart also denied the accuracy of the story.<ref name=\"Newspaper Stakeout Infuriates Hart\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cramer|first1=Richard Ben|title=[[What It Takes: The Way to the White House]]|date=1992|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-394-56260-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whatittakeswayt00cram/page/458 458]}}</ref>\n\nHart's popular appeal nevertheless suffered, and polls taken almost immediately afterward found him to be 10 points behind [[Massachusetts]] governor [[Michael Dukakis]] in New Hampshire.<ref name=Time1>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,964394,00.html|title=Stakeouts And Shouted Questions|author=Richard Zoglin|date=18 May 1987|newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=2007-01-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001000025/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,964394,00.html|archive-date=2007-10-01|url-status=live}}</ref>  On May 8, 1987, a week after the story broke, Hart suspended his campaign after the ''Washington Post'' threatened to run a story about a woman Hart had dated while separated from his wife,<ref>David Johnston for the New York Times.  7 June 1987 [https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/07/us/hart-s-link-to-2d-woman-was-found-by-a-private-detective.html Hart's Link to 2d Woman was Found by a Private Detective] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110070458/http://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/07/us/hart-s-link-to-2d-woman-was-found-by-a-private-detective.html |date=2017-11-10 }}</ref> and his wife and daughter became similar subjects of interest for tabloid newspapers.<ref name=2014bai>[[Matt Bai]]. ''All The Truth Is Out: The Week That Politics Went Tabloid.'' Knopf (September 30, 2014) {{ISBN|978-0307273383}}</ref>\n\n===''Monkey Business'' photo===\nOn the cover of its June 2, 1987 edition,<ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-06-01/news/mn-5369_1_gary-hart|title=Hart Photo Said to Cost $25,000|first=United Press|last=International|date=1 June 1987|accessdate=13 January 2017|via=LA Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424162716/http://articles.latimes.com/1987-06-01/news/mn-5369_1_gary-hart|archive-date=2017-04-24|url-status=live}}</ref> the celebrity tabloid ''[[National Enquirer]]'' published a photograph of Rice sitting on Hart's lap. The pair were pictured on a dock during a yacht trip to [[Bimini]] that Hart, Rice and others took before he announced his campaign for President of the United States.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cramer|first1=Richard Ben|title=[[What It Takes: The Way to the White House]]|date=1992|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=0-394-56260-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whatittakeswayt00cram/page/436 436\u2013437]}}</ref> Hart is wearing a T-shirt bearing the words ''[[Monkey Business (yacht)|Monkey Business]]'', the name of the yacht. The photo was published alongside the headline \"Gary Hart Asked Me to Marry Him\".<ref name=\"LAT\"/> It was published weeks after Hart suspended his campaign, but has been subsequently collectively confused as the reason for Hart's exit.<ref name=2014bai/><ref name=NYTimesBai>{{cite news |last=Bai |first=Matt |date=September 18, 2014 |title=How Gary Hart\u2019s Downfall Forever Changed American Politics |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/21/magazine/how-gary-harts-downfall-forever-changed-american-politics.html |magazine=The New York Times Magazine |access-date=2017-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207204156/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/21/magazine/how-gary-harts-downfall-forever-changed-american-politics.html |archive-date=2017-02-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> There are allegations that the photo was a set up by Republican operative [[Lee Atwater]] to discredit Hart.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/11/was-gary-hart-set-up/570802/|title=Was Gary Hart Set Up?|last=Fallows|first=James|date=2018-10-16|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-10-16|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016142315/https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/11/was-gary-hart-set-up/570802/|archive-date=2018-10-16|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nBoth Rice and Hart have consistently denied that their relationship was sexual and have stated they were just friends.<ref name=\"Alan Richman 1987\"/>\n\nThe scandal is depicted in the 2018 film ''[[The Front Runner (film)|The Front Runner]]'', with Rice played by [[Sara Paxton]].\n===Aftermath===\nThe enormous publicity generated by the Hart scandal resulted in numerous lucrative offers, and while Rice refused most \u2013 including one for an interview with ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine, an ABC movie of the week, book and magazine offers \u2013 she did appear in 1987 as the No Excuses jeans girl in commercials and advertisements for No Excuses jeans.<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/16/us/rice-loses-her-job.html|title=Rice Loses Her Job - Correction Appended|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=16 December 1987|access-date=2018-07-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729112238/https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/16/us/rice-loses-her-job.html|archive-date=2018-07-29|url-status=live}}</ref> She said, \"A month after the scandal broke, I tried to go back to work at the pharmaceutical company after a leave of absence. But because of all the publicity and resulting pressure and stress, I finally resigned.\"<ref name=Salon>{{cite news|url=http://archive.salon.com/business/green/2000/09/12/donna/index.html|title=Donna Rice Hughes says Enough is Enough|author=Amy Debra Feldman|date=September 12, 2000|newspaper=[[Salon Magazine]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209174428/http://archive.salon.com/business/green/2000/09/12/donna/index.html|archivedate=February 9, 2007}}</ref>  A month after the scandal broke, she began reconnecting with her Christian faith and then disappeared from the public eye for seven years.<ref name=20140509beast>{{cite news|last1=Goff|first1=Keli|title=Donna Rice: 'My Heart Really Goes Out to Monica Lewinsky'|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/05/09/donna-rice-my-heart-really-goes-out-to-monica-lewinsky.html|accessdate=19 September 2014|work=The Daily Beast|date=9 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817102722/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/05/09/donna-rice-my-heart-really-goes-out-to-monica-lewinsky.html|archive-date=2014-08-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Rice lived in Los Angeles briefly, then moved to the Washington, D.C. suburbs in Northern Virginia in the early 1990s. There Rice married Jack Hughes, a businessman, in May 1994.<ref name=20140509beast /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/25/AR2010062503844.html|title=Whatever Happened To ... the woman on the senator's lap|first=Kathleen|last=Hom|date=4 July 2010|accessdate=13 January 2017|via=washingtonpost.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128090856/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/25/AR2010062503844.html|archive-date=2017-01-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101216034158/http://enough.org/inside.php?tag=92OZ003W Enough Is Enough: Making the Internet Safer for Children and Families]\n* {{YouTube|Dsr4tYtqLM8|Internet Safety 101: The Perfect Storm}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/21/magazine/how-gary-harts-downfall-forever-changed-american-politics.html How Gary Hart\u2019s Downfall Forever Changed American Politics, The New York Times Magazine, September 18, 2014]\n* [http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/article2185644.html Who blabbed about Gary Hart-Donna Rice affair?, The Miami Herald, September 20, 2014]\n* {{C-SPAN|Donna Hughes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rice, Donna}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:American female models]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anti-pornography activists]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:American nonprofit chief executives]]\n[[Category:University of South Carolina alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAdvocacy:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donna_Rice_Hughes"}
{"title_page": "Alain Fuss", "text_new": "{{short description|French Paralympic athlete}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalSport|[[Paralympic athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{FRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 4x400 metre relay T53/54|4x400m - T53/54]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''Alain Fuss''' is a [[Paralympian]] [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[France]] competing mainly in category T54 long distance events.\n\nAlain has competed in two Paralympics.  His first appearance in [[Athens]] in [[2004 Summer Paralympics|2004]] he competed in the T54 5000m, 10000m and marathon without any medal success.  Four years later in [[Beijing]] at the [[2008 Summer Paralympics]] he competed in the T54 1500m, 5000m and 10000m  again without winning a medal but did pick up a medal as part of the bronze medal winning French team in the T53/54 4 \u00d7 400 m.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|alain-fuss|old_id=687621}}\n* {{CPSF profile|alain-fuss}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fuss, Alain}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of France]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2004 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n{{France-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French Paralympic athlete}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalSport|[[Paralympic athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{FRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 4x400 metre relay T53/54|4x400m - T53/54]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''Alain Fuss''' is a [[Paralympian]] [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[France]] competing mainly in category T54 long distance events.\n\nAlain has competed in two Paralympics.  His first appearance in [[Athens]] in [[2004 Summer Paralympics|2004]] he competed in the T54 5000m, 10000m and marathon without any medal success.  Four years later in [[Beijing]] at the [[2008 Summer Paralympics]] he competed in the T54 1500m, 5000m and 10000m  again without winning a medal but did pick up a medal as part of the bronze medal winning French team in the T53/54 4 \u00d7 400 m.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=alain-fuss|old_id=687621}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fuss, Alain}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of France]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2004 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for France]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n\n\n{{France-athletics-bio-stub}}\n{{France-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "add Paralympics link, misc formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alain_Fuss"}
{"title_page": "Gabriela Women's Party", "text_new": "{{Redirect|GABRIELA|other uses|Gabriela (disambiguation){{!}}Gabriela}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| country = the Philippines\n| name = GABRIELA Women's Party\n| logo = GABRIELA Women's Party (logo).svg\n| colorcode = #FE1978\n| leader = [[Liza Maza]]\n| spokesperson = [[Luzviminda Ilagan]]\n| slogan = ''Babae, bata, bayan... tuloy ang laban!'' (Women, children, (and the) nation... the fight continues!)\n| foundation = 1984, 2003 (as partylist)\n| position = [[Left-wing politics|Left-wing]]\n| ideology = [[Socialist feminism]]<br/>[[Marxist feminism]]\n| headquarters = [[Quezon City]]\n| colors = Purple, White\n| international = [[International League of Peoples' Struggle]]\n| national = [[Bagong Alyansang Makabayan|Bayan]]<br/>[[Makabayan]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.gabrielawomensparty.net}}\n| seats1_title = Seats in the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|1|303|hex=#FEB50C}}\n| seats2_title = House of Representatives party-list seats\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|1|58|hex=#FEB50C}}\n}}\nThe '''General Assembly Binding Women for Reforms, Integrity, Equality, Leadership, and Action''' ('''GABRIELA''')<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sobritchea|first=Carolyn I|date=June 30, 2005|title=Representations of Gender Inequality and Women's Issues in Philippine Feminist Discourses|url=|journal=Asian Journal of Women's Studies|volume=11|pages=|via=}}</ref> is a [[leftist]] [[Philippines|Filipino]] organization that advocates for women's issues.\n\nIt is a nationwide network of [[grassroots]] organizations, institutions, and programs that address issues such as [[human rights]], [[poverty]], [[globalization]], [[militarism]], [[violence]], [[rape culture]], [[health]], [[Trafficking in human beings|sex trafficking]], [[censorship]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/press/details.php?pressid=3253 |title=House wants to ban pornographic cartoon |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |date=2009-04-12 |accessdate=2010-10-18}}</ref> and other issues affecting women. There are regional chapters in [[Metro Manila]], [[Cordillera Administrative Region]], and [[Mindanao]]; sub-regional chapters in [[Negros Island|Negros]], [[Panay]] and [[Samar]], and provincial chapters in [[Bicol Region|Bicol]] and [[Cebu]]. GABRIELA is one of many coalitions within the Philippines and their priority includes many women from different sectors and focuses on the education and team building of the women in order to advocate for the many issues they are facing.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Civil Society in Southeast Asia|last=Guan|first=Lee Hock|publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nGABRIELA was founded in April 1984 after 10,000 women marched in [[Metro Manila|Manila]], defying a [[Ferdinand Marcos|Marcos]] decree against demonstrations.<ref name=\"radgeek.com\">{{cite web|url=http://radgeek.com/gt/2006/03/23/reign_of/ |title=Rad Geek People's Daily 2006-03-23 \u2013 Reign of Terror in the Philippines; women's movement criminalized |publisher=Radgeek.com |date=2006-03-23 |accessdate=2010-10-18}}</ref> Amidst a backdrop of widespread social inequality and unrest, GABRIELA aimed to synthesize issues of national liberation, poverty and women's emancipation. The organization's founders pushed for comprehensive social transformation, rather than focusing on individual forms of oppression. This came to be known as [[Postcolonial feminism|Third World feminism]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Feminista: Gender, Race and Class in the Philippines|last=Arnado|first=Mary Janet|publisher=Anvil Publishing|year=2011|isbn=978-971-27-2594-4|location=the Philippines|pages=12|via=}}</ref> \nThe NGO was named in honor of [[Gabriela Silang]], a revolutionary Filipina, who led a revolt against [[Spain]] in the second half of the eighteenth century. The death of her husband was the reason she took over his role as the anti-colonialist leader.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Niu|first=Greta Ai-Yu|date=Summer 1999|title=Wives, widows, and workers: Corazon Aquino, Imelda Marcos, and the Filipina \"other\"|url=|journal=NWSA Journal|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> GABRIELA has been a monumental party for Filipino women because they challenge a lot of the patriarchal views placed on them, alongside resisting foreign influence and [[neocolonialism]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ty|first=Rey|date=July 2018|title=GABRIELA: Contributions of a Third-World Women's Movement to Feminist Theory and Practice|url=|journal=Young Ambassadors of Peace in Asia (YAPA)|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral performance==\nIn 2003, the party-list 'Gabriela Women's Party' was launched by GABRIELA.<ref name=\"radgeek.com\" /> \nIn the [[2004 Philippine general election|2004 elections]] for the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|House of Representatives]] the party-list got 464,586 votes (3.6518% of the nationwide vote and one seat; [[Liza Maza]])<ref>[http://www.comelec.gov.ph/results/2004partylist.html Comelec] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070427161552/http://www.comelec.gov.ph/results/2004partylist.html |date=April 27, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/members/search.php?id=maza |title=Liza Maza |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |date= |accessdate=2010-10-18}}</ref> In the 14 May 2007 [[2007 Philippine general election|election]], the party won 2 seats in the nationwide party-list vote. The Gabriela Women's Party was the only women's party that was able to obtain a second term in Congress.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|title=The Internet and Mobile Technologies in Election Campaigns: The GABRIELA Womens Party During the 2007 Philippine Elections|journal=Journal of Information Technology & Politics|volume=6|issue=3\u20134|pages=326\u2013339|doi=10.1080/19331680903047420|year = 2009|last1 = Karan|first1 = Kavita|last2=Gimeno|first2=Jacques D. M.|last3=Tandoc|first3=Edson}}</ref> In the [[2007 Philippine general election|2007 elections]], the GWP (Gabriela Women's Party) made a lot of achievements when it came to representation in the election. It is important to note that many of the women who have been elected from the Gabriela Women's Party, are women who have survived abuse in their life.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chew|first=Huibin A|date=2018|title=Bringing the Revolution Home: Filipino Urban Poor Women, \"Neoliberal Imperial Feminisms,\" and a Social Movements Approach to Domestic Abuse|url=|journal=Women's Studies Journal|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n{|class=wikitable style=\"text-align:right\"\n|-\n!Election !! Votes !! % !! Seats\n|-\n|align=left|[[2004 Philippine general election|2004]] || 464,586 || 3.65% || 1\n|-\n|align=left|[[2007 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2007]] || 621,171 || 3.89% || 2\n|-\n|align=left|[[2010 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2010]] || 1,001,421 || 3.31% || 2\n|-\n|align=left|[[2013 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2013]] || 713,492 || 2.60% || 2\n|-\n|align=left|[[2016 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2016]] || 1,367,795 || 4.22% || 2\n|-\n|align=left|[[2019 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2019]] || 445,696 || 1.61% || 1\n|}\n\n=== Representatives to Congress ===\n*[[13th Congress of the Philippines|13th Congress]] (2004&ndash;2007) - [[Liza Maza]]\n*[[14th Congress of the Philippines|14th Congress]] (2007&ndash;2010) - [[Luzviminda Ilagan]], Liza Maza\n*[[15th Congress of the Philippines|15th Congress]] (2010&ndash;2013) - Luzviminda Ilagan, [[Emerenciana de Jesus]]\n*[[16th Congress of the Philippines|16th Congress]] (2013&ndash;2016) - Luzviminda Ilagan, Emerenciana de Jesus\n*[[17th Congress of the Philippines|17th Congress]] (2016&ndash;2019) - Emerenciana de Jesus, Arlene Brosas\n*[[18th Congress of the Philippines|18th Congress]] (2019&ndash;present) - Arlene Brosas\n\n== One Billion Rising (OBR) Task Force Philippines<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onebillionrising.org/41139/gabriela-national-alliance-of-filipino-women-southeast-asia-philippines-indonesia-thailand-vietnam-singapore-malaysia-cambodia-laos/|title=GABRIELA - NATIONAL ALLIANCE OF FILIPINO WOMEN Southeast Asia - Philippines, Indonesia, Thailand, Vietnam, Singapore, Malaysia, Cambodia, Laos|date=2013-07-16|website=One Billion Rising Revolution|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> ==\n[[One Billion Rising]] (OBR) is a global campaign founded to end rape and sexual violence against women.<ref>{{Citation|title=One Billion Rising|date=2019-09-23|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=One_Billion_Rising&oldid=917329419|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nSince 2013, GABRIELA have led the One Billion Rising in the Philippined and abroad (only where the chapters are situated). Now they are coordinating the campaign in the Southeast Asian region, they are part of a huge group who make up the OBR Task Force Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onebillionrising.org/41139/gabriela-national-alliance-of-filipino-women-southeast-asia-philippines-indonesia-thailand-vietnam-singapore-malaysia-cambodia-laos/|title=GABRIELA - NATIONAL ALLIANCE OF FILIPINO WOMEN Southeast Asia - Philippines, Indonesia, Thailand, Vietnam, Singapore, Malaysia, Cambodia, Laos|date=2013-07-16|website=One Billion Rising Revolution|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nOBR Task Force Philippines Members:\n\n* Gabriela\n* [[Gabriela Women's Party|Gabriela Women's Party]]\n* Gabriela Youth\n* [[Kilusang Mayo Uno]] (workers)\n* [[Alliance of Concerned Teachers]]\n* Ecumenical Women's Forum\n* Salinlahi Alliance for Children's Concerns\n* Association for the Rights of Children in Southeast Asia\n* Amihan Federation of Peasant Women\n* Kadamay (Urban Poor women)\n* Innabuyog Gabriela (Indigenous women)\n* [[Kabataan Partylist]]\n* Migrante\n\n<br />\n== Human Trafficking ==\nIn the Philippines, GABRIELA is actively involved in awareness campaigns to prevent the trafficking of women and girls from the Philippines. Its strategies consist of seminars and information dissemination to NGOs and government agencies and awareness campaigns at the community level.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.humantrafficking.org/combat_trafficking/prevention |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060426014613/http://www.humantrafficking.org/combat_trafficking/prevention |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-04-26 |title=Combat Trafficking: Prevention |publisher=HumanTrafficking.org |date= |access-date=2010-10-18 |df= }}</ref> GABRIELA Philippines reports that a Filipina woman sells for between $3000 and $5000 in the international sex trade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unpac.ca/economy/g_migration.html |title=Women & The Economy - Globalization & Migration |publisher=Unpac.ca |date= |access-date=2010-10-18 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514045035/http://www.unpac.ca/economy/g_migration.html |archive-date=2011-05-14 |df= }}</ref> The Gabriela Women's Party launched a campaign against the sex trafficking issue of Filipino women and children which they called the Purple Rose Campaign.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=NGO Responses to Trafficking in Women|journal = Gender & Development|volume = 10|pages = 60\u201368|last=Tzvetkova|first=Marina|doi=10.1080/13552070215893|year = 2002}}</ref> Not only do they have campaigns such as the Purple Rose Campaign, but GABRIELA is actively involved in Vow to Fight (VAW) which is the Vow to [[Violence against women in the Philippines|Fight Against Violence on Women]] and Free Our Sisters/Free Ourselves campaign.<ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Beins|first=Agatha|title=Free our sisters, free ourselves: locating U.S. feminism through feminist periodicals, 1970-1983|date=2011|publisher=Rutgers University - Graduate School - New Brunswick|url=https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/33573/|doi=10.7282/t3s75fpw}}</ref>\n\n==Gabriela USA and Gabriela Hong Kong==\n{{Multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{Expand section|date=August 2018}}\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2018}}\n}}\nGABRIELA USA and GABRIELA Hong Kong are the overseas chapters of the Philippine-based organization, extending the Filipino women's mass movement to the United States and Hong Kong.\n\nThe Gabriela Women's Party is part of the a grassroots organization. This has led to many more GABRIELA's in other countries, such as the United States, the Netherlands, Japan, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Italy and Germany.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Violeta Marasigan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://gabrielaph.com/ GABRIELA Alliance official website]\n*[http://www.gabrielawomensparty.net Gabriela Women's Party official website]\n*[http://gabrielausa.org/ GABRIELA USA]\n{{Bagong Alyansang Makabayan}}\n{{Feminism}}\n{{Philippine political parties}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:GABRIELA}}\n[[Category:Democratic socialist parties in Asia]]\n[[Category:Feminist organizations in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Feminist parties in Asia]]\n[[Category:Left-wing politics in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Party-lists represented in the House of Representatives of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Socialist feminist organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations that combat human trafficking]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Socialist parties in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Human trafficking in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Anti-pornography movements]]\n[[Category:Anti-pornography feminism]]\n[[Category:National Democracy Movement (Philippines)]]\n[[Category:International League of Peoples' Struggle]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|GABRIELA|other uses|Gabriela (disambiguation){{!}}Gabriela}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| country = the Philippines\n| name = GABRIELA Women's Party\n| logo = GABRIELA Women's Party (logo).svg\n| colorcode = #FE1978\n| leader = [[Liza Maza]]\n| spokesperson = [[Luzviminda Ilagan]]\n| slogan = ''Babae, bata, bayan... tuloy ang laban!'' (Women, children, (and the) nation... the fight continues!)\n| foundation = 1984, 2003 (as partylist)\n| position = [[Left-wing politics|Left-wing]]\n| ideology = [[Socialist feminism]]<br/>[[Marxist feminism]]\n| headquarters = [[Quezon City]]\n| colors = Purple, White\n| international = [[International League of Peoples' Struggle]]\n| national = [[Bagong Alyansang Makabayan|Bayan]]<br/>[[Makabayan]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.gabrielawomensparty.net}}\n| seats1_title = Seats in the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|1|303|hex=#FEB50C}}\n| seats2_title = House of Representatives party-list seats\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|1|58|hex=#FEB50C}}\n}}\nThe '''General Assembly Binding Women for Reforms, Integrity, Equality, Leadership, and Action''' ('''GABRIELA''')<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sobritchea|first=Carolyn I|date=June 30, 2005|title=Representations of Gender Inequality and Women's Issues in Philippine Feminist Discourses|url=|journal=Asian Journal of Women's Studies|volume=11|pages=|via=}}</ref> is a [[leftist]] [[Philippines|Filipino]] organization that advocates for women's issues.\n\nIt is a nationwide network of [[grassroots]] organizations, institutions, and programs that address issues such as [[human rights]], [[poverty]], [[globalization]], [[militarism]], [[violence]], [[rape culture]], [[health]], [[Trafficking in human beings|sex trafficking]], [[censorship]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/press/details.php?pressid=3253 |title=House wants to ban pornographic cartoon |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |date=2009-04-12 |accessdate=2010-10-18}}</ref> and other issues affecting women. There are regional chapters in [[Metro Manila]], [[Cordillera Administrative Region]], and [[Mindanao]]; sub-regional chapters in [[Negros Island|Negros]], [[Panay]] and [[Samar]], and provincial chapters in [[Bicol Region|Bicol]] and [[Cebu]]. GABRIELA is one of many coalitions within the Philippines and their priority includes many women from different sectors and focuses on the education and team building of the women in order to advocate for the many issues they are facing.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Civil Society in Southeast Asia|last=Guan|first=Lee Hock|publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nGABRIELA was founded in April 1984 after 10,000 women marched in [[Metro Manila|Manila]], defying a [[Ferdinand Marcos|Marcos]] decree against demonstrations.<ref name=\"radgeek.com\">{{cite web|url=http://radgeek.com/gt/2006/03/23/reign_of/ |title=Rad Geek People's Daily 2006-03-23 \u2013 Reign of Terror in the Philippines; women's movement criminalized |publisher=Radgeek.com |date=2006-03-23 |accessdate=2010-10-18}}</ref> Amidst a backdrop of widespread social inequality and unrest, GABRIELA aimed to synthesize issues of national liberation, poverty and women's emancipation. The organization's founders pushed for comprehensive social transformation, rather than focusing on individual forms of oppression. This came to be known as [[Postcolonial feminism|Third World feminism]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Feminista: Gender, Race and Class in the Philippines|last=Arnado|first=Mary Janet|publisher=Anvil Publishing|year=2011|isbn=978-971-27-2594-4|location=the Philippines|pages=12|via=}}</ref> \nThe NGO was named in honor of [[Gabriela Silang]], a revolutionary Filipina, who led a revolt against [[Spain]] in the second half of the eighteenth century. The death of her husband was the reason she took over his role as the anti-colonialist leader.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Niu|first=Greta Ai-Yu|date=Summer 1999|title=Wives, widows, and workers: Corazon Aquino, Imelda Marcos, and the Filipina \"other\"|url=|journal=NWSA Journal|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> GABRIELA has been a monumental party for Filipino women because they challenge a lot of the patriarchal views placed on them, alongside resisting foreign influence and [[neocolonialism]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ty|first=Rey|date=July 2018|title=GABRIELA: Contributions of a Third-World Women's Movement to Feminist Theory and Practice|url=|journal=Young Ambassadors of Peace in Asia (YAPA)|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral performance==\nIn 2003, the party-list 'Gabriela Women's Party' was launched by GABRIELA.<ref name=\"radgeek.com\" /> \nIn the [[2004 Philippine general election|2004 elections]] for the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|House of Representatives]] the party-list got 464,586 votes (3.6518% of the nationwide vote and one seat; [[Liza Maza]])<ref>[http://www.comelec.gov.ph/results/2004partylist.html Comelec] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070427161552/http://www.comelec.gov.ph/results/2004partylist.html |date=April 27, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.congress.gov.ph/members/search.php?id=maza |title=Liza Maza |publisher=Congress.gov.ph |date= |accessdate=2010-10-18}}</ref> In the 14 May 2007 [[2007 Philippine general election|election]], the party won 2 seats in the nationwide party-list vote. The Gabriela Women\u2019s Party was the only women\u2019s party that was able to obtain a second term in Congress.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|title=The Internet and Mobile Technologies in Election Campaigns: The GABRIELA Womens Party During the 2007 Philippine Elections|journal=Journal of Information Technology & Politics|volume=6|issue=3\u20134|pages=326\u2013339|doi=10.1080/19331680903047420|year = 2009|last1 = Karan|first1 = Kavita|last2=Gimeno|first2=Jacques D. M.|last3=Tandoc|first3=Edson}}</ref> In the [[2007 Philippine general election|2007 elections]], the GWP (Gabriela Women\u2019s Party) made a lot of achievements when it came to representation in the election. It is important to note that many of the women who have been elected from the Gabriela Women's Party, are women who have survived abuse in their life.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chew|first=Huibin A|date=2018|title=Bringing the Revolution Home: Filipino Urban Poor Women, \"Neoliberal Imperial Feminisms,\" and a Social Movements Approach to Domestic Abuse|url=|journal=Women's Studies Journal|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n{|class=wikitable style=\"text-align:right\"\n|-\n!Election !! Votes !! % !! Seats\n|-\n|align=left|[[2004 Philippine general election|2004]] || 464,586 || 3.65% || 1\n|-\n|align=left|[[2007 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2007]] || 621,171 || 3.89% || 2\n|-\n|align=left|[[2010 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2010]] || 1,001,421 || 3.31% || 2\n|-\n|align=left|[[2013 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2013]] || 713,492 || 2.60% || 2\n|-\n|align=left|[[2016 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2016]] || 1,367,795 || 4.22% || 2\n|-\n|align=left|[[2019 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2019]] || 445,696 || 1.61% || 1\n|}\n\n=== Representatives to Congress ===\n*[[13th Congress of the Philippines|13th Congress]] (2004&ndash;2007) - [[Liza Maza]]\n*[[14th Congress of the Philippines|14th Congress]] (2007&ndash;2010) - [[Luzviminda Ilagan]], Liza Maza\n*[[15th Congress of the Philippines|15th Congress]] (2010&ndash;2013) - Luzviminda Ilagan, [[Emerenciana de Jesus]]\n*[[16th Congress of the Philippines|16th Congress]] (2013&ndash;2016) - Luzviminda Ilagan, Emerenciana de Jesus\n*[[17th Congress of the Philippines|17th Congress]] (2016&ndash;2019) - Emerenciana de Jesus, Arlene Brosas\n*[[18th Congress of the Philippines|18th Congress]] (2019&ndash;present) - Arlene Brosas\n\n== One Billion Rising (OBR) Task Force Philippines<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onebillionrising.org/41139/gabriela-national-alliance-of-filipino-women-southeast-asia-philippines-indonesia-thailand-vietnam-singapore-malaysia-cambodia-laos/|title=GABRIELA - NATIONAL ALLIANCE OF FILIPINO WOMEN Southeast Asia - Philippines, Indonesia, Thailand, Vietnam, Singapore, Malaysia, Cambodia, Laos|date=2013-07-16|website=One Billion Rising Revolution|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> ==\n[[One Billion Rising]] (OBR) is a global campaign founded to end rape and sexual violence against women.<ref>{{Citation|title=One Billion Rising|date=2019-09-23|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=One_Billion_Rising&oldid=917329419|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nSince 2013, GABRIELA have led the One Billion Rising in the Philippined and abroad (only where the chapters are situated). Now they are coordinating the campaign in the Southeast Asian region, they are part of a huge group who make up the OBR Task Force Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onebillionrising.org/41139/gabriela-national-alliance-of-filipino-women-southeast-asia-philippines-indonesia-thailand-vietnam-singapore-malaysia-cambodia-laos/|title=GABRIELA - NATIONAL ALLIANCE OF FILIPINO WOMEN Southeast Asia - Philippines, Indonesia, Thailand, Vietnam, Singapore, Malaysia, Cambodia, Laos|date=2013-07-16|website=One Billion Rising Revolution|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nOBR Task Force Philippines Members:\n\n* Gabriela\n* [[Gabriela Women's Party|Gabriela Women\u2019s Party]]\n* Gabriela Youth\n* [[Kilusang Mayo Uno]] (workers)\n* [[Alliance of Concerned Teachers]]\n* Ecumenical Women\u2019s Forum\n* Salinlahi Alliance for Children\u2019s Concerns\n* Association for the Rights of Children in Southeast Asia\n* Amihan Federation of Peasant Women\n* Kadamay (Urban Poor women)\n* Innabuyog Gabriela (Indigenous women)\n* [[Kabataan Partylist]]\n* Migrante\n\n<br />\n== Human Trafficking ==\nIn the Philippines, GABRIELA is actively involved in awareness campaigns to prevent the trafficking of women and girls from the Philippines. Its strategies consist of seminars and information dissemination to NGOs and government agencies and awareness campaigns at the community level.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.humantrafficking.org/combat_trafficking/prevention |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060426014613/http://www.humantrafficking.org/combat_trafficking/prevention |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-04-26 |title=Combat Trafficking: Prevention |publisher=HumanTrafficking.org |date= |access-date=2010-10-18 |df= }}</ref> GABRIELA Philippines reports that a Filipina woman sells for between $3000 and $5000 in the international sex trade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unpac.ca/economy/g_migration.html |title=Women & The Economy - Globalization & Migration |publisher=Unpac.ca |date= |access-date=2010-10-18 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514045035/http://www.unpac.ca/economy/g_migration.html |archive-date=2011-05-14 |df= }}</ref> The Gabriela Women's Party launched a campaign against the sex trafficking issue of Filipino women and children which they called the Purple Rose Campaign.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=NGO Responses to Trafficking in Women|journal = Gender & Development|volume = 10|pages = 60\u201368|last=Tzvetkova|first=Marina|doi=10.1080/13552070215893|year = 2002}}</ref> Not only do they have campaigns such as the Purple Rose Campaign, but GABRIELA is actively involved in Vow to Fight (VAW) which is the Vow to [[Violence against women in the Philippines|Fight Against Violence on Women]] and Free Our Sisters/Free Ourselves campaign.<ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Beins|first=Agatha|title=Free our sisters, free ourselves: locating U.S. feminism through feminist periodicals, 1970-1983|date=2011|publisher=Rutgers University - Graduate School - New Brunswick|url=https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/33573/|doi=10.7282/t3s75fpw}}</ref>\n\n==Gabriela USA and Gabriela Hong Kong==\n{{Multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{Expand section|date=August 2018}}\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2018}}\n}}\nGABRIELA USA and GABRIELA Hong Kong are the overseas chapters of the Philippine-based organization, extending the Filipino women's mass movement to the United States and Hong Kong.\n\nThe Gabriela Women's Party is part of the a grassroots organization. This has led to many more GABRIELA's in other countries, such as the United States, the Netherlands, Japan, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Italy and Germany.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Violeta Marasigan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://gabrielaph.com/ GABRIELA Alliance official website]\n*[http://www.gabrielawomensparty.net Gabriela Women's Party official website]\n*[http://gabrielausa.org/ GABRIELA USA]\n{{Bagong Alyansang Makabayan}}\n{{Feminism}}\n{{Philippine political parties}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:GABRIELA}}\n[[Category:Democratic socialist parties in Asia]]\n[[Category:Feminist organizations in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Feminist parties in Asia]]\n[[Category:Left-wing politics in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Party-lists represented in the House of Representatives of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Socialist feminist organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations that combat human trafficking]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Socialist parties in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Human trafficking in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Anti-pornography movements]]\n[[Category:Anti-pornography feminism]]\n[[Category:National Democracy Movement (Philippines)]]\n[[Category:International League of Peoples' Struggle]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (6)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabriela_Women%27s_Party"}
{"title_page": "Opposition to pornography", "text_new": "{{expert needed|Politics|ex2=Sexology and sexuality|ex3=Conservatism|ex4=Libertarianism|date=December 2012}}\n[[File:Anti-pornography protest on Oxford Street in 2008.jpg|thumb|Anti-pornography protest on [[Oxford Street]], London]]\n\nReasons for '''opposition to pornography''' include [[Religious views on pornography|religious objections]], [[Feminist views of pornography|feminist concerns]], and claims of [[Effects of pornography|harmful effects]], such as [[pornography addiction]]. Anti-pornography movements have allied disparate social activists in opposition to pornography, from [[Social conservatism|social conservatives]] to [[harm reduction]] advocates.\n\nThe definition of \"[[pornography]]\" varies between countries and movements, and many make distinctions between pornography, which they oppose, and [[erotica]], which they consider acceptable. Sometimes opposition will deem certain forms of pornography more or less harmful, while others draw no such distinctions.\n\nA 2018 [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] survey reported that 43% of U.S. adults believe that it is \"morally acceptable,\" a 7% increase from 2017.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.gallup.com/poll/235280/americans-say-pornography-morally-acceptable.aspx|title=More Americans Say Pornography Is Morally Acceptable|last=Inc|first=Gallup|date=2018-06-05|website=Gallup.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Historically, from 1975\u20132012, the gender gap in pornography opposition has widened, with women remaining more opposed to pornography than men and men's opposition has declined faster.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lykke|first=Lucia|last2=Cohen|first2=Philip|year=2015|title=The Widening Gender Gap in Opposition to Pornography, 1975\u20132012|doi=10.1177/2329496515604170|journal=Social Currents|volume=2|issue=4|pages=307\u2013323|url=http://osf.io/4dymx/}}</ref>\n\n==Religious views==\n{{Main article|Religious views on pornography}}\n\nMost world religions have positions in opposition to pornography from a variety of rationales,<ref>{{cite web|last=Slick|first=Matt|title=What does the Bible say about pornography? Is it wrong?|url=http://carm.org/pornography|accessdate=6 May 2013|date=2008-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Freeman|first=Tzvi|title=What's Wrong With Pornography?|url=http://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/658901/jewish/Whats-Wrong-with-Pornography.htm|accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mujahid|first=Abdul Malik|title=Islam on Pornography: A Definite No-No|url=http://www.soundvision.com/info/life/porn/isporn.asp|accessdate=6 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509001316/http://www.soundvision.com/Info/life/porn/isporn.asp|archivedate=9 May 2013}}</ref> including concerns about [[modesty]], [[human dignity]], [[chastity]] and other virtues. There are numerous<ref>{{cite web|title=Bible Verses about Pornography |url=https://www.biblestudytools.com/topical-verses/bible-verses-about-pornography/}}</ref> verses in the Bible which are cited as condemning pornography or adultery, notably for [[Christians]], [[Matthew 5:28]] in the [[Sermon on the Mount]] which states \"that anyone who looks at a woman lustfully has already committed adultery with her in his heart.\" [[Islam]] also forbids adultery, and various verses of the Quran have been cited as condemning pornography, including [[Quran 24|Quran 24:31]] which tells men to \"restrain their eyes\" from looking sexually at women.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rashid |first=Qasim |title=Muslim men need to understand that the Quran says they should observe hijab first, not women |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/muslim-men-hijab-forcing-women-islam-teaching-mohammed-quran-modesty-a7655191.html}}</ref>\n\n==Feminist views==\n{{Main article|Feminist views on pornography}}\n\nSome [[feminists]] are opposed to pornography, arguing that it is an industry which exploits women and is complicit in [[violence against women]], both in its production (where they charge that abuse and exploitation of women performing in pornography is rampant) and in its consumption (where they charge that pornography eroticizes the [[Dominance hierarchy|domination]], [[humiliation]], and [[coercion]] of women, and reinforces sexual and cultural attitudes that are complicit in [[rape]] and [[sexual harassment]]).<ref>Morgan, Robin (1974). \"Theory and Practice: Pornography and Rape\". In: ''Going Too Far: The Personal Chronicle of a Feminist''. Random House. {{ISBN|0-394-48227-1}}.</ref> They charge that pornography contributes to the male-centered objectification of women and thus to sexism.<ref>MacKinnon, Catharine (1987). ''Feminism Unmodified: Discourses on Life and Law''. Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press. pp. 146\u2013150.</ref>\n\nHowever, many other feminists are opposed to censorship, and have argued against the introduction of anti-porn legislation in the United States - among them [[Betty Friedan]], [[Kate Millett]], [[Karen DeCrow]], [[Wendy Kaminer]] and [[Jamaica Kincaid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiawol.demon.co.uk/FAC/harm.htm|title=fiawol.demon.co.uk|author=|date=|website=www.fiawol.demon.co.uk|accessdate=8 April 2018|archive-date=2015-07-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709041905/http://www.fiawol.demon.co.uk:80/FAC/harm.htm}}</ref> Some [[sex-positive feminism|sex-positive feminists]] actively support pornography that depicts female sexuality in a positive way, without objectifying or demeaning women.\n\n== Conservative views ==\nReligious conservatives commonly oppose pornography, along with a subset of feminists, though their reasoning may differ.<ref name=\":0\" /> Many religious conservatives view pornography as a threat to children. Some conservative Protestants oppose pornography because it encourages non-procreative sex, encourages abortion, and can be connected to the rise of sexually transmitted diseases.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sherkat|first=Darren|last2=Ellison|first2=Christopher|year=1997|title=The Cognitive Structure of a Moral Crusade: Conservative Protestantism and Opposition to Pornography|jstor=2580526|journal=Social Forces|volume=75|issue=3|pages=957\u2013980|doi=10.1093/sf/75.3.957}}</ref>\n\n[[Concerned Women For America]] (CWA) is a conservative organization that opposes [[same-sex marriage]] and [[abortion]]. When discussing violence against women, the CWA often uses pornography to illustrate their points. The CWA asserts that pornography is a major reason why men inflict harm on women.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Righting Feminism|last=Schreiber|first=Ronnee|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2008|isbn=|location=New York|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> The CWA argues that pornography convinces men to disrespect their wives and neglect their marriages, thereby threatening the sanctity of traditional marriage. Unlike other issues CWA has tackled, they are less forcefully anti-feminist when it comes to the topic of pornography, as many of their points surrounding why pornography is distasteful parallels those of anti-pornography feminists.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Harm-based views==\n{{see also|Effects of pornography}}\n{{Imageframe|width=300|content=[[File:Zillmann Fig 7.png|300px]] [[File:Zillmann Fig 8.png|300px]] [[File:Zillmann Fig 9.png|300px]]|caption=Figures 7, 8, and 9 in Zillmann, Dolf: \"Effects of Prolonged Consumption of Pornography\", 1986.<ref name=\"Zillman\">{{cite web|url=http://profiles.nlm.nih.gov/NN/B/C/K/V/|title=Report of the Surgeon General's Workshop on Pornography and Public Health: Background Papers: 'Effects of Prolonged Consumption of Pornography'|first=Zillmann|last=Dolf|date=4 August 1986|website=profiles.nlm.nih.gov|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>|align=right}}\n\nDolf Zillmann argued in the 1986 publication \"Effects of Prolonged Consumption of Pornography\" that extensive viewing of pornographic material produces many unfavorable [[sociology|sociological]] effects, including a decreased respect for long-term [[monogamy|monogamous]] relationships, and an attenuated desire for [[reproduction|procreation]].<ref name=\"Zillman\"/> He describes the theoretical basis of these experimental findings:<blockquote>The values expressed in pornography clash so obviously with the family concept, and they potentially undermine the traditional values that favor marriage, family, and children... Pornographic scripts dwell on sexual engagements of parties who have just met, who are in no way attached or committed to each other, and who will part shortly, never to meet again... Sexual gratification in pornography is not a function of emotional attachment, of kindness, of caring, and especially not of continuance of the relationship, as such continuance would translate into responsibilities, curtailments, and costs...<ref>Zillmann, pages 16-17</ref></blockquote>\n\nA study by Zillman in 1982 also indicated that prolonged exposure to pornography desensitized both men and women toward victims of [[sexual violence]]. After being shown pornographic movies, test subjects were asked to judge an appropriate punishment for a rapist. The test subjects recommended incarceration terms that were significantly more lenient than those recommended by control subjects who had not watched pornography.<ref name=\"Zillman\"/>\n\nSome researchers like Zillman believe that pornography causes unequivocal harm to society by increasing rates of [[sexual assault]].<ref name=\"Zillman\"/><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Simmons | first1 = Catherine A. | last2 = Lehmann | first2 = Peter | last3 = Collier-Tenison | first3 = Shannon | title = Linking male use of the sex industry to controlling behaviors in violent relationships: an exploratory analysis | journal = [[Violence Against Women (journal)|Violence Against Women]] | volume = 14 | issue = 4 | pages = 406&ndash;417 | doi = 10.1177/1077801208315066 | pmid = 18359877 | date = April 2008 | ref = harv }}</ref> Other researchers believe that there is a correlation between pornography and a decrease of [[sex crime]]s.<ref name=\"Diamond,M\">{{Cite web | last = Diamond | first = Milton | title = The Effects of Pornography: An International Perspective | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115001619/http://www.hawaii.edu/PCSS/online_artcls/pornography/prngrphy_ovrvw.html |archive-date=15 January 2008 | url = http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/BIB/DIAM/effects_pornography.htm | publisher = Porn 101: Eroticism, Pornography, and the First Amendment, [[University of Hawaii]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | last = Kendall | first = Todd |url= http://www.law.stanford.edu/display/images/dynamic/events_media/Kendall%20cover%20+%20paper.pdf |title=Pornography, rape and the internet |accessdate=25 October 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061102192540/http://www.law.stanford.edu/display/images/dynamic/events_media/Kendall%20cover%20%2B%20paper.pdf |archivedate=2 November 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last = D'Amato | first = Anthony | title = Porn Up, Rape Down | journal = Northwestern Public Law Research Paper | id = id: 913013 | ssrn = 913013 | doi = 10.2139/ssrn.913013 | date = June 23, 2006 | url = https://ssrn.com/abstract=913013 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nPornography is often criticized for presenting an inaccurate picture of human sexuality.{{cn|date=May 2017}}\n\nThe appropriation of the sexually explicit in American culture is part of what has been called \"the [[pornification]] of America\".<ref>{{cite web | last = Whitehead | first = John W. | title = Miley Cyrus and the Pornification of America | url = https://www.rutherford.org/publications_resources/john_whiteheads_commentary/miley_cyrus_and_the_pornification_of_america | website = rutherford.org | publisher = The Rutherford Institute | access-date = 7 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Aucoin | first = Don | title = The pornification of America. From music to fashion to celebrity culture, mainstream entertainment reflects an X-rated attitude like never before | url =  http://www.boston.com/yourlife/articles/2006/01/24/the_pornification_of_america/?page=full | work = Boston Globe | date = January 24, 2006 | access-date = 7 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nRape culture is often discussed when it comes to pornography, and is defined by society victim-blaming women because of their rape. It is known as society making rape less substantial. Some of the most searched titles on pornography websites is rape scenes.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Makin | first1 = David A. | last2 = Morczek | first2 = Amber L. | title = The dark side of internet searches: a macro level assessment of rape culture | journal = International Journal of Cyber Criminology | volume = 9 | issue = 1 | pages = 1&ndash;23 | doi = 10.5281/zenodo.22057 | date = June 2015 | url = http://www.cybercrimejournal.com/Makin&Morczek2015vol9issue1.pdf | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n==Allegations of pornophobia<!--redirect from [[Pornophobia]]-->==\n{{expand-section|date=May 2017}}\n'''Pornophobia'''<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA-->, from Greek roots ''porn\u0113'', \"[[whore]]\" and ''[[wikt:phobia|phobia]]'', literally means fear of prostitutes. It may also refer to fear of sexual expression, in particular, fear of [[pornography]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Leigh | first = Carol (Scarlot Harlot) | author-link = Carol Leigh | chapter = Thanks, ma | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=zL0zAQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=pornophobia | editor-last = Sappington | editor-first = Rodney | editor-last2 = Stallings | editor-first2 = Tyler | title = Uncontrollable Bodies: Testimonies of Identity and Culture | page = [https://archive.org/details/uncontrollablebo0000unse/page/261 261] | publisher = Bay Press | location = Seattle | year = 1994 | isbn = 9780941920278 | quote = footnote 1 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/uncontrollablebo0000unse/page/261 }}</ref> \n\n[[Nadine Strossen]], former president of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], uses the coinages \"pornophobia\" and \"pornophobes\" when referring to attitudes of pro-[[censorship]] and [[conservatives]] to the imagery of [[nudity]], which they often refer to as \"pornography\".<ref name=nadine>{{cite news | last = Strossen | first = Nadine | author-link = Nadine Strossen | title = The perils of pornophobia | url = http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+perils+of+pornophobia-a016898789 | work = The Humanist | date = May 1, 1995}}\n:''Adapted from'': {{cite book | last = Strossen | first = Nadine | author-link = Nadine Strossen | title = Defending pornography: free speech, sex, and the fight for women's rights | publisher = New York University Press | location = New York London | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780814781494}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Strossen | first = Nadine | author-link = Nadine Strossen | title = Against pornophobia | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=keMCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=%22pornophobia%22&lr=lang_en&num=100&ei=NB2yStKWKZiQyQSl3uiTAw#v=onepage&q=&f=false | work = [[New York Magazine]] | date = 16 January 1995}}</ref> Strossen states that incidents have occurred at several colleges such as the [[University of Arizona]] and the [[University of Michigan]] Law School where feminist students have physically attacked exhibits of photographic self-portraits claiming that they must be taken down because these exhibits had sexual themes.<ref name=nadine/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Freedom of speech|Human sexuality|Erotica and pornography}}\n* [[Anti-pornography movement in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Anti-pornography movement in the United States]]\n* [[Effects of pornography]]\n* [[Pornography addiction]]\n* [[Pornography by region]]\n* [[Religious views on pornography]]\n* [[Right to pornography]]\n* [[Women Against Pornography]]\n* [[Women Against Violence in Pornography and Media]]\n* [[Criticism of Wikipedia#Sexual content]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n===Anti-pornography advocacy===\n* [[Susan Brownmiller]] (1999). ''In Our Time: Memoir of a Revolution''. The Dial Press. {{ISBN|0-385-31486-8}}.\n* [[Patrick Carnes]]\n* [[Victor Cline]]\n* [[Nikki Craft]], long-time political, anti-pornography activist and prolific writer on feminist subjects\n* [[Andrea Dworkin]] (1979). ''Pornography: Men Possessing Women''. {{ISBN|0-452-26793-5}}.\n* [[Susan Griffin]]. ''Pornography and Silence: Culture's Revenge Against Nature''. New York: Harper, 1981.\n* [[Craig Gross]], founder of [[XXXChurch|XXXchurch.com]], a non-profit [[Christianity|Christian]] organization that educates on the dangers of pornography use and involvement\n* [[Robert W. Jensen|Robert Jensen]] (2007). ''Getting Off: Pornography and the End of Masculinity''. Cambridge, MA: [[South End Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-89608-776-7}}.\n* [[Gail Dines]]/[[Robert W. Jensen|Robert Jensen]]/Ann Russo (1998). ''Pornography: The Production and Consumption of Inequality''. Routledge. {{ISBN|0-415-91813-8}}.\n* [[Susanne Kapeller]] (1986). ''The Pornography of Representation''. Polity Press, Cambridge, UK {{ISBN|0-7456-0122-7}}.\n* [[Michael Kimmel]] (1991). ''Men Confront Pornography''. New York: Meridian \u2014 Random House. {{ISBN|0-452-01077-2}}. (a variety of essays that try to assess ways that pornography may take influence or harm men)\n* [[Shelley Lubben]], former porn performer and self-described \"porn missionary\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shelleylubben.com/index.php?truth=bio|title=Shelley Lubben - My Blog, Thoughts, and Life|author=|date=|website=www.shelleylubben.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> who counsels active porn performers on how to escape the industry<ref name=\"cbn\">{{cite news|title = Out of Pornography and Into the Light|url = http://www.cbn.com/700club/guests/bios/shelley_lubben050506.aspx|publisher = CBN|accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> (2010). ''Truth Behind the Fantasy of Porn: The Greatest Illusion on Earth''. CreateSpace. {{ISBN|978-1-4538-6007-6}}.\n* [[Catharine MacKinnon]] (1985). ''Pornography, Civil Rights, and Speech.'' 20 Harv. C.R.-C.L. L. Rev. 1 (arguing that pornography is one of the mechanisms of power used to maintain gender inequality)\n* [[Donny Pauling]], former pornographic producer who currently speaks about the unseen side of porn that is damaging to the women involved; frequently worked with Craig Gross of XXXChurch, until pleading to a six-year underage sex sentencing\n* Christine Stark and [[Rebecca Whisnant]] (2004). {{cite book | title = Not for sale: feminists resisting prostitution and pornography | publisher = Spinifex Press | location = North Melbourne, Victoria | isbn = 9781876756499| year = 2004 }}\n\n===Criticism of anti-pornography===\n* [[Susie Bright]]. \"Susie Sexpert's Lesbian Sex World and Susie Bright's Sexual Reality: A Virtual Sex World Reader\", San Francisco, CA: Cleis Press, 1990 and 1992. Challenges any easy equation between feminism and anti-pornography positions.\n* [[Betty Dodson]]. \"Feminism and Free speech: Pornography.\" Feminists for Free Expression 1993. 8 May 2002.\n* Kate Ellis. Caught Looking: Feminism, Pornography, and Censorship. New York: Caught Looking Incorporated, 1986.\n* Matthew Gever. \"Pornography Helps Women, Society\", UCLA Bruin, 1998-12-03.\n* Michele Gregory. \"Pro-Sex Feminism: Redefining Pornography (or, a study in alliteration: the pro pornography position paper) \"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://witsendzine.com/musings/michele/ppp.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020809091134/http://witsendzine.com/musings/michele/ppp.htm |archivedate=2002-08-09 }}</ref>\n* [[Gayle Rubin]], \"Dangerous, Misguided, and Wrong: An Analysis of Anti-Pornograph Politics.\" In \"Bad Girl and Dirty Pictures,\" ed. Carol Assuster (1993). \n* Andrea Juno and V. Vale. Angry Women, Re/Search # 12. San Francisco, CA: Re/Search Publications, 1991. Performance artists and literary theorists who challenge Dworkin and MacKinnon's claim to speak on behalf of all women.\n** \"A Feminist Overview of Pornography, Ending in a Defense Thereof\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wendymcelroy.com/freeinqu.htm|title=A Feminist Overview of Pornography|first=Wendy|last=McElroy|date=|website=www.wendymcelroy.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n** \"A Feminist Defense of pornography\"<ref>[http://www.secularhumanism.org/library/fi/mcelroy_17_4.html A Feminist Defense of Pornography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/19981201205458/http://www.secularhumanism.org/library/fi/mcelroy_17_4.html |date=1998-12-01 }}</ref>\n* Ley, David, Prause, Nicole, & Finn, Peter. (2014). The Emperor Has No Clothes: A review of the \u201cPornography Addiction\u201d model. Current Sexual Health Reports, manuscript in press.<ref>{{cite journal | doi=10.1007/s11930-014-0016-8 | volume=6 | issue=2 | title=The Emperor Has No Clothes: A Review of the 'Pornography Addiction' Model | journal=Current Sexual Health Reports | pages=94\u2013105| year=2014 | last1=Ley | first1=David | last2=Prause | first2=Nicole | last3=Finn | first3=Peter}}</ref>\n* Annalee Newitz. \"Obscene Feminists: Why Women Are Leading the Battle Against Censorship.\" San Francisco Bay Guardian Online 8 May 2002. 9 May 2002<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfbg.com/36/32/news_womenvscensorship.html|title=sfbg.com|author=|date=|website=sfbg.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Nadine Strossen]]:\n** \"Defending Pornography: Free Speech, Sex and the Fight for Women's Rights\" ({{ISBN|0-8147-8149-7}})\n** \"Nadine Strossen: Pornography Must Be Tolerated\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spectacle.org/1195/strossen.html|author=Nadine Strossen|title=Pornography Must Be Tolerated|publisher=The Ethical Spectacle|date=November 1995}}</ref>\n* Scott Tucker. \"Gender, Fucking, and Utopia: An Essay in Response to John Stoltenberg's Refusing to Be a Man.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=am37yVCaQXAC&pg=PR14&lpg=PR14&dq=Gender,+Fucking,+and+Utopia:+An+Essay+in+Response+to+John+Stoltenberg's+Refusing+to+Be+a+Man|title=The Columbia Reader on Lesbians and Gay Men in Media, Society, and Politics|first1=Larry P.|last1=Gross|first2=James D.|last2=Woods|date=8 April 1999|publisher=Columbia University Press|accessdate=8 April 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9780231104463}}</ref> in Social Text 27 (1991): 3-34. Critique of Stoltenberg and Dworkin's positions on pornography and power.\n* Carole Vance, Editor. \"Pleasure and Danger: Exploring Female Sexuality\". Boston: Routledge, 1984. Collection of papers from 1982 conference; visible and divisive split between anti-pornography activists and lesbian S&M theorists.\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pornography}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anti-Pornography Movement}}\n[[Category:Anti-pornography movements| ]]\n[[Category:Censorship of pornography]]\n", "text_old": "{{expert needed|Politics|ex2=Sexology and sexuality|ex3=Conservatism|ex4=Libertarianism|date=December 2012}}\n[[File:Anti-pornography protest on Oxford Street in 2008.jpg|thumb|Anti-pornography protest on [[Oxford Street]], London]]\n\nReasons for '''opposition to pornography''' include [[Religious views on pornography|religious objections]], [[Feminist views of pornography|feminist concerns]], and claims of [[Effects of pornography|harmful effects]], such as [[pornography addiction]]. Anti-pornography movements have allied disparate social activists in opposition to pornography, from [[Social conservatism|social conservatives]] to [[harm reduction]] advocates.\n\nThe definition of \"[[pornography]]\" varies between countries and movements, and many make distinctions between pornography, which they oppose, and [[erotica]], which they consider acceptable. Sometimes opposition will deem certain forms of pornography more or less harmful, while others draw no such distinctions.\n\nA 2018 [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] survey reported that 43% of U.S. adults believe that it is \"morally acceptable,\" a 7% increase from 2017.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.gallup.com/poll/235280/americans-say-pornography-morally-acceptable.aspx|title=More Americans Say Pornography Is Morally Acceptable|last=Inc|first=Gallup|date=2018-06-05|website=Gallup.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> Historically, from 1975-2012, the gender gap in pornography opposition has widened, with women remaining more opposed to pornography than men and men's opposition has declined faster.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lykke|first=Lucia|last2=Cohen|first2=Philip|year=2015|title=The Widening Gender Gap in Opposition to Pornography, 1975\u20132012|doi=10.1177/2329496515604170|journal=Social Currents|volume=2|issue=4|pages=307\u2013323|url=http://osf.io/4dymx/}}</ref>\n\n==Religious views==\n{{Main article|Religious views on pornography}}\n\nMost world religions have positions in opposition to pornography from a variety of rationales,<ref>{{cite web|last=Slick|first=Matt|title=What does the Bible say about pornography? Is it wrong?|url=http://carm.org/pornography|accessdate=6 May 2013|date=2008-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Freeman|first=Tzvi|title=What's Wrong With Pornography?|url=http://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/658901/jewish/Whats-Wrong-with-Pornography.htm|accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mujahid|first=Abdul Malik|title=Islam on Pornography: A Definite No-No|url=http://www.soundvision.com/info/life/porn/isporn.asp|accessdate=6 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509001316/http://www.soundvision.com/Info/life/porn/isporn.asp|archivedate=9 May 2013}}</ref> including concerns about [[modesty]], [[human dignity]], [[chastity]] and other virtues. There are numerous<ref>{{cite web|title=Bible Verses about Pornography |url=https://www.biblestudytools.com/topical-verses/bible-verses-about-pornography/}}</ref> verses in the Bible which are cited as condemning pornography or adultery, notably for [[Christians]], [[Matthew 5:28]] in the [[Sermon on the Mount]] which states \"that anyone who looks at a woman lustfully has already committed adultery with her in his heart.\" [[Islam]] also forbids adultery, and various verses of the Quran have been cited as condemning pornography, including [[Quran 24|Quran 24:31]] which tells men to \"restrain their eyes\" from looking sexually at women.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rashid |first=Qasim |title=Muslim men need to understand that the Quran says they should observe hijab first, not women |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/muslim-men-hijab-forcing-women-islam-teaching-mohammed-quran-modesty-a7655191.html}}</ref>\n\n==Feminist views==\n{{Main article|Feminist views on pornography}}\n\nSome [[feminists]] are opposed to pornography, arguing that it is an industry which exploits women and is complicit in [[violence against women]], both in its production (where they charge that abuse and exploitation of women performing in pornography is rampant) and in its consumption (where they charge that pornography eroticizes the [[Dominance hierarchy|domination]], [[humiliation]], and [[coercion]] of women, and reinforces sexual and cultural attitudes that are complicit in [[rape]] and [[sexual harassment]]).<ref>Morgan, Robin (1974). \"Theory and Practice: Pornography and Rape\". In: ''Going Too Far: The Personal Chronicle of a Feminist''. Random House. {{ISBN|0-394-48227-1}}.</ref> They charge that pornography contributes to the male-centered objectification of women and thus to sexism.<ref>MacKinnon, Catharine (1987). ''Feminism Unmodified: Discourses on Life and Law''. Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press. pp. 146\u2013150.</ref>\n\nHowever, many other feminists are opposed to censorship, and have argued against the introduction of anti-porn legislation in the United States - among them [[Betty Friedan]], [[Kate Millett]], [[Karen DeCrow]], [[Wendy Kaminer]] and [[Jamaica Kincaid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiawol.demon.co.uk/FAC/harm.htm|title=fiawol.demon.co.uk|author=|date=|website=www.fiawol.demon.co.uk|accessdate=8 April 2018|archive-date=2015-07-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709041905/http://www.fiawol.demon.co.uk:80/FAC/harm.htm}}</ref> Some [[sex-positive feminism|sex-positive feminists]] actively support pornography that depicts female sexuality in a positive way, without objectifying or demeaning women.\n\n== Conservative views ==\nReligious conservatives commonly oppose pornography, along with a subset of feminists, though their reasoning may differ.<ref name=\":0\" /> Many religious conservatives view pornography as a threat to children. Some conservative Protestants oppose pornography because it encourages non-procreative sex, encourages abortion, and can be connected to the rise of sexually transmitted diseases.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sherkat|first=Darren|last2=Ellison|first2=Christopher|year=1997|title=The Cognitive Structure of a Moral Crusade: Conservative Protestantism and Opposition to Pornography|jstor=2580526|journal=Social Forces|volume=75|issue=3|pages=957\u2013980|doi=10.1093/sf/75.3.957}}</ref>\n\n[[Concerned Women For America]] (CWA) is a conservative organization that opposes [[same-sex marriage]] and [[abortion]]. When discussing violence against women, the CWA often uses pornography to illustrate their points. The CWA asserts that pornography is a major reason why men inflict harm on women.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Righting Feminism|last=Schreiber|first=Ronnee|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2008|isbn=|location=New York|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> The CWA argues that pornography convinces men to disrespect their wives and neglect their marriages, thereby threatening the sanctity of traditional marriage. Unlike other issues CWA has tackled, they are less forcefully anti-feminist when it comes to the topic of pornography, as many of their points surrounding why pornography is distasteful parallels those of anti-pornography feminists.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Harm-based views==\n{{see also|Effects of pornography}}\n{{Imageframe|width=300|content=[[File:Zillmann Fig 7.png|300px]] [[File:Zillmann Fig 8.png|300px]] [[File:Zillmann Fig 9.png|300px]]|caption=Figures 7, 8, and 9 in Zillmann, Dolf: \"Effects of Prolonged Consumption of Pornography\", 1986.<ref name=\"Zillman\">{{cite web|url=http://profiles.nlm.nih.gov/NN/B/C/K/V/|title=Report of the Surgeon General's Workshop on Pornography and Public Health: Background Papers: 'Effects of Prolonged Consumption of Pornography'|first=Zillmann|last=Dolf|date=4 August 1986|website=profiles.nlm.nih.gov|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>|align=right}}\n\nDolf Zillmann argued in the 1986 publication \"Effects of Prolonged Consumption of Pornography\" that extensive viewing of pornographic material produces many unfavorable [[sociology|sociological]] effects, including a decreased respect for long-term [[monogamy|monogamous]] relationships, and an attenuated desire for [[reproduction|procreation]].<ref name=\"Zillman\"/> He describes the theoretical basis of these experimental findings:<blockquote>The values expressed in pornography clash so obviously with the family concept, and they potentially undermine the traditional values that favor marriage, family, and children... Pornographic scripts dwell on sexual engagements of parties who have just met, who are in no way attached or committed to each other, and who will part shortly, never to meet again... Sexual gratification in pornography is not a function of emotional attachment, of kindness, of caring, and especially not of continuance of the relationship, as such continuance would translate into responsibilities, curtailments, and costs...<ref>Zillmann, pages 16-17</ref></blockquote>\n\nA study by Zillman in 1982 also indicated that prolonged exposure to pornography desensitized both men and women toward victims of [[sexual violence]]. After being shown pornographic movies, test subjects were asked to judge an appropriate punishment for a rapist. The test subjects recommended incarceration terms that were significantly more lenient than those recommended by control subjects who had not watched pornography.<ref name=\"Zillman\"/>\n\nSome researchers like Zillman believe that pornography causes unequivocal harm to society by increasing rates of [[sexual assault]].<ref name=\"Zillman\"/><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Simmons | first1 = Catherine A. | last2 = Lehmann | first2 = Peter | last3 = Collier-Tenison | first3 = Shannon | title = Linking male use of the sex industry to controlling behaviors in violent relationships: an exploratory analysis | journal = [[Violence Against Women (journal)|Violence Against Women]] | volume = 14 | issue = 4 | pages = 406&ndash;417 | doi = 10.1177/1077801208315066 | pmid = 18359877 | date = April 2008 | ref = harv }}</ref> Other researchers believe that there is a correlation between pornography and a decrease of [[sex crime]]s.<ref name=\"Diamond,M\">{{Cite web | last = Diamond | first = Milton | title = The Effects of Pornography: An International Perspective | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115001619/http://www.hawaii.edu/PCSS/online_artcls/pornography/prngrphy_ovrvw.html |archive-date=15 January 2008 | url = http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/BIB/DIAM/effects_pornography.htm | publisher = Porn 101: Eroticism, Pornography, and the First Amendment, [[University of Hawaii]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | last = Kendall | first = Todd |url= http://www.law.stanford.edu/display/images/dynamic/events_media/Kendall%20cover%20+%20paper.pdf |title=Pornography, rape and the internet |accessdate=25 October 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061102192540/http://www.law.stanford.edu/display/images/dynamic/events_media/Kendall%20cover%20%2B%20paper.pdf |archivedate=2 November 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last = D'Amato | first = Anthony | title = Porn Up, Rape Down | journal = Northwestern Public Law Research Paper | id = id: 913013 | ssrn = 913013 | doi = 10.2139/ssrn.913013 | date = June 23, 2006 | url = https://ssrn.com/abstract=913013 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nPornography is often criticized for presenting an inaccurate picture of human sexuality.{{cn|date=May 2017}}\n\nThe appropriation of the sexually explicit in American culture is part of what has been called \"the [[pornification]] of America\".<ref>{{cite web | last = Whitehead | first = John W. | title = Miley Cyrus and the Pornification of America | url = https://www.rutherford.org/publications_resources/john_whiteheads_commentary/miley_cyrus_and_the_pornification_of_america | website = rutherford.org | publisher = The Rutherford Institute | access-date = 7 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Aucoin | first = Don | title = The pornification of America. From music to fashion to celebrity culture, mainstream entertainment reflects an X-rated attitude like never before | url =  http://www.boston.com/yourlife/articles/2006/01/24/the_pornification_of_america/?page=full | work = Boston Globe | date = January 24, 2006 | access-date = 7 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nRape culture is often discussed when it comes to pornography, and is defined by society victim-blaming women because of their rape. It is known as society making rape less substantial. Some of the most searched titles on pornography websites is rape scenes.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Makin | first1 = David A. | last2 = Morczek | first2 = Amber L. | title = The dark side of internet searches: a macro level assessment of rape culture | journal = International Journal of Cyber Criminology | volume = 9 | issue = 1 | pages = 1&ndash;23 | doi = 10.5281/zenodo.22057 | date = June 2015 | url = http://www.cybercrimejournal.com/Makin&Morczek2015vol9issue1.pdf | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n==Allegations of pornophobia<!--redirect from [[Pornophobia]]-->==\n{{expand-section|date=May 2017}}\n'''Pornophobia'''<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA-->, from Greek roots ''porn\u0113'', \"[[whore]]\" and ''[[wikt:phobia|phobia]]'', literally means fear of prostitutes. It may also refer to fear of sexual expression, in particular, fear of [[pornography]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Leigh | first = Carol (Scarlot Harlot) | author-link = Carol Leigh | chapter = Thanks, ma | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=zL0zAQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=pornophobia | editor-last = Sappington | editor-first = Rodney | editor-last2 = Stallings | editor-first2 = Tyler | title = Uncontrollable Bodies: Testimonies of Identity and Culture | page = [https://archive.org/details/uncontrollablebo0000unse/page/261 261] | publisher = Bay Press | location = Seattle | year = 1994 | isbn = 9780941920278 | quote = footnote 1 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/uncontrollablebo0000unse/page/261 }}</ref> \n\n[[Nadine Strossen]], former president of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], uses the coinages \"pornophobia\" and \"pornophobes\" when referring to attitudes of pro-[[censorship]] and [[conservatives]] to the imagery of [[nudity]], which they often refer to as \"pornography\".<ref name=nadine>{{cite news | last = Strossen | first = Nadine | author-link = Nadine Strossen | title = The perils of pornophobia | url = http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+perils+of+pornophobia-a016898789 | work = The Humanist | date = May 1, 1995}}\n:''Adapted from'': {{cite book | last = Strossen | first = Nadine | author-link = Nadine Strossen | title = Defending pornography: free speech, sex, and the fight for women's rights | publisher = New York University Press | location = New York London | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780814781494}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Strossen | first = Nadine | author-link = Nadine Strossen | title = Against pornophobia | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=keMCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=%22pornophobia%22&lr=lang_en&num=100&ei=NB2yStKWKZiQyQSl3uiTAw#v=onepage&q=&f=false | work = [[New York Magazine]] | date = 16 January 1995}}</ref> Strossen states that incidents have occurred at several colleges such as the [[University of Arizona]] and the [[University of Michigan]] Law School where feminist students have physically attacked exhibits of photographic self-portraits claiming that they must be taken down because these exhibits had sexual themes.<ref name=nadine/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Freedom of speech|Human sexuality|Erotica and pornography}}\n* [[Anti-pornography movement in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Anti-pornography movement in the United States]]\n* [[Effects of pornography]]\n* [[Pornography addiction]]\n* [[Pornography by region]]\n* [[Religious views on pornography]]\n* [[Right to pornography]]\n* [[Women Against Pornography]]\n* [[Women Against Violence in Pornography and Media]]\n* [[Criticism of Wikipedia#Sexual content]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n===Anti-pornography advocacy===\n* [[Susan Brownmiller]] (1999). ''In Our Time: Memoir of a Revolution''. The Dial Press. {{ISBN|0-385-31486-8}}.\n* [[Patrick Carnes]]\n* [[Victor Cline]]\n* [[Nikki Craft]], long-time political, anti-pornography activist and prolific writer on feminist subjects\n* [[Andrea Dworkin]] (1979). ''Pornography: Men Possessing Women''. {{ISBN|0-452-26793-5}}.\n* [[Susan Griffin]]. ''Pornography and Silence: Culture's Revenge Against Nature''. New York: Harper, 1981.\n* [[Craig Gross]], founder of [[XXXChurch|XXXchurch.com]], a non-profit [[Christianity|Christian]] organization that educates on the dangers of pornography use and involvement\n* [[Robert W. Jensen|Robert Jensen]] (2007). ''Getting Off: Pornography and the End of Masculinity''. Cambridge, MA: [[South End Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-89608-776-7}}.\n* [[Gail Dines]]/[[Robert W. Jensen|Robert Jensen]]/Ann Russo (1998). ''Pornography: The Production and Consumption of Inequality''. Routledge. {{ISBN|0-415-91813-8}}.\n* [[Susanne Kapeller]] (1986). ''The Pornography of Representation''. Polity Press, Cambridge, UK {{ISBN|0-7456-0122-7}}.\n* [[Michael Kimmel]] (1991). ''Men Confront Pornography''. New York: Meridian \u2014 Random House. {{ISBN|0-452-01077-2}}. (a variety of essays that try to assess ways that pornography may take influence or harm men)\n* [[Shelley Lubben]], former porn performer and self-described \"porn missionary\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shelleylubben.com/index.php?truth=bio|title=Shelley Lubben - My Blog, Thoughts, and Life|author=|date=|website=www.shelleylubben.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> who counsels active porn performers on how to escape the industry<ref name=\"cbn\">{{cite news|title = Out of Pornography and Into the Light|url = http://www.cbn.com/700club/guests/bios/shelley_lubben050506.aspx|publisher = CBN|accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> (2010). ''Truth Behind the Fantasy of Porn: The Greatest Illusion on Earth''. CreateSpace. {{ISBN|978-1-4538-6007-6}}.\n* [[Catharine MacKinnon]] (1985). ''Pornography, Civil Rights, and Speech.'' 20 Harv. C.R.-C.L. L. Rev. 1 (arguing that pornography is one of the mechanisms of power used to maintain gender inequality)\n* [[Donny Pauling]], former pornographic producer who currently speaks about the unseen side of porn that is damaging to the women involved; frequently worked with Craig Gross of XXXChurch, until pleading to a six-year underage sex sentencing\n* Christine Stark and [[Rebecca Whisnant]] (2004). {{cite book | title = Not for sale: feminists resisting prostitution and pornography | publisher = Spinifex Press | location = North Melbourne, Victoria | isbn = 9781876756499| year = 2004 }}\n\n===Criticism of anti-pornography===\n* [[Susie Bright]]. \"Susie Sexpert's Lesbian Sex World and Susie Bright's Sexual Reality: A Virtual Sex World Reader\", San Francisco, CA: Cleis Press, 1990 and 1992. Challenges any easy equation between feminism and anti-pornography positions.\n* [[Betty Dodson]]. \"Feminism and Free speech: Pornography.\" Feminists for Free Expression 1993. 8 May 2002.\n* Kate Ellis. Caught Looking: Feminism, Pornography, and Censorship. New York: Caught Looking Incorporated, 1986.\n* Matthew Gever. \"Pornography Helps Women, Society\", UCLA Bruin, 1998-12-03.\n* Michele Gregory. \"Pro-Sex Feminism: Redefining Pornography (or, a study in alliteration: the pro pornography position paper) \"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://witsendzine.com/musings/michele/ppp.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020809091134/http://witsendzine.com/musings/michele/ppp.htm |archivedate=2002-08-09 }}</ref>\n* [[Gayle Rubin]], \"Dangerous, Misguided, and Wrong: An Analysis of Anti-Pornograph Politics.\" In \"Bad Girl and Dirty Pictures,\" ed. Carol Assuster (1993). \n* Andrea Juno and V. Vale. Angry Women, Re/Search # 12. San Francisco, CA: Re/Search Publications, 1991. Performance artists and literary theorists who challenge Dworkin and MacKinnon's claim to speak on behalf of all women.\n** \"A Feminist Overview of Pornography, Ending in a Defense Thereof\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wendymcelroy.com/freeinqu.htm|title=A Feminist Overview of Pornography|first=Wendy|last=McElroy|date=|website=www.wendymcelroy.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n** \"A Feminist Defense of pornography\"<ref>[http://www.secularhumanism.org/library/fi/mcelroy_17_4.html A Feminist Defense of Pornography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/19981201205458/http://www.secularhumanism.org/library/fi/mcelroy_17_4.html |date=1998-12-01 }}</ref>\n* Ley, David, Prause, Nicole, & Finn, Peter. (2014). The Emperor Has No Clothes: A review of the \u201cPornography Addiction\u201d model. Current Sexual Health Reports, manuscript in press.<ref>{{cite journal | doi=10.1007/s11930-014-0016-8 | volume=6 | issue=2 | title=The Emperor Has No Clothes: A Review of the 'Pornography Addiction' Model | journal=Current Sexual Health Reports | pages=94\u2013105| year=2014 | last1=Ley | first1=David | last2=Prause | first2=Nicole | last3=Finn | first3=Peter}}</ref>\n* Annalee Newitz. \"Obscene Feminists: Why Women Are Leading the Battle Against Censorship.\" San Francisco Bay Guardian Online 8 May 2002. 9 May 2002<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfbg.com/36/32/news_womenvscensorship.html|title=sfbg.com|author=|date=|website=sfbg.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Nadine Strossen]]:\n** \"Defending Pornography: Free Speech, Sex and the Fight for Women's Rights\" ({{ISBN|0-8147-8149-7}})\n** \"Nadine Strossen: Pornography Must Be Tolerated\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spectacle.org/1195/strossen.html|author=Nadine Strossen|title=Pornography Must Be Tolerated|publisher=The Ethical Spectacle|date=November 1995}}</ref>\n* Scott Tucker. \"Gender, Fucking, and Utopia: An Essay in Response to John Stoltenberg's Refusing to Be a Man.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=am37yVCaQXAC&pg=PR14&lpg=PR14&dq=Gender,+Fucking,+and+Utopia:+An+Essay+in+Response+to+John+Stoltenberg's+Refusing+to+Be+a+Man|title=The Columbia Reader on Lesbians and Gay Men in Media, Society, and Politics|first1=Larry P.|last1=Gross|first2=James D.|last2=Woods|date=8 April 1999|publisher=Columbia University Press|accessdate=8 April 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9780231104463}}</ref> in Social Text 27 (1991): 3-34. Critique of Stoltenberg and Dworkin's positions on pornography and power.\n* Carole Vance, Editor. \"Pleasure and Danger: Exploring Female Sexuality\". Boston: Routledge, 1984. Collection of papers from 1982 conference; visible and divisive split between anti-pornography activists and lesbian S&M theorists.\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pornography}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anti-Pornography Movement}}\n[[Category:Anti-pornography movements| ]]\n[[Category:Censorship of pornography]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1975-2012 \u2192 1975\u20132012", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opposition_to_pornography"}
{"title_page": "Shu Lea Cheang", "text_new": "'''Shu Lea Cheang''' ({{zh|c=\u912d\u6dd1\u9e97|p=Zh\u00e8ng Sh\u00fal\u00ec}}; born April 13, 1954, [[Taiwan]]) is a multimedia artist who works in the fields of net-based [[Installation art|installation]], social interface and film production. Cheang received a BA in History from the [[National Taiwan University]] in 1976 and  an MA in [[Film theory|Cinema Studies]] from [[Tisch School of the Arts|New York University]] in 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apa.nyu.edu/shu-lea-cheang-papers-mss-381/|title=Shu Lea Cheang Papers (MSS 381) \u2013 Asian/Pacific/American Institute at NYU|website=apa.nyu.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref> \n\nOver the past decade, she has emerged as a prominent figure in [[new media art]]. Cheang is one of the leading multimedia artists dealing with multidisciplinary topics. She is regarded as a pioneering figure in internet-based art, with her multimedia approach at the interface between film, video, internet-based installation, software interaction and durational performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seditionart.com/shu-lea-cheang |website=s[edition]}}</ref> Her work is often interactive. She is most noted for her individual approach in the realm of art and technology, creatively intermingling social issues with artistic methods.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walkerart.org/archive/1/B7737137B85D01716161.htm |title=WAC \u2013 Gallery9 \u2013 Bowling Alley |author=Shu Lea Cheang |accessdate=2008-04-28 |date=2004-02-13 |publisher=Walker art gallery |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081118051407/http://www.walkerart.org/archive/1/B7737137B85D01716161.htm |archivedate=2008-11-18 }}</ref>\n\nCheang's work employs film, video, net-based installation, and interface to explore \"...ethnic stereotyping, the nature and excesses of popular media, institutional - and especially governmental - power, race relations, and sexual politics.\" <ref>Tribe, M., & Jana, Reena. (2006). New media art (Basic art series).</ref> Cheang has also written and directed feature films [[I.K.U.]] and [[Fluid\u00f8]].\n\nShe has been a member of the [[Paper Tiger Television]] collective since 1981. Though originally based in New York, Cheang is currently living and working in Paris, France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://media.digitalarti.com/blog/digitalarti_mag/portrait_shu_lea_cheangs_interactive_mythologies|title=Portrait : SHU LEA CHEANG's interactive mythologies|date=2017-02-09|website=media.digitalarti.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Life events==\nCheang was born during a time when the island of Taiwan was under martial law in 1954. From Taiwan, Cheang moved to New York in the 1980s. She admitted to feeling liberated after moving, calling it a process of \u201cself-acknowledgment and affirmation.\u201d Her art career seeded and bloomed in New York.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ng |first1=Christina |title=At the Venice Biennale, Shu Lea Cheang Surveils the Surveillance System |url=https://hyperallergic.com/503068/at-the-venice-biennale-shu-lea-cheang-surveils-the-surveillance-system/ |website=HYPERALLERGIC |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter 20 years in New York, she went on a decade of a self-imposed lifestyle as a digital nomad which she says \u201cliberated me from monthly fixed payments of rent, electricity and phone bills.\u201d She lived in Japan, Holland, the United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/shu-lea-cheang |website=Guggenheim |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> and finally relocated to Paris in 2007, where she currently works and resides.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ng |first1=Christina |title=At the Venice Biennale, Shu Lea Cheang Surveils the Surveillance System |url=https://hyperallergic.com/503068/at-the-venice-biennale-shu-lea-cheang-surveils-the-surveillance-system/ |website=HYPERALLERGIC |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nTough social themes such as racial politics help progress her work. She recalls, \u201cWhen I first got to New York, I was more concerned about certain kinds of racial discrimination or stereotypes of being an Asian woman \u2014 there were many different kinds of fantasies about Asian women.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ng |first1=Christina |title=At the Venice Biennale, Shu Lea Cheang Surveils the Surveillance System |url=https://hyperallergic.com/503068/at-the-venice-biennale-shu-lea-cheang-surveils-the-surveillance-system/ |website=HYPERALLERGIC |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable works==\n''Color Schemes'', is an interactive three-channel video installation exhibited at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] in 1990. The video features people of different ethnicities and reveals the complex attitudes surrounding ethnic stereotyping embedded in American Culture. <ref>Furlong, B. Lucinda. Shu Lea Cheang's Genre-Bending Affirmations.</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Cheang directed the film ''[http://www.vdb.org/titles/fresh-kill&#x20;Kill Fresh Kill]''. The title refers to a garbage dump in Staten Island.<ref>{{Citation|last=Cheang|first=Shu Lea|title=Fresh Kill|date=1996-01-12|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0109843/|others=Sarita Choudhury, Erin McMurtry, Abraham Lim|accessdate=2018-03-03}}</ref> The film \"envisions a post-apocalyptic landscape strewn with electronic detritus and suffering the toxic repercussions of mass marketing in a high-tech commodity culture.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vdb.org/titles/fresh-kill|title=Fresh Kill {{!}} Video Data Bank|website=www.vdb.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref>\n\n''Bowling Alley'', commissioned by the [[Walker Art Center]] and funded by [[AT&T]] New Art/New Visions, was exhibited in 1995. The installation linked the Walker's Gallery 7, the city's community bowling alley (Bryant-Lake Bowl), and the [[World Wide Web]]. ''Bowling Alley'' mixed real-life with cyberspace to illustrate the similarities and differences of how people communicate with one another face-to-face and through the Internet. ''Bowling Alley''  was Cheang's first cybernetic installation. Cheang collaborated with other Minneapolis artists to present a work which set to challenge the idea of what is personal and public, popular art and fine art by intertwining these oppositions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bowlingalley.walkerart.org/cgi-bin/feedtitle.cgi|title=Bowling Alley :Introduction|website=bowlingalley.walkerart.org|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\nAnother major Web-based project Cheang created was ''Brandon'' (1998\u201399).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/15337|title=Brandon|date=1998-01-01|work=Guggenheim|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref> The one-year narrative project explored the issues of gender fusion and techno-body in both public space and cyberspace. The site got its name from [[Brandon Teena]], a trans man who was raped and murdered in 1993 after his biological sex was revealed. ''Brandon'' was the first Web-based artwork commissioned by [[The Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/15337|title=Brandon|date=1998-01-01|work=Guggenheim|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref> It explores Brandon Teena's story in an experimental way that conveys the \"fluidity and ambiguity of gender and identity in contemporary societies.\" <ref>{{cite book |title=New Media Art |last=Tribe |first=Mark |author2=Jana, Reena  |year=2007 |url= https://wiki.brown.edu/confluence/display/MarkTribe/New+Media+Art |publisher=Taschen |location=Germany |isbn=978-3-8228-3041-3 |pages= }}</ref> In addition to the website, ''Brandon'' included live public events at the Guggenheim Museum, the [https://waag.org/en/home De Waag Society for Old and New Media] in Amsterdam, and Harvard University.  \n\nOver time, as web browsers evolved, ''Brandon'' stopped displaying correctly. In 2017, the artwork was digitally restored and made publicly viewable again in a joint initiative by the Guggenheim's conservation department and [[New York University|New York University's]] department of computer science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.format.com/magazine/news/art/restoring-early-net-art-brandon-shu-lea-cheang-guggenheim|title=The Guggenheim Restores \u2018Brandon,\u2019 its First Web-Based Work|website=www.format.com|access-date=2017-10-13}}</ref>  ''Brandon'' was also featured in [[Rhizome (organization)|Rhizome]]'s Net Art Anthology, an online exhibition of one hundred important net artworks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://anthology.rhizome.org/brandon|title=NET ART ANTHOLOGY: Brandon|date=2016-10-27|work=NET ART ANTHOLOGY: Brandon|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref> ''Brandon'' is currently accessible at http://brandon.guggenheim.org. The project was a major achievement in the conservation of net.born art.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/blogs/checklist/restoring-brandon-shu-lea-cheangs-early-web-artwork|title=Restoring Brandon, Shu Lea Cheang's Early Web Work|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Cheang directed the feature film ''[[I.K.U.]]'',<ref>{{Citation|last=Aja|first=Shu Lea|title=I.K.U.|date=2001-05-03|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0255233/|last2=Akira|last3=Ariga|last4=As\u00f4|first3=Miho|first4=My\u00fb|accessdate=2017-03-12}}</ref> a pornographic film which she claimed was inspired by ''[[Blade Runner]].''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KIYbDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT67&lpg=PT67&dq=i.k.u.+blade+runner&source=bl&ots=17rHJ33Li6&sig=ux_eoCSlt-E-WxkjfiG-UZ8uoHw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi71uWH1dHSAhWM8oMKHUozBRAQ6AEIKDAC#v=onepage&q=i.k.u.%20blade%20runner&f=false|title=Trans Studies: The Challenge to Hetero/Homo Normativities|last=Miguel|first=Yolanda Mart\u00ednez-San|last2=Tobias|first2=Sarah|date=2016-03-22|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=9780813576428|language=en}}</ref> ''I.K.U.'' was nominated for an [[International Fantasy Film Award]].\n\n==Recent works==\nCheang's Locker Baby Project (2001-2012) is a playfield of sonic imagery triggered only by human interaction. Her baby series project proposes a fictional scenario set in year 2030. The transnational DPT (DollyPolly Transgency) advances clone babies as an intelligent industry. The Clone Generation holds the key to unlock the networked inter-sphere of ME-motion (Memory+Emotion).\n* ''Baby Play'' (2001), the first installment employs a large scale table football field. Opposing rows of 22 ball players are replaced by human sized cloned locker babies. The tracking of ball movement retrieves ME-data (texts and sound) deposited in respective lockers.\n* ''Baby Love'' (2005), the second installment consists of 6 large size teacups and 6 clone babies. Each teacup is an auto-driving mobile unit with spinning wheels allowing direction maneuver and speed variation. Each baby is a situated mac-mini engine with wifi linked to the net depository of shuffles and remixes of popular love songs.\n* ''Baby Work'' (2012),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://2012.zero1biennial.org/shu-lea-cheang|title=2012 ZERO1 Biennial|website=2012.zero1biennial.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> the third installment designates the public visiting the gallery to collect and rearrange scattered keys and compose words into collective sonic expression. Active participants are the clone babies who are entrusted to store and retrieve ME-data.\nCheang wrote and directed the 2017 science fiction film [[Fluid\u00f8]].\n\n== Archive ==\nThe Shu Lea Cheang Papers are part of [[Fales Library|Fales Library and Special Collections]] at New York University. This collection relates to Cheang's work from 1989 to 2007 and includes video footage, photographs, sketches, press clippings, installation objects, exhibition ephemera, and digital files.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apa.nyu.edu/shu-lea-cheang-papers-mss-381/|title=Shu Lea Cheang Papers (MSS 381) \u2013 Asian/Pacific/American Institute at NYU|website=apa.nyu.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== 2019 Venice Biennale ==\nShu Lea Cheang represented Taiwan at the [[58th Venice Biennale]] in 2019. She is the first woman to represent Taiwan with a solo-exhibition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.e-flux.com/announcements/204948/artist-shu-lea-cheang-to-represent-taiwan-at-2019-venice-biennale/|title=Artist Shu Lea Cheang to Represent Taiwan at 2019 Venice Biennale|website=eflux}}</ref> Her site-specific work was installed at the [[Palazzo delle Prigioni]], a former prison across from the [[Doge's Palace|Palazzo Ducale]] in [[Piazza San Marco]]. Curated by philosopher [[Paul B. Preciado]], the immersive installation explored pervasive technologies of control, from surveillance to incarceration, drawing from historical and contemporary cases in which people have been imprisoned due to their gender, sexual orientation, or race.[https://hyperallergic.com/472785/taiwan-pavilion-venice-biennale-shu-lea-cheang/]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://bowlingalley.walkerart.org/ Bowling Alley]\n* [http://brandon.guggenheim.org/ Brandon]\n* [http://babylove.biz/ Baby Love]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080405060947/http://www.vdb.org/smackn.acgi$artistdetail?CHEANGS Shu Lea Cheang] in the [[Video Data Bank]]\n* {{IMDb name|0154751}}\n* Shu Lea Cheang's artworks and [http://www.experimentaltvcenter.org/shu-lea-cheang biographical information] can be found in [[Experimental Television Center]] and [http://hdl.handle.net/1813.001/8946249a its Repository] in the [[Rose Goldsen Archive of New Media Art]]|, [[Cornell University Library]]. \n* [https://vimeo.com/user5349216 Shu Lea Cheang] on [[Vimeo]]  \n* https://web.archive.org/web/20080203204921/http://tiger.towson.edu/~kbinya1/shu_lea_cheang.html \n* https://web.archive.org/web/20081118051407/http://www.walkerart.org/archive/1/B7737137B85D01716161.htm \n* http://the-artists.org/artist/Shu-Lea-Cheang \n* Tribe, Mark and Reena Jana. New Media Art. https://wiki.brown.edu/confluence/x/Wkg{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \n* http://www.babywork.biz/proposal/lockerbaby-3parts.pdf\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cheang, Shu Lea}}\n[[Category:New media artists]]\n[[Category:Women pornographic film directors]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Installation artists]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Artists from Paris]]\n", "text_old": "'''Shu Lea Cheang''' ({{zh|c=\u912d\u6dd1\u9e97|p=Zh\u00e8ng Sh\u00fal\u00ec}}; born April 13, 1954, [[Taiwan]]) is a multimedia artist who works in the fields of net-based [[Installation art|installation]], social interface and film production. Cheang received a BA in History from the [[National Taiwan University]] in 1976 and  an MA in [[Film theory|Cinema Studies]] from [[Tisch School of the Arts|New York University]] in 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apa.nyu.edu/shu-lea-cheang-papers-mss-381/|title=Shu Lea Cheang Papers (MSS 381) \u2013 Asian/Pacific/American Institute at NYU|website=apa.nyu.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref> \n\nOver the past decade, she has emerged as a prominent figure in [[new media art]]. Cheang is one of the leading multimedia artists dealing with multidisciplinary topics. She is regarded as a pioneering figure in internet-based art, with her multimedia approach at the interface between film, video, internet-based installation, software interaction and durational performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seditionart.com/shu-lea-cheang |website=s[edition]}}</ref> Her work is often interactive. She is most noted for her individual approach in the realm of art and technology, creatively intermingling social issues with artistic methods.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walkerart.org/archive/1/B7737137B85D01716161.htm |title=WAC \u2013 Gallery9 \u2013 Bowling Alley |author=Shu Lea Cheang |accessdate=2008-04-28 |date=2004-02-13 |publisher=Walker art gallery |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081118051407/http://www.walkerart.org/archive/1/B7737137B85D01716161.htm |archivedate=2008-11-18 }}</ref>\n\nCheang's work employs film, video, net-based installation, and interface to explore \"...ethnic stereotyping, the nature and excesses of popular media, institutional - and especially governmental - power, race relations, and sexual politics.\" <ref>Tribe, M., & Jana, Reena. (2006). New media art (Basic art series).</ref> Cheang has also written and directed feature films [[I.K.U.]] and [[Fluid\u00f8]].\n\nShe has been a member of the [[Paper Tiger Television]] collective since 1981. Though originally based in New York, Cheang is currently living and working in Paris, France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://media.digitalarti.com/blog/digitalarti_mag/portrait_shu_lea_cheangs_interactive_mythologies|title=Portrait : SHU LEA CHEANG's interactive mythologies|date=2017-02-09|website=media.digitalarti.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Life events==\nCheang was born during a time when the island of Taiwan was under martial law in 1954. From Taiwan, Cheang moved to New York in the 1980s. She admitted to feeling liberated after moving, calling it a process of \u201cself-acknowledgment and affirmation.\u201d Her art career seeded and bloomed in New York.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ng |first1=Christina |title=At the Venice Biennale, Shu Lea Cheang Surveils the Surveillance System |url=https://hyperallergic.com/503068/at-the-venice-biennale-shu-lea-cheang-surveils-the-surveillance-system/ |website=HYPERALLERGIC |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter 20 years in New York, she went on a decade of a self-imposed lifestyle as a digital nomad which she says \u201cliberated me from monthly fixed payments of rent, electricity and phone bills.\u201d She lived in Japan, Holland, the United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/shu-lea-cheang |website=Guggenheim |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> and finally relocated to Paris in 2007, where she currently works and resides.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ng |first1=Christina |title=At the Venice Biennale, Shu Lea Cheang Surveils the Surveillance System |url=https://hyperallergic.com/503068/at-the-venice-biennale-shu-lea-cheang-surveils-the-surveillance-system/ |website=HYPERALLERGIC |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nTough social themes such as racial politics help progress her work. She recalls, \u201cWhen I first got to New York, I was more concerned about certain kinds of racial discrimination or stereotypes of being an Asian woman \u2014 there were many different kinds of fantasies about Asian women.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ng |first1=Christina |title=At the Venice Biennale, Shu Lea Cheang Surveils the Surveillance System |url=https://hyperallergic.com/503068/at-the-venice-biennale-shu-lea-cheang-surveils-the-surveillance-system/ |website=HYPERALLERGIC |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable works==\n''Color Schemes'', is an interactive three-channel video installation exhibited at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] in 1990. The video features people of different ethnicities and reveals the complex attitudes surrounding ethnic stereotyping embedded in American Culture. <ref>Furlong, B. Lucinda. Shu Lea Cheang's Genre-Bending Affirmations.</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Cheang directed the film ''[http://www.vdb.org/titles/fresh-kill&#x20;Kill Fresh Kill]''. The title refers to a garbage dump in Staten Island.<ref>{{Citation|last=Cheang|first=Shu Lea|title=Fresh Kill|date=1996-01-12|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0109843/|others=Sarita Choudhury, Erin McMurtry, Abraham Lim|accessdate=2018-03-03}}</ref> The film \"envisions a post-apocalyptic landscape strewn with electronic detritus and suffering the toxic repercussions of mass marketing in a high-tech commodity culture.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vdb.org/titles/fresh-kill|title=Fresh Kill {{!}} Video Data Bank|website=www.vdb.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref>\n\n''Bowling Alley'', commissioned by the [[Walker Art Center]] and funded by [[AT&T]] New Art/New Visions, was exhibited in 1995. The installation linked the Walker's Gallery 7, the city's community bowling alley (Bryant-Lake Bowl), and the [[World Wide Web]]. ''Bowling Alley'' mixed real-life with cyberspace to illustrate the similarities and differences of how people communicate with one another face-to-face and through the Internet. ''Bowling Alley''  was Cheang's first cybernetic installation. Cheang collaborated with other Minneapolis artists to present a work which set to challenge the idea of what is personal and public, popular art and fine art by intertwining these oppositions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bowlingalley.walkerart.org/cgi-bin/feedtitle.cgi|title=Bowling Alley :Introduction|website=bowlingalley.walkerart.org|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\nAnother major Web-based project Cheang created was ''Brandon'' (1998\u201399).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/15337|title=Brandon|date=1998-01-01|work=Guggenheim|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref> The one-year narrative project explored the issues of gender fusion and techno-body in both public space and cyberspace. The site got its name from [[Brandon Teena]], a trans man who was raped and murdered in 1993 after his biological sex was revealed. ''Brandon'' was the first Web-based artwork commissioned by [[The Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/15337|title=Brandon|date=1998-01-01|work=Guggenheim|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref> It explores Brandon Teena's story in an experimental way that conveys the \"fluidity and ambiguity of gender and identity in contemporary societies.\" <ref>{{cite book |title=New Media Art |last=Tribe |first=Mark |author2=Jana, Reena  |year=2007 |url= https://wiki.brown.edu/confluence/display/MarkTribe/New+Media+Art |publisher=Taschen |location=Germany |isbn=978-3-8228-3041-3 |pages= }}</ref> In addition to the website, ''Brandon'' included live public events at the Guggenheim Museum, the [https://waag.org/en/home De Waag Society for Old and New Media] in Amsterdam, and Harvard University.  \n\nOver time, as web browsers evolved, ''Brandon'' stopped displaying correctly. In 2017, the artwork was digitally restored and made publicly viewable again in a joint initiative by the Guggenheim's conservation department and [[New York University|New York University's]] department of computer science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.format.com/magazine/news/art/restoring-early-net-art-brandon-shu-lea-cheang-guggenheim|title=The Guggenheim Restores \u2018Brandon,\u2019 its First Web-Based Work|website=www.format.com|access-date=2017-10-13}}</ref>  ''Brandon'' was also featured in [[Rhizome (organization)|Rhizome]]'s Net Art Anthology, an online exhibition of one hundred important net artworks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://anthology.rhizome.org/brandon|title=NET ART ANTHOLOGY: Brandon|date=2016-10-27|work=NET ART ANTHOLOGY: Brandon|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref> ''Brandon'' is currently accessible at http://brandon.guggenheim.org. The project was a major achievement in the conservation of net.born art.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/blogs/checklist/restoring-brandon-shu-lea-cheangs-early-web-artwork|title=Restoring Brandon, Shu Lea Cheang's Early Web Work|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Cheang directed the feature film ''[[I.K.U.]]'',<ref>{{Citation|last=Aja|first=Shu Lea|title=I.K.U.|date=2001-05-03|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0255233/|last2=Akira|last3=Ariga|last4=As\u00f4|first3=Miho|first4=My\u00fb|accessdate=2017-03-12}}</ref> a pornographic film which she claimed was inspired by ''[[Blade Runner]].''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KIYbDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT67&lpg=PT67&dq=i.k.u.+blade+runner&source=bl&ots=17rHJ33Li6&sig=ux_eoCSlt-E-WxkjfiG-UZ8uoHw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi71uWH1dHSAhWM8oMKHUozBRAQ6AEIKDAC#v=onepage&q=i.k.u.%20blade%20runner&f=false|title=Trans Studies: The Challenge to Hetero/Homo Normativities|last=Miguel|first=Yolanda Mart\u00ednez-San|last2=Tobias|first2=Sarah|date=2016-03-22|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=9780813576428|language=en}}</ref> ''I.K.U.'' was nominated for an [[International Fantasy Film Award]].\n\n==Recent works==\nCheang's Locker Baby Project (2001-2012) is a playfield of sonic imagery triggered only by human interaction. Her baby series project proposes a fictional scenario set in year 2030. The transnational DPT (DollyPolly Transgency) advances clone babies as an intelligent industry. The Clone Generation holds the key to unlock the networked inter-sphere of ME-motion (Memory+Emotion).\n* ''Baby Play'' (2001), the first installment employs a large scale table football field. Opposing rows of 22 ball players are replaced by human sized cloned locker babies. The tracking of ball movement retrieves ME-data (texts and sound) deposited in respective lockers.\n* ''Baby Love'' (2005), the second installment consists of 6 large size teacups and 6 clone babies. Each teacup is an auto-driving mobile unit with spinning wheels allowing direction maneuver and speed variation. Each baby is a situated mac-mini engine with wifi linked to the net depository of shuffles and remixes of popular love songs.\n* ''Baby Work'' (2012),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://2012.zero1biennial.org/shu-lea-cheang|title=2012 ZERO1 Biennial|website=2012.zero1biennial.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> the third installment designates the public visiting the gallery to collect and rearrange scattered keys and compose words into collective sonic expression. Active participants are the clone babies who are entrusted to store and retrieve ME-data.\nCheang wrote and directed the 2017 science fiction film [[Fluid\u00f8]].\n\n== Archive ==\nThe Shu Lea Cheang Papers are part of [[Fales Library|Fales Library and Special Collections]] at New York University. This collection relates to Cheang's work from 1989 to 2007 and includes video footage, photographs, sketches, press clippings, installation objects, exhibition ephemera, and digital files.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apa.nyu.edu/shu-lea-cheang-papers-mss-381/|title=Shu Lea Cheang Papers (MSS 381) \u2013 Asian/Pacific/American Institute at NYU|website=apa.nyu.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== 2019 Venice Biennale ==\nShu Lea Cheang represented Taiwan at the [[58th Venice Biennale]] in 2019. She is the first woman to represent Taiwan with a solo-exhibition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.e-flux.com/announcements/204948/artist-shu-lea-cheang-to-represent-taiwan-at-2019-venice-biennale/|title=Artist Shu Lea Cheang to Represent Taiwan at 2019 Venice Biennale|website=eflux}}</ref> Her site-specific work was installed at the [[Palazzo delle Prigioni]], a former prison across from the [[Doge's Palace|Palazzo Ducale]] in [[Piazza San Marco]]. Curated by philosopher [[Paul B. Preciado]], the immersive installation explored pervasive technologies of control, from surveillance to incarceration, drawing from historical and contemporary cases in which people have been imprisoned due to their gender, sexual orientation, or race.[https://hyperallergic.com/472785/taiwan-pavilion-venice-biennale-shu-lea-cheang/]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://bowlingalley.walkerart.org/ Bowling Alley]\n* [http://brandon.guggenheim.org/ Brandon]\n* [http://babylove.biz/ Baby Love]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080405060947/http://www.vdb.org/smackn.acgi$artistdetail?CHEANGS Shu Lea Cheang] in the [[Video Data Bank]]\n* {{IMDb name|0154751}}\n* Shu Lea Cheang\u2019s artworks and [http://www.experimentaltvcenter.org/shu-lea-cheang biographical information] can be found in [[Experimental Television Center]] and [http://hdl.handle.net/1813.001/8946249a its Repository] in the [[Rose Goldsen Archive of New Media Art]]|, [[Cornell University Library]]. \n* [https://vimeo.com/user5349216 Shu Lea Cheang] on [[Vimeo]]  \n* https://web.archive.org/web/20080203204921/http://tiger.towson.edu/~kbinya1/shu_lea_cheang.html \n* https://web.archive.org/web/20081118051407/http://www.walkerart.org/archive/1/B7737137B85D01716161.htm \n* http://the-artists.org/artist/Shu-Lea-Cheang \n* Tribe, Mark and Reena Jana. New Media Art. https://wiki.brown.edu/confluence/x/Wkg{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \n* http://www.babywork.biz/proposal/lockerbaby-3parts.pdf\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cheang, Shu Lea}}\n[[Category:New media artists]]\n[[Category:Women pornographic film directors]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Installation artists]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Artists from Paris]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shu_Lea_Cheang"}
{"title_page": "Al Goldstein", "text_new": "{{about|the American pornographer|the American football player|Al Goldstein (American football)}}\n{{short description|American pornographer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Al Goldstein\n| image       = Al Goldstein.jpg\n| birthname   = Alvin Goldstein\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date |1936|1|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2013|12|19|1936|1|10}}\n| death_place = [[Cobble Hill, Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.\n| spouse      = {{Unbulleted list|{{marriage|Lonnie Leavitt|1963|1965|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Mary Phillips|1968|1977|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Gena Goldstein|1978|1991|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Patricia Flaherty|1994|1999|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Christina Ava Maharaj|2004|2006|end=divorced}}}}\n| children    = Jordan Goldstein\n| occupation  = [[Publisher]]\n}}\n\n'''Alvin''' \"'''Al'''\" '''Goldstein''' (January 10, 1936 \u2013 December 19, 2013) was an American [[Pornography|pornographer]]. He is known for normalizing hardcore pornography in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"nytobit\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/people-algoldstein/al-goldstein-pornography-pioneer-who-claimed-free-speech-dies-idUSL2N0JY17Q20131219|title=Al Goldstein, pornography pioneer who claimed free speech, dies|last=Cavaliere|first=Victoria|date=December 19, 2013|website=[[Reuters]]|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/dec/19/screw-magazine-publisher-al-goldstein-dies-aged-77|title=Screw magazine publisher Al Goldstein dies aged 77|last=|first=|date=December 19, 2013|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was described in his [[obituary]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"a cartoonishly vituperative amalgam of [[Borscht Belt]] comic, free-range social critic and sex-obsessed loser who seemed to embody a moment in New York City's cultural history: the sleaze and decay of [[Times Square]] in the 1960s and \u201870s.\"<ref name=\"nytobit\">{{cite news |title=Al Goldstein, a Publisher Who Took the Romance Out of Sex, Dies at 77 |first=Andy |last=Newman |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=A1 |date=December 19, 2013| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/20/nyregion/al-goldstein-pioneering-pornographer-dies-at-77.html}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nGoldstein was born in [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn]] to a [[Jewish]] family. He attended [[Boys High School (Brooklyn)|Boys High]]. He served in the Army as a photographer (in the [[Signal Corps (United States Army)|Signal Corps]]), captained the debate team at [[Pace College]] (for whose newspaper he interviewed [[Allen Ginsberg]]), and was a photojournalist, taking pictures of [[Jacqueline Kennedy]] on a 1962 state trip to [[Pakistan]] and spending several days in a Cuban jail for taking unauthorized photos of [[Fidel Castro]]'s brother, [[Ra\u00fal Castro|Ra\u00fal]].<ref name=AntiHef>{{cite web|first=Will|last=Sloan|title=Al Goldstein: The Anti-Hef|url=http://penguinrandomhouse.ca/hazlitt/longreads/al-goldstein-anti-hef|date=December 20, 2013|accessdate=November 20, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030211908/http://penguinrandomhouse.ca/hazlitt/longreads/al-goldstein-anti-hef|archive-date=October 30, 2014|url-status = dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe sold insurance; wrote freelance articles; ran a dime-pitch concession at the [[1964 New York World's Fair|1964-65 New York World's Fair]]; sold rugs, encyclopedias, and his own blood; drove a cab (he kept his hack [cab driver's] license active until his death); and landed a job as an industrial spy infiltrating a labor union, an experience that so appalled him he wrote an expos\u00e9 about it for the ''[[New York Free Press]]'', a radical weekly.<ref name=\"nytobit\"/><ref name=NYTDirty>{{cite news|first=Steven|last=Haller|title=My Dirty Life and Times\" (review of ''I, Goldstein. My Screwed Life'')|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 19, 2006|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D02E6DF1F3FF93AA25752C1A9609C8B63&pagewanted=2|accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Print publications==\n\n===''Screw''===\nIn November 1968 in New York, Al and his partner Jim Buckley, investing $175 each, founded ''[[Screw (magazine)|Screw]]'', a weekly tabloid. It featured reviews of [[Pornographic film|porn movies]], [[peep show]]s, erotic [[massage parlors]], [[brothel]]s, [[Call girl|escorts]] and other offerings of the [[adult entertainment]] industry. Such items were interspersed with sexual news, book reviews of sexual books, and hardcore \"gynecological\" pictorials. He regularly ran, without permission, photos and drawings of celebrities.\n\n\"''Screw'' grew from a combination of many factors, chief of which was my own dissatisfaction with the sex literature of 1968 and my yearning for a publication that reflected my sexual appetites,\" he wrote. \"I may be making a lot of money, but I really believe I'm doing some good by demythologizing a lot about sexuality\", he said in a [[Playboy Interview]]. It was described as \"raunchy, obnoxious, usually disgusting and sometimes political.\"<ref name=Jewniverse>{{cite web|first=Marc|last=Davis|title=The Screw-y, Filthy World of Al Goldstein|work=Jewniverse|date=November 18, 2013|url=http://thejewniverse.com/2013/the-screw-y-filthy-world-of-al-goldstein|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref> The initial price was 25\u00a2. At its peak, ''Screw'' sold 140,000 copies a week.<ref name=Rialto>{{cite web|first=Ashley|last=West|title=Remembering Al Goldstein: A Happy Jew|work=The Rialto Report|date=January 4, 2014| url=http://www.therialtoreport.com/2014/01/05/remembering-al-goldstein-a-happy-jew|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=BrowardScrewed>{{cite news|first=Bob|last=Whitby|title=Screwed|newspaper=Broward/Palm Beach New Times|date=February 22, 2001|url=http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2001-02-22/news/screwed|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nArrested 19 times on obscenity charges, he spent millions on [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] lawsuits, ultimately scoring a major victory when a federal judge dismissed an obscenity case in 1974. (Goldstein believed that the case began as a result of ''Screw''{{'}}s article, \"Is [[Sexuality of J. Edgar Hoover|J. Edgar Hoover]] a Fag?\",<ref name=Jewniverse/><ref>{{cite magazine |number=11 |date=May 2, 1969 |url=http://www.specificobject.com/objects/info.cfm?object_id=12758#.VL16PkfF9S0 |magazine=[[Screw (magazine)|Screw]] |title=Is J. Edgar Hoover a Fag?}}</ref> the first published comment on Hoover's sexuality.<ref name=\"Dirty\">{{cite book|last=Edison|first=Mike|title=Dirty! Dirty! Dirty!: Of \u2014Playboys, Pigs, and Penthouse Paupers \u2014An American Tale of Sex and Wonder|publisher=Soft Skull Press|year=2011|isbn=978-1-5937-6284-1|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dirtydirtydirtyo0000edis}}</ref>) [[Forum shopping|Venue-shopping]] prosecutors selected conservative [[Wichita, Kansas]], to prosecute Goldstein for [[obscenity]];<ref>{{cite news|first=John|last=Marshall|title=Postal Officials Admit False-Name Subscriptions|newspaper=Garden City [Kansas] Telegram|date=May 28, 1976|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/468445|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> when he was found not guilty, he flew the jury to New York to attend a party at the swing club [[Plato's Retreat]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2199&dat=19800504&id=_pYyAAAAIBAJ&pg=4013,531430| title=Goldstein says 2nd thank you|newspaper=Lawrence Journal-World|date=May 4, 1980|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref> His long-term attorney was Herald Price Fahringer.<ref name=NYTDirty/><ref>{{cite web|title=Al Goldstein: Screw, Midnight Blue, and Fuck You Podcast 31|work=The Rialto Report|date=February 23, 2014|url=http://www.therialtoreport.com/2014/02/23/al-goldstein-screw-midnight-blue-and-fuck-you-podcast-31|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Will Sloan, \"Goldstein was the first journalist to seriously review porn films. Had he not written a rave review of a low-budget film called ''Deep Throat'' (\u201cI was never so moved by any theatrical performance since stuttering through my own bar mitzvah\u201d), it would never have become a hit at New York's World Theater, would never have been targeted by the vice squad, would never have spawned a First Amendment cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre, and might not have led to the modern porn industry.\"<ref name=AntiHef/>\n\n===''Bitch'' magazine===\nIn the March 11, 1974, issue of ''Screw'' Goldstein ran an ad seeking subscribers to a new magazine, ''Bitch'', which \"brings women's sexuality out of the closet for the first time\" and also \"takes women out of politics and puts them back on their back where they belong.\" (Note: there have been several other magazines also called ''Bitch''.)<ref>{{cite web|publisher=WorldCat.org|title=Journals + Publications entitled \"Bitch\"|url=http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=ti%3ABitch&fq=x0%3Ajrnl&qt=advanced&dblist=638|accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref> The first issue \"contain[ed] an explosive symposium about blowjobs by four women who talk about giving head and what they like and don't like about it\". It also included an interview with actor [[James Caan]], and a centerfold of a man shot by a female photographer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://40.media.tumblr.com/51cdb2a332ae633aa4b7b48b54668c8e/tumblr_n5diz1VSXK1sbtct0o1_500.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image : Bitch Bites Back! |date=March 11, 1974 |website=40.media.tumblr.com |accessdate=2016-10-16}}</ref>\n\n===''Smut'' Magazine===\nIn the same March 11, 1974, issue of ''Screw'' Goldstein also ran an ad seeking subscribers to ''Smut'', a magazine \"so filthy that not only do you have to wash after every page, but every reader must disinfect after reading! SMUT is so dirty, so scummy, that once you have it on your hands you can't get it off!\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/image/89331982458 |title=Subscribe to Smut Today |website=[[Tumblr]] |access-date=November 20, 2014}}</ref> The magazine offered pornography in images and words, without the news articles found in ''Screw''.\n\n===''National Screw''===\nIn 1976-1977 ''National Screw'' was published; the place of publication was given as [[Secaucus, New Jersey]]. The June 1977 issue of the magazine contained, according to its cover, a new story by [[William Burroughs]] and an interview with [[Allen Ginsberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageadultmagazinecovers.tumblr.com/post/85141297591 |title=Vintage Adult Magazine Covers |publisher=Vintageadultmagazinecovers.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> It is known to have published five issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cornell.worldcat.org/oclc/55740108|work=Cornell University|title=Library Catalog \u2013 National Screw|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===''Death'' magazine===\nIn 1979, Goldstein began ''Death'' magazine. It lasted four issues.<ref>A cover is reproduced at {{cite web|url=http://nonpopocculture.tumblr.com/image/98793218925 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-30 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109125620/http://nonpopocculture.tumblr.com/image/98793218925 |archivedate=November 9, 2014 }}</ref> The February, 1980 issue had a picture of [[Elvis Presley]] on the cover, \"Grim Reaper Awards\", \"Eulogy to a War Lover\", \"Death by Hanging\", \"Femme Fatales\", and other articles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/image/99335715723 |title=Screw Magazine : Photo |publisher=Screwmag.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n===''Screw West''===\nIn 1979-1980 Goldstein's company, Milky Way Productions, published ''Screw West'' out of an office in [[Hollywood, California]]. According to an advertisement, it was intended to answer such questions as, \"Where can I get laid in San Francisco? What's the best swinger's club in Los Angeles? How do I find all those out-of-the-way Pacific Coast nude beaches? And what are those bawdy brothels outside Las Vegas really like?\" It is known to have published 54 issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://suncat.csun.edu/record=b2477029| work=California State University |title=Library Catalog \u2013 Screw West|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Movies and television==\n{{More citations needed section|date=October 2016}}\n\n===''It Happened in Hollywood''===\nIn 1973, \"Screw Magazine present[ed]\" ''It Happened in Hollywood'', a pornographic movie, produced by Goldstein's partner Jim Buckley. Goldstein played a character in the movie, and is also credited as \"fourth unit director.\" At the 2nd Annual [[New York Erotic Film Festival]] it won awards for Best Picture, Best Female Performance, and Best Supporting Actor.<ref>\"Screw Film Sweeps Awards\", ''Screw'', March 26, 1973.</ref>\n\n===''Midnight Blue''===\nIn 1974 Goldstein began ''Screw Magazine of the Air'', soon renamed ''[[Midnight Blue (TV series)|Midnight Blue]]'', a thrice weekly hour-long adult-oriented public access television program that ran for nearly 30 years on [[Manhattan Cable Television|Manhattan Cable]]'s Channel J; federal regulations regarding public access to cable TV systems made it impossible for the cable system to refuse his program.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/03/05/arts/channel-j-pornography-is-cause-of-lockout-law.html|newspaper=The New York Times| title=Channel J Pornography is Cause of Lockout Law|first=Sally|last=Bedell Smith|date=March 5, 1984|accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Screw magazine publisher Al Goldstein dies aged 77|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/dec/19/screw-magazine-publisher-al-goldstein-dies-aged-77|accessdate=2013-12-28|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2013-12-19}}</ref> (Similarly, Goldstein used a legal prohibition on the censorship of political advertisements to force television broadcast of pornography, under a transparent, but legal, veil of \"political candidacy\".) In it, he regularly interviewed porn stars, other adult industry figures, and sympathetic celebrities and \"freaks\", and ran advertisements for brothels and phone sex services.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nIn the later years, after departure of original director Alex Bennett, Goldstein featured on each program a \"Fuck You\" segment, a few minutes in which he viciously attacked celebrities, politicians, the judge who presided over his latest trial, the [[New York County]] District Attorney, and businesses he felt had wronged him.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nIn its early years, ''Midnight Blue'' presented porn star [[Georgina Spelvin]] doing her nude tap-dance act at the Melody Burlesque; Tara Alexander attempting the world's biggest [[gang bang]] at [[Plato's Retreat]], the New York swing club; the 10th anniversary ''Screw'' party, where Buck Henry and Melvin Van Peebles hobnob with Goldstein's jurors; and an early look at the S&M community in New York. Throughout its run, Midnight Blue interviewed almost every major porn star, and regularly hit the limits of what was acceptable for cable television.\"<ref name=AntiHef/> Seven volumes of excerpts from the show have been reissued on DVD.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=sr_nr_n_12?rh=n%3A2625373011%2Cp_n_format_browse-bin%3A2650304011%2Ck%3A%22midnight+blue%22&keywords=%22midnight+blue%22&ie=UTF8&qid=1408017915&rnid=2941120011 |title=\"midnight blue\" \u2013 DVD: Movies & TV |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n===SOS: Screw on the Screen===\nIn 1975, Goldstein issued ''SOS: Screw on the Screen'', a stridently unsexy attempt at a cinematic newsmagazine that included a lot of goofy comedy, a gay scene, and several minutes of Goldstein ranting about America's sexual hypocrisy. Also appearing was [[Honeysuckle Divine]] (who often appeared in ''SCREW'').<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://36.media.tumblr.com/95598a5d4bba63bc4aa7ace5b6fe37a1/tumblr_n8et7yfxSe1sbtct0o1_1280.jpg |title=Diary of a Dirty Broad |publisher=Screw |date=1974-03-11 |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> A poster of her was on sale in the same issue. [[Honeysuckle Divine]] was a Times Square stripper whose specialty was inserting objects such as pickles in her vagina, shooting out many of them. She put the pickles in baggies and sold them to patrons. Goldstein said that her act \"was unbelievably disgusting, so naturally, we made her our symbol.\"<ref name=AntiHef/>\n\n==Other business ventures==\n\n===The Screw Store===\nIn the May 17, 1976, issue of ''Screw'' Goldstein ran an ad for the \"Screw Store\", which offered dildos, including a \"Bicentennial Dildo\", vibrating [[Ben wa]] eggs, and a vibrating [[cock ring]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/post/83282516250/may-17-1976 |title=Screw Magazine |publisher=Screwmag.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> Selling dildos brought one of Goldstein's many arrests.<ref name=AntiHef/><ref>Josh Alan Friedman, [http://mmuseumm.com/exhibitions/al-goldsteins-personal-ephemera \"Al Goldstein's Personal Ephemera\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210050717/http://mmuseumm.com/exhibitions/al-goldsteins-personal-ephemera |date=December 10, 2014 }}; accessed November 20, 2014.</ref>\n\n===Al Goldstein's Cinema===\nThe October 17, 1977, issue of ''Screw'' contained an advertisement for \"Al Goldstein's Cinema\", located at 8th Avenue and 46th Street near [[Times Square]]. Admission was 99\u00a2.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/post/68563086292/october-17-1977 |title=Screw Magazine |publisher=Screwmag.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> In the same issue, in the movie listings, it is described as \"a large, comfortable porn house which shows average hardcore features. Some of these are first-run features, some have already played theaters in the city.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/post/71220104271/reviews-of-porn-theaters-october-17-1977 |title=Screw Magazine |publisher=Screwmag.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> The theater is not found in a listing of porn theaters from 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/image/96709693643 |title=Screw Magazine : Photo |publisher=Screwmag.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n===Rabbit Ranch===\nIn 2001, on [[Saint Martin]], an island in the [[Lesser Antilles]], Goldstein planned to open the Rabbit Ranch, the first of what he hoped would be a chain of 10 to 30 bordellos that would flourish wherever prostitution is legal.<ref name=BrowardScrewed /> He intended to use the profits to finance his second run for sheriff. The brothel never opened; authorities refused to give him a license because he was not a citizen of that nation. \"We didn't bribe the right people or something,\" he said.<ref name=\"Bob Whitby 2001\">Bob Whitby, [http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2001-05-03/news/undercurrents/2 \"Undercurrents\"], ''Broward/Palm Beach New Times'', May 3, 2001; retrieved October 30, 2014.</ref>\n\n== Political and religious views ==\n\n=== Free speech ===\nIn 1989, Goldstein ran a full page ad in ''Screw'' offering $1 million for the assassination of the [[Ayatollah Khomeini]], in response to Khomeini's [[fatwa]] against novelist [[Salman Rushdie]] for allegedly [[Blasphemy|blaspheming]] [[Islam]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1291&dat=19890414&id=WFBYAAAAIBAJ&pg=4665,5019656|title=Threat begets threats|date=1989-04-14|newspaper=Boca Raton News|accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref>\n\n===View on Christianity===\nIn his book ''XXX-Communicated: A Rebel Without a Shul'', [[Luke Ford (blogger)|Luke Ford]] wrote about a conversation with Goldstein, in which Ford asked Goldstein why Jews were dramatically overrepresented in the porn industry. He answered, \"The only reason that Jews are in pornography is that we think that Christ sucks. Catholicism sucks. We don't believe in authoritarianism.\" Ford then asked, \"What does it mean to you to be a Jew?\" To which Goldstein responded, \"It doesn't mean anything. It means that I'm called a [[kike]].\"  Ford also asked, \"Do you believe in God?\" Goldstein said, \"I believe in me. I'm God.  Screw God. God is your need to believe in some super being. I am the super being. I am your God, admit it. We're random. We're the flea on the butt of the dog.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rMzW_FLdJGwC&pg=PA69&lpg=PA69&dq=al+goldstein+luke+ford#v=onepage&q=al%20goldstein%20luke%20ford&f=false|title=XXX-Communicated: A Rebel Without a Shul|accessdate=2016-10-08|isbn=9780595318940|last1=Ford|first1=Luke|year=2004}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Friendship with Larry Flynt===\nOne of Goldstein's best friends was [[Larry Flynt]]. Goldstein said that Flynt's ''[[Hustler]]'' magazine, founded seven years after ''Screw'', stole the ''Hustler'' format from ''Screw'', but that he was not angry. According to Goldstein, Flynt succeeded in creating a national publication, at which he had failed.<ref>{{YouTube|id=GdBWpHZkPPo|title=\"Goldstein on Flynt, Flynt on Goldstein\"}}</ref>\n\n===Family===\nGoldstein married five times and had a son, Jordan Ari Goldstein, with his third wife, Gina. According to Goldstein, he and Jordan had a close relationship until the Goldsteins' divorce. They became estranged after Al called Gina \"a contemptible vagina\".<ref>Al Goldstein and Josh Alan Friedman, ''I, Goldstein. My Screwed Life''</ref>\n\n==Life in Florida==\nWhile mostly associated with the city of New York, Goldstein was also a well-known figure in [[Broward County, Florida]], making the cover of a local alternative tabloid, ''[[New Times Broward-Palm Beach|New Times]]''.<ref name=AntiHef /> He owned a 10,000-square-foot mansion in [[Pompano Beach, Florida|Pompano Beach]], famous for its statue, {{convert|11|ft|m}} high, of a raised [[the finger|middle finger]] on the back lawn, visible to boaters on the [[Intracoastal Waterway]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Screwed |magazine=[[New Times (magazine)|New Times]] |url=https://40.media.tumblr.com/c1466b07a7c0d05e08f7b1499a0bf652/tumblr_mzgstuarGq1qez03po1_r1_500.jpg |access-date=October 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>Chris Joseph, [http://blogs.browardpalmbeach.com/pulp/2013/12/al_goldstein_publisher_of_scre.php \"Al Goldstein, Publisher of ''Screw'' Magazine, Dies in New York at 77\"], ''Broward/Palm Beach New Times'', December 19, 2013; retrieved October 30, 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 1992, he filed to run for sheriff against [[Nick Navarro]], who had gained Goldstein's enmity by arresting on obscenity charges [[2 Live Crew]] members and a record dealer who sold their album ''[[As Nasty As They Wanna Be]]''. (The accused were convicted, but won on appeal.) Goldstein withdrew before the election took place. In 2001 he spoke publicly of his intent to run a second time, against [[Ken Jenne]], on a platform of \"leaving folks the hell alone\". He never filed, saying that he could not afford the campaign.<ref name=\"Bob Whitby 2001\"/>\n\n==Last years==\n\n===Legal issues and financial woes===\nIn 2002, Goldstein was found guilty of harassing a former employee, having published her telephone number and place of employment in ''Screw'' and encouraging readers to call her and tell her \"to stop being such a cunt.\" Goldstein was sentenced to 60 days in jail. He served six days  before the charges were overturned on appeal. Goldstein apologized as part of a plea bargain.<ref>Albin, Stacy (October 23, 2003). [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/10/23/nyregion/metro-briefing-new-york-brooklyn-pornographer-in-plea-deal.html \"Pornographer In Plea Deal\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref><ref>Christian, Nichole M. (February 28, 2002). [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/28/nyregion/pornographer-guilty-in-harassment-case.html \"Pornographer Guilty in Harassment Case\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref>Newman, Andy. [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/18/nyregion/6-days-in-jail-broke-him-freed-pornographer-says.html \"6 Days in Jail Broke Him, Freed Pornographer Says\"], ''The New York Times'', May 18, 2002.</ref> ''Screw'' folded in 2003, unable to make payroll;<ref>Nathan Thornburgh, [http://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/encounter/70052 \"82 Minutes with Al Goldstein\"], ''New York'' [magazine], December 10, 2010; retrieved November 20, 2014.</ref> only 600 copies were sold of the last issue.<ref name=AntiHef/>\n\nGoldstein's company, Milky Way Productions, which published ''Screw'' and ''Midnight Blue'', entered bankruptcy in 2004, having lost sales and subscribers as a result of the proliferation of internet pornography, abetted by Goldstein's financial mismanagement.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newman|first=Andy|title=68 and Sleeping on Floor, Ex-Publisher Seeks Work|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/12/nyregion/68-and-sleeping-on-floor-ex-publisher-seeks-work.html|accessdate=2013-12-23|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2004-08-12}}; Al Goldstein and Josh Alan Friedman, ''I, Goldstein. My Screwed Life''</ref>\n\nGoldstein lost his Florida mansion and his townhouse on [[Manhattan]]'s [[Upper East Side]]. Jobless and penniless, he ended up living briefly in a Manhattan [[homeless shelter]]. He was fired from New York's well-known [[Second Avenue Deli]] for sleeping in the basement, after a brief stint there as a greeter.<ref name=\"Dirty\"/><ref>Mary Reinholz, [http://thevillager.com/villager_72/expornkingtradessex.html \"Ex-porn king trades sex for salami at 2nd Ave. Deli\"], ''The Villager'', September 15\u201321, 2004; retrieved November 21, 2014.</ref>\n\nHe was arrested for shoplifting four health-related books from [[Barnes & Noble]].<ref>\"The Ludicrous 12 of 2004\", [http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2004-12-30/news/the-ludicrous-12-of-2004 \"The Ludicrous 12 of 2004\"], ''Broward/Palm Beach New Times'', December 20, 2004; retrieved 10-30-2014.</ref> He worked in 2005 as a commissioned salesman for New York City Bagels.<ref>John Zawadzinski. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A33955-2005Jan24.html \"From Smut to Schmears: Al Goldstein's New Venture\"], ''Washington Post'', January 25, 2005, p. C09; retrieved January 20, 2005.</ref> Between 2005\u201308, he blogged for booble.com, a pornographic search engine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://algoldstein.booble.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516005332/http://algoldstein.booble.com/ |archivedate=May 16, 2008 |title=Blog of Screw Magazine Founder Al Goldstein |date=2008-05-16 |accessdate=2016-10-08 |url-status = dead}}</ref> he then continued on his own website until 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.algoldstein.com/2009/06 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731053106/http://www.algoldstein.com/2009/06 |archivedate=July 31, 2009 |title=Booble Presents: Al Goldstein's G Spot \u00bb 2009 \u00bb June |date=2009-07-31 |accessdate=2016-10-08 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nHe was financially supported in his last years by his friend the [[illusionist]] [[Penn Jillette]], on whose floor he once slept, and who admired Goldstein for his [[First Amendment]] activism.<ref name=AntiHef/> His final residence, prior to a nursing home, was a small apartment in the [[Far Rockaway]] neighborhood of [[Queens]], paid for by Jillette.<ref>Ashley West, [http://www.therialtoreport.com/2014/01/05/remembering-al-goldstein-a-happy-jew \"Remembering Al Goldstein: A Happy Jew\"], ''The Rialto Report'', January 5, 2014; retrieved 10-30-2014.</ref>\n\n===Death===\nGoldstein died on December 19, 2013, aged 77, from renal failure at a nursing home in [[Cobble Hill, Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"nytobit\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===Documentary===\nIn 2003, Lancaster Pictures produced a documentary on Goldstein entitled ''Goldstein: The Trials of the Sultan of Smut''. It focused on his legal troubles. [[Larry Flynt]], [[Ron Jeremy]], and [[Jimmy Breslin]] appeared in the movie.<ref>Dennis Harvey, [https://variety.com/2004/film/reviews/goldstein-the-trials-of-the-sultan-of-smut-1200533105 Review: ''Goldstein: The Trials of the Sultan of Smut''], ''Variety'', May 27, 2004; retrieved January 20, 2005.</ref> He claimed to have had 7,000 sexual partners.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Thornburgh|first=Nathan|date=December 10, 2010|title=82 Minutes with Al Goldstein|url=http://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/encounter/70052|journal=New York Magazine|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref> Another writer called him \"a hairy, sweaty, cigar-chomping, eczema-ridden fatso\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.com/2011/02/al-goldstein-the-pornographer-in-winter|title=Al Goldstein: The Pornographer in Winter|last=Anolik|first=Lili|date=February 23, 2011|newspaper=New York Observer|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Retrospective===\nIn his 2011 book ''Dirty! Dirty! Dirty! \u2013 of Playboys, Pigs, and Penthouse Paupers, an American Tale of Sex and Wonder'', former ''Screw'' writer and editor [[Mike Edison]] documents Goldstein's rise and fall against the successes of his peers [[Larry Flynt]] of ''[[Hustler]]'', [[Bob Guccione]] of ''[[Penthouse (magazine)|Penthouse]]'', and [[Hugh Hefner]] of ''[[Playboy]]''. Edison also lauds Goldstein as a staunch fighter for the First Amendment, quoting [[Gay Talese]], who referred to Goldstein in his book ''[[Thy Neighbor's Wife (book)|Thy Neighbor's Wife]]'', saying, \"We need a free society, and freedom is not won by literary tea parties and well-meaning, virtuous publishers, it is won by disreputable people like Al Goldstein.\" Edison also quotes the New York reporter [[Jimmy Breslin]] as saying, \"Al Goldstein is one of four people in the last 35 years who has effectively protected the First Amendment rights of reporters who bring the news to you. The others are [[Ralph Ginzburg]], [[Larry Flynt]], and [[Lenny Bruce]]. I know you don\u2019t want to meet them, but you owe them.\u201d<ref name=\"Dirty\" />\n\n==Filmography==\nUnless otherwise noted, Goldstein appeared as himself in the following movies:\n* ''Dynamite Chicken'' (1971)\n* ''It Happened in Hollywood'' (1973)\n* ''Let My Puppets Come'' (1976)\n* ''[[Denial (1998 film)|Denial]]'' (1998)\n* ''Wadd: The Life and Times of [[John Holmes (pornographic actor)|John C. Holmes]]'' (1998)\n* ''Sex: The [[Annabel Chong]] Story'' (1999)\n* ''[[Citizen Toxie: The Toxic Avenger IV]]'' (2001)\n* ''Porn Star: The Legend of [[Ron Jeremy]]'' (2001)\n* ''Al Goldstein and Ron Jeremy are Screwed'' (2003) (X-rated)\n* ''[[Inside Deep Throat]]'' (2005)\n* ''Obscene'' (2007)\n* ''[[American Swing]]'' (2008)\n* ''Filthy Gorgeous: The [[Bob Guccione]] Story'' (2013)\n* ''Back Issues: The Hustler Magazine Story'' (2014)\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last1=Goldstein |first1=Al |last2=Friedman |first2=Josh Alan |author-link2=Josh Alan Friedman |title=I, Goldstein: My Screwed Life |year=2006 |location=New York |publisher=[[Thunder's Mouth Press]] |isbn=978-1560258681 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/igoldsteinmyscre00gold }}\n* {{cite book |editor-first1=Al |editor-last1=Goldstein |editor-first2=Jim |editor-last2=Buckley |title=The Screw Reader |year=1971 |location=New York |publisher=Lyle Stuart |asin=B0010C5MBE}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Al Goldstein}}\n* {{IMDb name|0326155}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050604022712/http://www.rotten.com/library/bio/pornographers/al-goldstein/ Rotten Timeline]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050131094736/http://www.thevillager.com/villager_72/expornkingtradessex.html The Villager] (September 15\u201321, 2004)\n* [http://www.therialtoreport.com/2014/02/23/al-goldstein-screw-midnight-blue-and-fuck-you-podcast-31/ 118-minute discussion of Goldstein by [[Steven Heller (design writer)|Steven Heller]] (''Screw'' collaborator), Goldstein's biographer [[Josh Alan Friedman]], and Goldstein's attorney Herald Price Fahringer]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldstein, Al}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Adult magazine publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American magazine founders]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Pompano Beach, Florida]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:American public access television personalities]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Free speech activists]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in literature]]\n[[Category:Pace University alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:American taxicab drivers]]\n[[Category:Homeless people]]\n[[Category:People from Williamsburg, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:American photojournalists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from kidney failure]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Boys High School (Brooklyn) alumni]]\n[[Category:People convicted of obscenity]]\n[[Category:People from Far Rockaway, Queens]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper East Side]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the American pornographer|the American football player|Al Goldstein (American football)}}\n{{short description|American pornographer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Al Goldstein\n| image       = Al Goldstein.jpg\n| birthname   = Alvin Goldstein\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date |1936|1|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2013|12|19|1936|1|10}}\n| death_place = [[Cobble Hill, Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.\n| spouse      = {{Unbulleted list|{{marriage|Lonnie Leavitt|1963|1965|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Mary Phillips|1968|1977|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Gena Goldstein|1978|1991|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Patricia Flaherty|1994|1999|end=divorced}}|{{marriage|Christina Ava Maharaj|2004|2006|end=divorced}}}}\n| children    = Jordan Goldstein\n| occupation  = [[Publisher]]\n}}\n\n'''Alvin''' \"'''Al'''\" '''Goldstein''' (January 10, 1936 \u2013 December 19, 2013) was an American [[Pornography|pornographer]]. He is known for normalizing hardcore pornography in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"nytobit\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/people-algoldstein/al-goldstein-pornography-pioneer-who-claimed-free-speech-dies-idUSL2N0JY17Q20131219|title=Al Goldstein, pornography pioneer who claimed free speech, dies|last=Cavaliere|first=Victoria|date=December 19, 2013|website=[[Reuters]]|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/dec/19/screw-magazine-publisher-al-goldstein-dies-aged-77|title=Screw magazine publisher Al Goldstein dies aged 77|last=|first=|date=December 19, 2013|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was described in his [[obituary]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"a cartoonishly vituperative amalgam of [[Borscht Belt]] comic, free-range social critic and sex-obsessed loser who seemed to embody a moment in New York City's cultural history: the sleaze and decay of [[Times Square]] in the 1960s and \u201870s.\"<ref name=\"nytobit\">{{cite news |title=Al Goldstein, a Publisher Who Took the Romance Out of Sex, Dies at 77 |first=Andy |last=Newman |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=A1 |date=December 19, 2013| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/20/nyregion/al-goldstein-pioneering-pornographer-dies-at-77.html}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nGoldstein was born in [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn]] to a [[Jewish]] family. He attended [[Boys High School (Brooklyn)|Boys High]]. He served in the Army as a photographer (in the [[Signal Corps (United States Army)|Signal Corps]]), captained the debate team at [[Pace College]] (for whose newspaper he interviewed [[Allen Ginsberg]]), and was a photojournalist, taking pictures of [[Jacqueline Kennedy]] on a 1962 state trip to [[Pakistan]] and spending several days in a Cuban jail for taking unauthorized photos of [[Fidel Castro]]'s brother, [[Ra\u00fal Castro|Ra\u00fal]].<ref name=AntiHef>{{cite web|first=Will|last=Sloan|title=Al Goldstein: The Anti-Hef|url=http://penguinrandomhouse.ca/hazlitt/longreads/al-goldstein-anti-hef|date=December 20, 2013|accessdate=November 20, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030211908/http://penguinrandomhouse.ca/hazlitt/longreads/al-goldstein-anti-hef|archive-date=October 30, 2014|url-status = dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe sold insurance; wrote freelance articles; ran a dime-pitch concession at the [[1964 New York World's Fair|1964-65 New York World's Fair]]; sold rugs, encyclopedias, and his own blood; drove a cab (he kept his hack [cab driver's] license active until his death); and landed a job as an industrial spy infiltrating a labor union, an experience that so appalled him he wrote an expos\u00e9 about it for the ''[[New York Free Press]]'', a radical weekly.<ref name=\"nytobit\"/><ref name=NYTDirty>{{cite news|first=Steven|last=Haller|title=My Dirty Life and Times\" (review of ''I, Goldstein. My Screwed Life'')|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 19, 2006|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D02E6DF1F3FF93AA25752C1A9609C8B63&pagewanted=2|accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Print publications==\n\n===''Screw''===\nIn November 1968 in New York, Al and his partner Jim Buckley, investing $175 each, founded ''[[Screw (magazine)|Screw]]'', a weekly tabloid. It featured reviews of [[Pornographic film|porn movies]], [[peep show]]s, erotic [[massage parlors]], [[brothel]]s, [[Call girl|escorts]] and other offerings of the [[adult entertainment]] industry. Such items were interspersed with sexual news, book reviews of sexual books, and hardcore \"gynecological\" pictorials. He regularly ran, without permission, photos and drawings of celebrities.\n\n\"''Screw'' grew from a combination of many factors, chief of which was my own dissatisfaction with the sex literature of 1968 and my yearning for a publication that reflected my sexual appetites,\" he wrote. \"I may be making a lot of money, but I really believe I'm doing some good by demythologizing a lot about sexuality\", he said in a [[Playboy Interview]]. It was described as \"raunchy, obnoxious, usually disgusting and sometimes political.\"<ref name=Jewniverse>{{cite web|first=Marc|last=Davis|title=The Screw-y, Filthy World of Al Goldstein|work=Jewniverse|date=November 18, 2013|url=http://thejewniverse.com/2013/the-screw-y-filthy-world-of-al-goldstein|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref> The initial price was 25\u00a2. At its peak, ''Screw'' sold 140,000 copies a week.<ref name=Rialto>{{cite web|first=Ashley|last=West|title=Remembering Al Goldstein: A Happy Jew|work=The Rialto Report|date=January 4, 2014| url=http://www.therialtoreport.com/2014/01/05/remembering-al-goldstein-a-happy-jew|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=BrowardScrewed>{{cite news|first=Bob|last=Whitby|title=Screwed|newspaper=Broward/Palm Beach New Times|date=February 22, 2001|url=http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2001-02-22/news/screwed|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nArrested 19 times on obscenity charges, he spent millions on [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] lawsuits, ultimately scoring a major victory when a federal judge dismissed an obscenity case in 1974. (Goldstein believed that the case began as a result of ''Screw''{{'}}s article, \"Is [[Sexuality of J. Edgar Hoover|J. Edgar Hoover]] a Fag?\",<ref name=Jewniverse/><ref>{{cite magazine |number=11 |date=May 2, 1969 |url=http://www.specificobject.com/objects/info.cfm?object_id=12758#.VL16PkfF9S0 |magazine=[[Screw (magazine)|Screw]] |title=Is J. Edgar Hoover a Fag?}}</ref> the first published comment on Hoover's sexuality.<ref name=\"Dirty\">{{cite book|last=Edison|first=Mike|title=Dirty! Dirty! Dirty!: Of \u2014Playboys, Pigs, and Penthouse Paupers \u2014An American Tale of Sex and Wonder|publisher=Soft Skull Press|year=2011|isbn=978-1-5937-6284-1|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dirtydirtydirtyo0000edis}}</ref>) [[Forum shopping|Venue-shopping]] prosecutors selected conservative [[Wichita, Kansas]], to prosecute Goldstein for [[obscenity]];<ref>{{cite news|first=John|last=Marshall|title=Postal Officials Admit False-Name Subscriptions|newspaper=Garden City [Kansas] Telegram|date=May 28, 1976|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/468445|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> when he was found not guilty, he flew the jury to New York to attend a party at the swing club [[Plato's Retreat]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2199&dat=19800504&id=_pYyAAAAIBAJ&pg=4013,531430| title=Goldstein says 2nd thank you|newspaper=Lawrence Journal-World|date=May 4, 1980|accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref> His long-term attorney was Herald Price Fahringer.<ref name=NYTDirty/><ref>{{cite web|title=Al Goldstein: Screw, Midnight Blue, and Fuck You Podcast 31|work=The Rialto Report|date=February 23, 2014|url=http://www.therialtoreport.com/2014/02/23/al-goldstein-screw-midnight-blue-and-fuck-you-podcast-31|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Will Sloan, \"Goldstein was the first journalist to seriously review porn films. Had he not written a rave review of a low-budget film called ''Deep Throat'' (\u201cI was never so moved by any theatrical performance since stuttering through my own bar mitzvah\u201d), it would never have become a hit at New York's World Theater, would never have been targeted by the vice squad, would never have spawned a First Amendment cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre, and might not have led to the modern porn industry.\"<ref name=AntiHef/>\n\n===''Bitch'' magazine===\nIn the March 11, 1974, issue of ''Screw'' Goldstein ran an ad seeking subscribers to a new magazine, ''Bitch'', which \"brings women's sexuality out of the closet for the first time\" and also \"takes women out of politics and puts them back on their back where they belong.\" (Note: there have been several other magazines also called ''Bitch''.)<ref>{{cite web|publisher=WorldCat.org|title=Journals + Publications entitled \"Bitch\"|url=http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=ti%3ABitch&fq=x0%3Ajrnl&qt=advanced&dblist=638|accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref> The first issue \"contain[ed] an explosive symposium about blowjobs by four women who talk about giving head and what they like and don't like about it\". It also included an interview with actor [[James Caan]], and a centerfold of a man shot by a female photographer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://40.media.tumblr.com/51cdb2a332ae633aa4b7b48b54668c8e/tumblr_n5diz1VSXK1sbtct0o1_500.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image : Bitch Bites Back! |date=March 11, 1974 |website=40.media.tumblr.com |accessdate=2016-10-16}}</ref>\n\n===''Smut'' Magazine===\nIn the same March 11, 1974, issue of ''Screw'' Goldstein also ran an ad seeking subscribers to ''Smut'', a magazine \"so filthy that not only do you have to wash after every page, but every reader must disinfect after reading! SMUT is so dirty, so scummy, that once you have it on your hands you can't get it off!\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/image/89331982458 |title=Subscribe to Smut Today |website=[[Tumblr]] |access-date=November 20, 2014}}</ref> The magazine offered pornography in images and words, without the news articles found in ''Screw''.\n\n===''National Screw''===\nIn 1976-1977 ''National Screw'' was published; the place of publication was given as [[Secaucus, New Jersey]]. The June 1977 issue of the magazine contained, according to its cover, a new story by [[William Burroughs]] and an interview with [[Allen Ginsberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageadultmagazinecovers.tumblr.com/post/85141297591 |title=Vintage Adult Magazine Covers |publisher=Vintageadultmagazinecovers.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> It is known to have published five issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cornell.worldcat.org/oclc/55740108|work=Cornell University|title=Library Catalog \u2013 National Screw|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===''Death'' magazine===\nIn 1979, Goldstein began ''Death'' magazine. It lasted four issues.<ref>A cover is reproduced at {{cite web|url=http://nonpopocculture.tumblr.com/image/98793218925 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-30 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109125620/http://nonpopocculture.tumblr.com/image/98793218925 |archivedate=November 9, 2014 }}</ref> The February, 1980 issue had a picture of [[Elvis Presley]] on the cover, \"Grim Reaper Awards\", \"Eulogy to a War Lover\", \"Death by Hanging\", \"Femme Fatales\", and other articles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/image/99335715723 |title=Screw Magazine : Photo |publisher=Screwmag.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n===''Screw West''===\nIn 1979-1980 Goldstein's company, Milky Way Productions, published ''Screw West'' out of an office in [[Hollywood, California]]. According to an advertisement, it was intended to answer such questions as, \"Where can I get laid in San Francisco? What's the best swinger's club in Los Angeles? How do I find all those out-of-the-way Pacific Coast nude beaches? And what are those bawdy brothels outside Las Vegas really like?\" It is known to have published 54 issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://suncat.csun.edu/record=b2477029| work=California State University |title=Library Catalog \u2013 Screw West|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Movies and television==\n{{More citations needed section|date=October 2016}}\n\n===''It Happened in Hollywood''===\nIn 1973, \"Screw Magazine present[ed]\" ''It Happened in Hollywood'', a pornographic movie, produced by Goldstein's partner Jim Buckley. Goldstein played a character in the movie, and is also credited as \"fourth unit director.\" At the 2nd Annual [[New York Erotic Film Festival]] it won awards for Best Picture, Best Female Performance, and Best Supporting Actor.<ref>\"Screw Film Sweeps Awards\", ''Screw'', March 26, 1973.</ref>\n\n===''Midnight Blue''===\nIn 1974 Goldstein began ''Screw Magazine of the Air'', soon renamed ''[[Midnight Blue (TV series)|Midnight Blue]]'', a thrice weekly hour-long adult-oriented public access television program that ran for nearly 30 years on [[Manhattan Cable Television|Manhattan Cable]]'s Channel J; federal regulations regarding public access to cable TV systems made it impossible for the cable system to refuse his program.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/03/05/arts/channel-j-pornography-is-cause-of-lockout-law.html|newspaper=The New York Times| title=Channel J Pornography is Cause of Lockout Law|first=Sally|last=Bedell Smith|date=March 5, 1984|accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Screw magazine publisher Al Goldstein dies aged 77|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/dec/19/screw-magazine-publisher-al-goldstein-dies-aged-77|accessdate=2013-12-28|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2013-12-19}}</ref> (Similarly, Goldstein used a legal prohibition on the censorship of political advertisements to force television broadcast of pornography, under a transparent, but legal, veil of \"political candidacy\".) In it, he regularly interviewed porn stars, other adult industry figures, and sympathetic celebrities and \"freaks\", and ran advertisements for brothels and phone sex services.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nIn the later years, after departure of original director Alex Bennett, Goldstein featured on each program a \"Fuck You\" segment, a few minutes in which he viciously attacked celebrities, politicians, the judge who presided over his latest trial, the [[New York County]] District Attorney, and businesses he felt had wronged him.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\nIn its early years, ''Midnight Blue'' presented porn star [[Georgina Spelvin]] doing her nude tap-dance act at the Melody Burlesque; Tara Alexander attempting the world's biggest [[gang bang]] at [[Plato's Retreat]], the New York swing club; the 10th anniversary ''Screw'' party, where Buck Henry and Melvin Van Peebles hobnob with Goldstein's jurors; and an early look at the S&M community in New York. Throughout its run, Midnight Blue interviewed almost every major porn star, and regularly hit the limits of what was acceptable for cable television.\"<ref name=AntiHef/> Seven volumes of excerpts from the show have been reissued on DVD.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=sr_nr_n_12?rh=n%3A2625373011%2Cp_n_format_browse-bin%3A2650304011%2Ck%3A%22midnight+blue%22&keywords=%22midnight+blue%22&ie=UTF8&qid=1408017915&rnid=2941120011 |title=\"midnight blue\" \u2013 DVD: Movies & TV |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n===SOS: Screw on the Screen===\nIn 1975, Goldstein issued ''SOS: Screw on the Screen'', a stridently unsexy attempt at a cinematic newsmagazine that included a lot of goofy comedy, a gay scene, and several minutes of Goldstein ranting about America's sexual hypocrisy. Also appearing was [[Honeysuckle Divine]] (who often appeared in ''SCREW'').<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://36.media.tumblr.com/95598a5d4bba63bc4aa7ace5b6fe37a1/tumblr_n8et7yfxSe1sbtct0o1_1280.jpg |title=Diary of a Dirty Broad |publisher=Screw |date=1974-03-11 |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> A poster of her was on sale in the same issue. [[Honeysuckle Divine]] was a Times Square stripper whose specialty was inserting objects such as pickles in her vagina, shooting out many of them. She put the pickles in baggies and sold them to patrons. Goldstein said that her act \"was unbelievably disgusting, so naturally, we made her our symbol.\"<ref name=AntiHef/>\n\n==Other business ventures==\n\n===The Screw Store===\nIn the May 17, 1976, issue of ''Screw'' Goldstein ran an ad for the \"Screw Store\", which offered dildos, including a \"Bicentennial Dildo\", vibrating [[Ben wa]] eggs, and a vibrating [[cock ring]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/post/83282516250/may-17-1976 |title=Screw Magazine |publisher=Screwmag.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> Selling dildos brought one of Goldstein's many arrests.<ref name=AntiHef/><ref>Josh Alan Friedman, [http://mmuseumm.com/exhibitions/al-goldsteins-personal-ephemera \"Al Goldstein's Personal Ephemera\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210050717/http://mmuseumm.com/exhibitions/al-goldsteins-personal-ephemera |date=December 10, 2014 }}; accessed November 20, 2014.</ref>\n\n===Al Goldstein's Cinema===\nThe October 17, 1977, issue of ''Screw'' contained an advertisement for \"Al Goldstein's Cinema\", located at 8th Avenue and 46th Street near [[Times Square]]. Admission was 99\u00a2.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/post/68563086292/october-17-1977 |title=Screw Magazine |publisher=Screwmag.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> In the same issue, in the movie listings, it is described as \"a large, comfortable porn house which shows average hardcore features. Some of these are first-run features, some have already played theaters in the city.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/post/71220104271/reviews-of-porn-theaters-october-17-1977 |title=Screw Magazine |publisher=Screwmag.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref> The theater is not found in a listing of porn theaters from 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screwmag.tumblr.com/image/96709693643 |title=Screw Magazine : Photo |publisher=Screwmag.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n===Rabbit Ranch===\nIn 2001, on [[Saint Martin]], an island in the [[Lesser Antilles]], Goldstein planned to open the Rabbit Ranch, the first of what he hoped would be a chain of 10 to 30 bordellos that would flourish wherever prostitution is legal.<ref name=BrowardScrewed /> He intended to use the profits to finance his second run for sheriff. The brothel never opened; authorities refused to give him a license because he was not a citizen of that nation. \"We didn't bribe the right people or something,\" he said.<ref name=\"Bob Whitby 2001\">Bob Whitby, [http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2001-05-03/news/undercurrents/2 \"Undercurrents\"], ''Broward/Palm Beach New Times'', May 3, 2001; retrieved October 30, 2014.</ref>\n\n== Political and religious views ==\n\n=== Free speech ===\nIn 1989, Goldstein ran a full page ad in ''Screw'' offering $1 million for the assassination of the [[Ayatollah Khomeini]], in response to Khomeini's [[fatwa]] against novelist [[Salman Rushdie]] for allegedly [[Blasphemy|blaspheming]] [[Islam]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1291&dat=19890414&id=WFBYAAAAIBAJ&pg=4665,5019656|title=Threat begets threats|date=1989-04-14|newspaper=Boca Raton News|accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref>\n\n===View on Christianity===\nIn his book ''XXX-Communicated: A Rebel Without a Shul'', [[Luke Ford (blogger)|Luke Ford]] wrote about a conversation with Goldstein, in which Ford asked Goldstein why Jews were dramatically overrepresented in the porn industry. He answered, \"The only reason that Jews are in pornography is that we think that Christ sucks. Catholicism sucks. We don't believe in authoritarianism.\" Ford then asked, \"What does it mean to you to be a Jew?\" To which Goldstein responded, \"It doesn't mean anything. It means that I'm called a [[kike]].\"  Ford also asked, \"Do you believe in God?\" Goldstein said, \"I believe in me. I'm God.  Screw God. God is your need to believe in some super being. I am the super being. I am your God, admit it. We're random. We're the flea on the butt of the dog.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=rMzW_FLdJGwC&pg=PA69&lpg=PA69&dq=al+goldstein+luke+ford#v=onepage&q=al%20goldstein%20luke%20ford&f=false|title=XXX-Communicated: A Rebel Without a Shul|accessdate=2016-10-08|isbn=9780595318940|last1=Ford|first1=Luke|year=2004}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Friendship with Larry Flynt===\nOne of Goldstein's best friends was [[Larry Flynt]]. Goldstein said that Flynt's ''[[Hustler]]'' magazine, founded seven years after ''Screw'', stole the ''Hustler'' format from ''Screw'', but that he was not angry. According to Goldstein, Flynt succeeded in creating a national publication, at which he had failed.<ref>{{YouTube|id=GdBWpHZkPPo|title=\"Goldstein on Flynt, Flynt on Goldstein\"}}</ref>\n\n===Family===\nGoldstein married five times and had a son, Jordan Ari Goldstein, with his third wife, Gina. According to Goldstein, he and Jordan had a close relationship until the Goldsteins' divorce. They became estranged after Al called Gina \"a contemptible vagina\".<ref>Al Goldstein and Josh Alan Friedman, ''I, Goldstein. My Screwed Life''</ref>\n\n==Life in Florida==\nWhile mostly associated with the city of New York, Goldstein was also a well-known figure in [[Broward County, Florida]], making the cover of a local alternative tabloid, ''[[New Times Broward-Palm Beach|New Times]]''.<ref name=AntiHef /> He owned a 10,000-square-foot mansion in [[Pompano Beach, Florida|Pompano Beach]], famous for its statue, {{convert|11|ft|m}} high, of a raised [[the finger|middle finger]] on the back lawn, visible to boaters on the [[Intracoastal Waterway]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Screwed |magazine=[[New Times (magazine)|New Times]] |url=https://40.media.tumblr.com/c1466b07a7c0d05e08f7b1499a0bf652/tumblr_mzgstuarGq1qez03po1_r1_500.jpg |access-date=October 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>Chris Joseph, [http://blogs.browardpalmbeach.com/pulp/2013/12/al_goldstein_publisher_of_scre.php \"Al Goldstein, Publisher of ''Screw'' Magazine, Dies in New York at 77\"], ''Broward/Palm Beach New Times'', December 19, 2013; retrieved October 30, 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 1992, he filed to run for sheriff against [[Nick Navarro]], who had gained Goldstein's enmity by arresting on obscenity charges [[2 Live Crew]] members and a record dealer who sold their album ''[[As Nasty As They Wanna Be]]''. (The accused were convicted, but won on appeal.) Goldstein withdrew before the election took place. In 2001 he spoke publicly of his intent to run a second time, against [[Ken Jenne]], on a platform of \"leaving folks the hell alone\". He never filed, saying that he could not afford the campaign.<ref name=\"Bob Whitby 2001\"/>\n\n==Last years==\n\n===Legal issues and financial woes===\nIn 2002, Goldstein was found guilty of harassing a former employee, having published her telephone number and place of employment in ''Screw'' and encouraging readers to call her and tell her \"to stop being such a cunt.\" Goldstein was sentenced to 60 days in jail. He served six days  before the charges were overturned on appeal. Goldstein apologized as part of a plea bargain.<ref>Albin, Stacy (October 23, 2003). [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/10/23/nyregion/metro-briefing-new-york-brooklyn-pornographer-in-plea-deal.html \"Pornographer In Plea Deal\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref><ref>Christian, Nichole M. (February 28, 2002). [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/28/nyregion/pornographer-guilty-in-harassment-case.html \"Pornographer Guilty in Harassment Case\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref>Newman, Andy. [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/18/nyregion/6-days-in-jail-broke-him-freed-pornographer-says.html \"6 Days in Jail Broke Him, Freed Pornographer Says\"], ''The New York Times'', May 18, 2002.</ref> ''Screw'' folded in 2003, unable to make payroll;<ref>Nathan Thornburgh, [http://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/encounter/70052 \"82 Minutes with Al Goldstein\"], ''New York'' [magazine], December 10, 2010; retrieved November 20, 2014.</ref> only 600 copies were sold of the last issue.<ref name=AntiHef/>\n\nGoldstein's company, Milky Way Productions, which published ''Screw'' and ''Midnight Blue'', entered bankruptcy in 2004, having lost sales and subscribers as a result of the proliferation of internet pornography, abetted by Goldstein's financial mismanagement.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newman|first=Andy|title=68 and Sleeping on Floor, Ex-Publisher Seeks Work|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/12/nyregion/68-and-sleeping-on-floor-ex-publisher-seeks-work.html|accessdate=2013-12-23|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2004-08-12}}; Al Goldstein and Josh Alan Friedman, ''I, Goldstein. My Screwed Life''</ref>\n\nGoldstein lost his Florida mansion and his townhouse on [[Manhattan]]'s [[Upper East Side]]. Jobless and penniless, he ended up living briefly in a Manhattan [[homeless shelter]]. He was fired from New York's well-known [[Second Avenue Deli]] for sleeping in the basement, after a brief stint there as a greeter.<ref name=\"Dirty\"/><ref>Mary Reinholz, [http://thevillager.com/villager_72/expornkingtradessex.html \"Ex-porn king trades sex for salami at 2nd Ave. Deli\"], ''The Villager'', September 15\u201321, 2004; retrieved November 21, 2014.</ref>\n\nHe was arrested for shoplifting four health-related books from [[Barnes & Noble]].<ref>\"The Ludicrous 12 of 2004\", [http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/2004-12-30/news/the-ludicrous-12-of-2004 \"The Ludicrous 12 of 2004\"], ''Broward/Palm Beach New Times'', December 20, 2004; retrieved 10-30-2014.</ref> He worked in 2005 as a commissioned salesman for New York City Bagels.<ref>John Zawadzinski. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A33955-2005Jan24.html \"From Smut to Schmears: Al Goldstein's New Venture\"], ''Washington Post'', January 25, 2005, p. C09; retrieved January 20, 2005.</ref> Between 2005-08, he blogged for booble.com, a pornographic search engine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://algoldstein.booble.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516005332/http://algoldstein.booble.com/ |archivedate=May 16, 2008 |title=Blog of Screw Magazine Founder Al Goldstein |date=2008-05-16 |accessdate=2016-10-08 |url-status = dead}}</ref> he then continued on his own website until 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.algoldstein.com/2009/06 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731053106/http://www.algoldstein.com/2009/06 |archivedate=July 31, 2009 |title=Booble Presents: Al Goldstein's G Spot \u00bb 2009 \u00bb June |date=2009-07-31 |accessdate=2016-10-08 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nHe was financially supported in his last years by his friend the [[illusionist]] [[Penn Jillette]], on whose floor he once slept, and who admired Goldstein for his [[First Amendment]] activism.<ref name=AntiHef/> His final residence, prior to a nursing home, was a small apartment in the [[Far Rockaway]] neighborhood of [[Queens]], paid for by Jillette.<ref>Ashley West, [http://www.therialtoreport.com/2014/01/05/remembering-al-goldstein-a-happy-jew \"Remembering Al Goldstein: A Happy Jew\"], ''The Rialto Report'', January 5, 2014; retrieved 10-30-2014.</ref>\n\n===Death===\nGoldstein died on December 19, 2013, aged 77, from renal failure at a nursing home in [[Cobble Hill, Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"nytobit\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===Documentary===\nIn 2003, Lancaster Pictures produced a documentary on Goldstein entitled ''Goldstein: The Trials of the Sultan of Smut''. It focused on his legal troubles. [[Larry Flynt]], [[Ron Jeremy]], and [[Jimmy Breslin]] appeared in the movie.<ref>Dennis Harvey, [https://variety.com/2004/film/reviews/goldstein-the-trials-of-the-sultan-of-smut-1200533105 Review: ''Goldstein: The Trials of the Sultan of Smut''], ''Variety'', May 27, 2004; retrieved January 20, 2005.</ref> He claimed to have had 7,000 sexual partners.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Thornburgh|first=Nathan|date=December 10, 2010|title=82 Minutes with Al Goldstein|url=http://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/encounter/70052|journal=New York Magazine|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref> Another writer called him \"a hairy, sweaty, cigar-chomping, eczema-ridden fatso\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.com/2011/02/al-goldstein-the-pornographer-in-winter|title=Al Goldstein: The Pornographer in Winter|last=Anolik|first=Lili|date=February 23, 2011|newspaper=New York Observer|accessdate=November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Retrospective===\nIn his 2011 book ''Dirty! Dirty! Dirty! \u2013 of Playboys, Pigs, and Penthouse Paupers, an American Tale of Sex and Wonder'', former ''Screw'' writer and editor [[Mike Edison]] documents Goldstein's rise and fall against the successes of his peers [[Larry Flynt]] of ''[[Hustler]]'', [[Bob Guccione]] of ''[[Penthouse (magazine)|Penthouse]]'', and [[Hugh Hefner]] of ''[[Playboy]]''. Edison also lauds Goldstein as a staunch fighter for the First Amendment, quoting [[Gay Talese]], who referred to Goldstein in his book ''[[Thy Neighbor's Wife (book)|Thy Neighbor's Wife]]'', saying, \"We need a free society, and freedom is not won by literary tea parties and well-meaning, virtuous publishers, it is won by disreputable people like Al Goldstein.\" Edison also quotes the New York reporter [[Jimmy Breslin]] as saying, \"Al Goldstein is one of four people in the last 35 years who has effectively protected the First Amendment rights of reporters who bring the news to you. The others are [[Ralph Ginzburg]], [[Larry Flynt]], and [[Lenny Bruce]]. I know you don\u2019t want to meet them, but you owe them.\u201d<ref name=\"Dirty\" />\n\n==Filmography==\nUnless otherwise noted, Goldstein appeared as himself in the following movies:\n* ''Dynamite Chicken'' (1971)\n* ''It Happened in Hollywood'' (1973)\n* ''Let My Puppets Come'' (1976)\n* ''[[Denial (1998 film)|Denial]]'' (1998)\n* ''Wadd: The Life and Times of [[John Holmes (pornographic actor)|John C. Holmes]]'' (1998)\n* ''Sex: The [[Annabel Chong]] Story'' (1999)\n* ''[[Citizen Toxie: The Toxic Avenger IV]]'' (2001)\n* ''Porn Star: The Legend of [[Ron Jeremy]]'' (2001)\n* ''Al Goldstein and Ron Jeremy are Screwed'' (2003) (X-rated)\n* ''[[Inside Deep Throat]]'' (2005)\n* ''Obscene'' (2007)\n* ''[[American Swing]]'' (2008)\n* ''Filthy Gorgeous: The [[Bob Guccione]] Story'' (2013)\n* ''Back Issues: The Hustler Magazine Story'' (2014)\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last1=Goldstein |first1=Al |last2